{"title_page": "Percy Mansell Jones", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=January 2018}}\n\n'''Percy Mansell Jones''' (11 April 1889 - 24 January 1968) was a Welsh Professor of French.\n\nHe was born 11 April 1889 at [[Carmarthen]] to Arnaud Johnson Jones and his wife. He started his education at [[Queen Elizabeth High School, Carmarthen|Queen Elizabeth Grammar School]] in Carmarthen before going on to gain a first-class honours degree in French in 1908 at [[Aberystwyth University]]. He later went on to achieving a master's degree. After his time at Aberystwyth, he attended [[Balliol College, Oxford]], where he obtained a [[Bachelor of Letters|B.Litt]].\n\nHe became a lecturer at various universities, specialising in French literature and history <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://snaccooperative.org/ark:/99166/w6xx9qk7|title=Jones, P. Mansell (Percy Mansell), 1889-1968 @ SNAC|website=snaccooperative.org|access-date=2018-01-03}}</ref> and modern French poetry. He obtained the position of lecturer at Aberystwyth University, University College of South Wales, Cambridge University and Cardiff. He was appointed Professor of French at [[Bangor University]] in 1937 and went on to hold the position of the first Professor of Modern French Literature at the University of Manchester in 1951. In 1960, he was honoured with an Hon. [[Doctor of Letters|D.Litt]] degree from the University of Wales which was given to him soon after his retirement.\n\nP Mansell Jones specialised in modern French poetry which provided a natural sensitivity and understanding to various French poets. For example, he studied poets such as [[Emile Verhaeren]] and [[Charles Baudelaire|Baudelaire]]. This is highlighted in his book ''The Oxford Book of French Verse'', published in 1957. As well as a passion for French poetry, he wrote various essays highlighting his interest in understanding French thought and contemporary issues. These essays are:&nbsp;''French Introspectives''&nbsp;(1937), ''The Background of Modern French Poetry''&nbsp;(1951) and ''Tradition and Barbarism''&nbsp;(1930).\n\nHe died on 24 January 1968.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://biography.wales/article/s2-JONE-MAN-1889|title=The National Library of Wales :: Dictionary of Welsh Biography|website=yba.llgc.org.uk|access-date=2018-01-03}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Percy Mansell}}\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Carmarthen]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Aberystwyth University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Welsh writers]]\n[[Category:Welsh scholars and academics]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=January 2018}}\n\n'''Percy Mansell Jones''' (11 April 1889 - 24 January 1968) was a Welsh Professor of French.\n\nHe was born 11 April 1889 at [[Carmarthen]] to Arnaud Johnson Jones and his wife. He started his education at [[Queen Elizabeth High School, Carmarthen|Queen Elizabeth Grammar School]] in Carmarthen before going on to gain a first-class honours degree in French in 1908 at [[Aberystwyth University]]. He later went on to achieving a master's degree. After his time at Aberystwyth, he attended [[Balliol College, Oxford]], where he obtained a [[Bachelor of Letters|B.Litt]].\n\nHe became a lecturer at various universities, specialising in French literature and history <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://snaccooperative.org/ark:/99166/w6xx9qk7|title=Jones, P. Mansell (Percy Mansell), 1889-1968 @ SNAC|website=snaccooperative.org|access-date=2018-01-03}}</ref> and modern French poetry. He obtained the position of lecturer at Aberystwyth University, University College of South Wales, Cambridge University and Cardiff. He was appointed Professor of French at [[Bangor University]] in 1937 and went on to hold the position of the first Professor of Modern French Literature at the University of Manchester in 1951. In 1960, he was honoured with an Hon. [[Doctor of Letters|D.Litt]] degree from the University of Wales which was given to him soon after his retirement.\n\nPercy Jones specialised in modern French poetry which provided a natural sensitivity and understanding to various French poets. For example, he studied poets such as [[Emile Verhaeren]] and [[Charles Baudelaire|Baudelaire]]. This is highlighted in his book ''The Oxford Book of French Verse'', published in 1957. As well as a passion for French poetry, he wrote various essays highlighting his interest in understanding French thought and contemporary issues. These essays are:&nbsp;''French Introspectives''&nbsp;(1937), ''The Background of Modern French Poetry''&nbsp;(1951) and ''Tradition and Barbarism''&nbsp;(1930).\n\nHe died on 24 January 1968.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://biography.wales/article/s2-JONE-MAN-1889|title=The National Library of Wales :: Dictionary of Welsh Biography|website=yba.llgc.org.uk|access-date=2018-01-03}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Percy Mansell}}\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Carmarthen]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Aberystwyth University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Welsh writers]]\n[[Category:Welsh scholars and academics]]\n", "name_user": "PMHawley", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Mansell_Jones"}
{"title_page": "Volume of an n-ball", "text_new": "{{Short description|Generalizing the notion of 3-dimensional volume to regions of points in n-dimensional Euclidean space with distance to a center less than a constant}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Volume of an ''n''-ball}}\n{{hypersphere_volume_and_surface_area_graphs.svg|250px}}\nIn [[geometry]], a '''[[ball (mathematics)|ball]]''' is a region in space comprising all points within a fixed distance from a given point; that is, it is the region enclosed by a [[sphere]] or [[hypersphere]]. An {{math|''n''}}-ball is a ball in {{math|''n''}}-dimensional [[Euclidean space]]. The '''volume of a unit {{math|''n''}}-ball''' is an important expression that occurs in formulas throughout mathematics; it generalizes the notion of the volume enclosed by a sphere in 3-dimensional space.\n\n== Formulas ==\n\n=== The volume ===\nThe {{math|''n''}}-dimensional volume of a Euclidean ball of radius {{math|''R''}} in {{math|''n''}}-dimensional Euclidean space is:<ref>Equation 5.19.4, ''NIST Digital Library of Mathematical Functions.'' http://dlmf.nist.gov/5.19#E4, Release 1.0.6 of 2013-05-06.</ref>\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\frac{\\pi^\\frac{n}{2}}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2} + 1\\right)}R^n,</math>\nwhere {{math|\u0393}} is [[Leonhard Euler]]'s [[gamma function]].  The gamma function extends the [[factorial]] function to non-integer arguments.  It satisfies {{math|\u0393(''n'') {{=}} (''n'' \u2212 1)!}} if {{math|''n''}} is a positive integer and {{math|\u0393(''n'' + {{sfrac|1|2}}) {{=}} (''n'' \u2212 {{sfrac|1|2}}) \u00b7 (''n'' \u2212 {{sfrac|3|2}}) \u00b7 \u2026 \u00b7 {{sfrac|1|2}} \u00b7 \u03c0<sup>1/2</sup>}} if {{math|''n''}} is a non-negative integer.\n\n=== Alternative forms ===\nUsing explicit formulas for [[particular values of the gamma function]] at the integers and half integers gives formulas for the volume of a Euclidean ball that do not require an evaluation of the gamma function. These are:\n:<math>\\begin{align}V_{2k}(R) &= \\frac{\\pi^k}{k!}R^{2k}, \\\\\nV_{2k+1}(R) &= \\frac{2^{k+1}\\pi^k}{(2k+1)!!}R^{2k+1} = \\frac{2(k!)(4\\pi)^k}{(2k+1)!}R^{2k+1}.\\end{align}</math>\nIn the formula for odd-dimensional volumes, the [[double factorial]] {{math|(2''k'' + 1)!!}} is defined for odd integers {{math|2''k'' + 1}} as {{math|(2''k'' + 1)!! {{=}} 1 \u00b7 3 \u00b7 5 \u00b7 \u2026 \u00b7 (2''k'' \u2212 1) \u00b7 (2''k'' + 1)}}. \n\nInstead of expressing the volume {{math|''V''}} of the ball in terms of its radius {{math|''R''}}, the formula can be [[Inverse function|inverted]] to express the radius as a function of the volume:\n:<math>R_n(V) = \\frac{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2} + 1\\right)^\\frac{1}{n}}{\\sqrt{\\pi}}V^\\frac{1}{n}.</math>\nThis formula, too, can be separated into even- and odd-dimensional cases using factorials and double factorials in place of the gamma function:\n:<math>\\begin{align}R_{2k}(V) &= \\frac{(k!V)^\\frac{1}{2k}}{\\sqrt{\\pi}}, \\\\\nR_{2k+1}(V) &= \\left(\\frac{(2k+1)!!V}{2^{k+1}\\pi^k}\\right)^\\frac{1}{2k+1}.\\end{align}</math>\n\n=== Recursions ===\nThe volume satisfies several recursive formulas. These formulas can either be proved directly or proved as consequences of the general volume formula above. The simplest to state is a formula for the volume of an {{math|''n''}}-ball in terms of the volume of an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 2)}}-ball of the same radius:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\frac{2\\pi R^2}{n} V_{n-2}(R).</math>\n\nThere is also a formula for the volume of an {{math|''n''}}-ball in terms of the volume of an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-ball of the same radius:\n:<math>V_n(R) = R\\sqrt{\\pi}\\frac{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n+1}{2}\\right)}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2} + 1\\right)} V_{n-1}(R).</math>\nUsing explicit formulas for the gamma function again shows that the one-dimension recursion formula can also be written as:\n\n:<math>\\begin{align}\nV_{2k}(R) &= R\\pi \\frac{(2k - 1)!!}{2^k k!} V_{2k-1}(R) = R\\pi \\frac{(2k-1)(2k-3) \\cdots 5 \\cdot 3 \\cdot 1}{(2k)(2k - 2) \\cdots 6 \\cdot 4 \\cdot 2} V_{2k-1}(R), \\\\[10px]\nV_{2k+1}(R) &= 2R\\frac{2^k k!}{(2k+1)!!} V_{2k}(R) = 2R\\frac{(2k)(2k - 2) \\cdots 6 \\cdot 4 \\cdot 2}{(2k+1)(2k-1) \\cdots 5 \\cdot 3 \\cdot 1} V_{2k}(R).\n\\end{align}</math>\n\nThe radius of an {{math|''n''}}-ball of volume {{math|''V''}} may be expressed recursively in terms of the radius of an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-ball or an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 2)}}-ball.  These formulas may be derived from the explicit formula for {{math|''R''<sub>''n''</sub>(''V'')}} above.\n:<math>\\begin{align}\nR_n(V) &= \\frac{\\Gamma(\\frac{n}{2} + 1)^{1/n}}{\\Gamma(\\frac{n-1}{2} + 1)^{1/(n-1)}}V^{-1/(n(n-1))}R_{n-1}(V), \\\\\nR_n(V) &= \\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)^{1/n}\\left(V \\cdot \\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)\\right)^{-2/(n(n-2))}R_{n-2}(V).\n\\end{align}</math>\nUsing explicit formulas for the gamma function shows that the one-dimension recursion formula is equivalent to\n:<math>\\begin{align}\nR_{2k}(V)\n&= \\frac{(2^kk!)^{1/(2k)}}{(2k-1)!!^{1/(2k-1)}}\\left(\\frac{2}{\\pi}\\right)^{1/(4k-2)}V^{-1/(2k(2k-1))} R_{2k-1}(V) \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\big((2k)(2k - 2) \\cdots 6 \\cdot 4 \\cdot 2\\big)^{1/(2k)}}{\\big((2k - 1)(2k - 3) \\cdots 5 \\cdot 3 \\cdot 1\\big)^{1/(2k-1)}} \\left(\\frac{2}{\\pi}\\right)^{1/(4k-2)}V^{-1/(2k(2k-1))} R_{2k-1}(V), \\\\\nR_{2k+1}(V)\n&= \\frac{(2k+1)!!^{1/(2k+1)}}{(2^k k!)^{1/(2k)}} \\left(\\frac{\\pi}{2}\\right)^{1/(4k+2)} V^{-1/((2k+1)2k)} R_{2k}(V) \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\big((2k + 1)(2k - 1) \\cdots 5 \\cdot 3 \\cdot 1\\big)^{1/(2k+1)}}{\\big((2k)(2k - 2) \\cdots 6 \\cdot 4 \\cdot 2\\big)^{1/(2k)}} \\left(\\frac{\\pi}{2}\\right)^{1/(4k+2)} V^{-1/((2k+1)2k)} R_{2k}(V), \\\\\n\\end{align}</math>\nand that the two-dimension recursion formula is equivalent to\n:<math>\\begin{align}\nR_{2k}(V)\n&= k^{1/(2k)} (V \\cdot (k-1)!)^{-1/(2(k-1)k)} R_{2k-2}(V) \\\\\n&= k^{1/(2k)} (V \\cdot (k-1) \\cdot (k-2) \\cdots 3 \\cdot 2 \\cdot 1)^{-1/(2(k-1)k)} R_{2k-2}(V), \\\\\nR_{2k+1}(V)\n&= (2k + 1)^{1/(2k+1)} \\left(V \\cdot (2k - 1)!!\\sqrt{\\frac{\\pi}{2}}\\right)^{-2/(4k^2 - 1)} R_{2k-1}(V) \\\\\n&= (2k + 1)^{1/(2k+1)} \\left(V \\cdot (2k - 1)(2k - 3) \\cdots 5 \\cdot 3 \\cdot 1 \\sqrt{\\frac{\\pi}{2}}\\right)^{-2/(4k^2-1)} R_{2k-1}(V).\n\\end{align}</math>\n\n=== Low dimensions ===\nIn low dimensions, these volume and radius formulas simplify to the following.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Dimension !! Volume of a ball of radius {{math|''R''}} !! Radius of a ball of volume {{math|''V''}}\n|-\n| 0\n| <math>1</math>\n| (all 0-balls have volume 1)\n|-\n| 1\n| <math>2R</math>\n| <math>\\frac{V}{2}=0.5\\times V</math>\n|-\n| 2\n| <math>\\pi R^2 \\approx 3.142\\times R^2</math>\n| <math>\\frac{V^\\frac12}{\\sqrt{\\pi}}\\approx 0.564\\times V^{\\frac{1}{2}}</math>\n|-\n| 3\n| <math>\\frac{4\\pi}{3} R^3 \\approx 4.189\\times R^3</math> \t\n| <math>\\left(\\frac{3V}{4\\pi}\\right)^\\frac13\\approx 0.620\\times V^\\frac13</math>\n|-\n| 4\n| <math>\\frac{\\pi^2}{2} R^4 \\approx 4.935\\times R^4</math>\n| <math>\\frac{(2V)^\\frac14}{\\sqrt{\\pi}}\\approx 0.671\\times V^\\frac14</math>\n|-\n| 5\n| <math>\\frac{8\\pi^2}{15} R^5\\approx 5.264\\times R^5</math>\n| <math>\\left(\\frac{15V}{8\\pi^2}\\right)^\\frac15\\approx 0.717\\times V^\\frac15</math>\n|-\n| 6\n| <math>\\frac{\\pi^3}{6} R^6 \\approx 5.168 \\times R^6</math>\n| <math>\\frac{(6V)^\\frac16}{\\sqrt{\\pi}}\\approx 0.761\\times V^\\frac16</math>\n|-\n| 7\n| <math>\\frac{16\\pi^3}{105} R^7 \\approx 4.725\\times R^7</math>\n| <math>\\left(\\frac{105V}{16\\pi^3}\\right)^\\frac17\\approx 0.801\\times V^\\frac17</math>\n|-\n| 8\n| <math>\\frac{\\pi^4}{24} R^8 \\approx 4.059\\times R^8</math>\n| <math>\\frac{(24V)^\\frac18}{\\sqrt{\\pi}}\\approx 0.839\\times V^\\frac18</math>\n|-\n| 9\n| <math>\\frac{32\\pi^4}{945} R^9 \\approx 3.299\\times R^9</math>\n| <math>\\left(\\frac{945V}{32\\pi^4}\\right)^\\frac19\\approx 0.876\\times V^\\frac19</math>\n|-\n| 10\n| <math>\\frac{\\pi^5}{120} R^{10} \\approx 2.550\\times R^{10}</math>\n| <math>\\frac{(120V)^\\frac{1}{10}}{\\sqrt{\\pi}}\\approx 0.911\\times V^\\frac{1}{10}</math>\n|-\n| 11\n| <math>\\frac{64\\pi^5}{10395} R^{11} \\approx 1.884\\times R^{11}</math>\n| <math>\\left(\\frac{10395V}{64\\pi^5}\\right)^\\frac{1}{11}\\approx 0.944\\times V^\\frac{1}{11}</math>\n|-\n| 12\n| <math>\\frac{\\pi^6}{720} R^{12} \\approx 1.335\\times R^{12}</math>\n| <math>\\frac{(720V)^\\frac{1}{12}}{\\sqrt{\\pi}}\\approx 0.976\\times V^\\frac{1}{12}</math>\n|}\n\n=== High dimensions ===\nSuppose that {{math|''R''}} is fixed. Then the volume of an {{math|''n''}}-ball of radius {{math|''R''}} approaches zero as {{math|''n''}} tends to infinity. This can be shown using the two-dimension recursion formula. At each step, the new factor being multiplied into the volume is proportional to {{math|1 / ''n''}}, where the constant of proportionality {{math|2\u03c0''R''<sup>2</sup>}} is independent of {{math|''n''}}. Eventually, {{math|''n''}} is so large that the new factor is less than 1. From then on, the volume of an {{math|''n''}}-ball must decrease at least geometrically, and therefore it tends to zero. A variant on this proof uses the one-dimension recursion formula. Here, the new factor is proportional to a quotient of gamma functions. [[Gautschi's inequality]] bounds this quotient above by {{math|''n''<sup>\u22121/2</sup>}}. The argument concludes as before by showing that the volumes decrease at least geometrically.\n\nA more precise description of the high dimensional behavior of the volume can be obtained using [[Stirling's approximation]]. It implies the [[asymptotic formula]]:\n:<math>V_n(R) \\sim \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{n\\pi}}\\left(\\frac{2\\pi e}{n}\\right)^\\frac{n}{2}R^n.</math>\nThe error in this approximation is a factor of {{math|1 + O(''n''<sup>\u22121</sup>)}}. Stirling's approximation is in fact an underestimate of the gamma function, so the above formula is an upper bound. This provides another proof that the volume of the ball decreases exponentially: When {{math|''n''}} is sufficiently large, the factor {{math|''R''{{sqrt|2\u03c0''e''/''n''}}}} is less than one, and then the same argument as before applies.\n\nIf instead {{math|''V''}} is fixed while {{math|''n''}} is large, then by Stirling's approximation again, the radius of an {{math|''n''}}-ball of volume {{math|''V''}} is approximately\n:<math>R_n(V) \\sim (\\pi n)^{\\frac{1}{2n}}\\sqrt{\\frac{n}{2\\pi e}}V^{\\frac{1}{n}}.</math>\nThis expression is a lower bound for {{math|''R''<sub>''n''</sub>(''V'')}}, and the error is again a factor of {{math|1 + O(''n''<sup>\u22121</sup>)}}. As {{math|''n''}} increases, {{math|''R''<sub>''n''</sub>(''V'')}} grows as <math>\\Theta(\\sqrt{n}).</math>\n\n=== Relation with surface area ===\nLet {{math|''A{{sub|n}}''(''R'')}} denote the surface area of the [[n-sphere|{{math|''n''}}-sphere]] of radius {{math|''R''}}. The {{math|''n''}}-sphere is the boundary of the {{math|(''n'' + 1)}}-ball of radius {{math|''R''}}. The {{math|(''n'' + 1)}}-ball is a union of concentric spheres, and consequently the surface area and the volume are related by:\n:<math>A_n(R) = \\frac{d}{dR}V_{n+1}(R).</math>\nCombining this with the explicit formula for the volume of an {{math|(''n'' + 1)}}-ball gives\n:<math>A_n(R) = \\frac{2\\pi^{\\frac{n + 1}{2}}}{\\Gamma\\big(\\frac{n + 1}{2}\\big)}R^n.</math>\n\nSince the volume is proportional to a power of the radius, the above relation leads to a simple equation relating the surface area of an {{math|''n''}}-ball and the volume of an {{math|(''n'' + 1)}}-ball. By applying the two-dimension recursion formula, it also gives an equation relating the surface area of an {{math|''n''}}-ball and the volume of an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-ball.  These formulas, together with the volume and surface area of zero-dimensional balls, can be used as a system of recurrence relations for the volumes and surface areas of balls:\n:<math>\\begin{align}\nV_0(R) &= 1, \\\\\nA_0(R) &= 2, \\\\\nV_{n+1}(R) &= \\frac{R}{n+1}A_n(R), \\\\\nA_{n+1}(R) &= (2\\pi R)V_n(R).\n\\end{align}</math>\n\n=== Dimension maximizing the volume of a fixed-radius ball ===\nSuppose that {{math|''R''}} is a fixed positive real number, and consider the volume {{math|''V''<sub>''n''</sub>(''R'')}} as a function of the positive integer {{nowrap|dimension {{math|''n''}}.}} Since the volume of a ball with fixed positive radius tends to zero as {{math|''n'' \u2192 \u221e}}, the maximum volume is achieved for some value of {{mvar|n}}. The dimension in which this happens depends on the radius {{math|''R''}}.\n\nTo find the {{mvar|n}} for which the maximum occurs, interpolate the function <math>n \\mapsto V_n(R)</math> to all real {{math|''x'' > 0}} by defining\n:<math>V(x, R) = \\frac{\\pi^\\frac{x}{2}}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{x}{2} + 1\\right)}R^x.</math>\nWhen {{math|''x''}} is not a positive integer, this function has no obvious geometric interpretation. However, it is smooth, so the techniques of calculus can be used to find maxima. \n\nThe extrema of {{math|''V''(''x'', ''R'')}} for fixed {{mvar|R}} may occur only at the critical points or at the boundaries {{math|''x'' \u2192 0<sup>+</sup>}} and {{math|''x'' \u2192 \u221e}}.  Because the logarithm is monotonically increasing, the critical points of <math>V(x, R)</math> are the same as those of its logarithm.  The derivative of <math>\\log V(x, R)</math> with respect to {{mvar|x}} is\n:<math>\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial x}\\big(\\log V(x, R)\\big) = \\frac{\\log \\pi}{2} + \\log R - \\frac{1}{2}\\psi\\left(\\frac{x}{2} + 1\\right),</math>\nwhere {{mvar|\u03c8}} is the [[digamma function]], the [[logarithmic derivative]] of the [[gamma function]].  The critical points of {{math|''V''(''x'', ''R'')}} therefore occur at the solutions of\n:<math>\\psi\\left(\\frac{x}{2} + 1\\right) = \\log \\pi + 2\\log R.</math>\n\nBecause the gamma function is [[logarithmically convex]] on the positive real axis, the digamma function is monotonically increasing there, so the above equation has at most one solution.  Because <math>\\textstyle\\lim_{x \\to 0^+} \\psi(x) = -\\infty</math> and <math>\\textstyle\\lim_{x \\to \\infty} \\psi(x) = +\\infty</math>, there is at least one positive real solution.  Therefore the above equation has a unique solution.  Denoting the solution by {{math|''x''<sub>0</sub>}}, we have\n:<math>x_0 =  2\\psi^{-1}(\\log \\pi + 2\\log R) - 2.</math>\n\nThe monotonicity of the digamma function along the positive real axis further implies that {{math|''V''(''x'', ''R'')}} is increasing for all {{math|''x'' < ''x''<sub>0</sub>}} and decreasing for all {{math|''x'' > ''x''<sub>0</sub>}}.  It follows that {{math|''x''<sub>0</sub>}} is the unique maximum of {{math|''V''(''x'', ''R'')}} and that the maxima of {{math|''n'' \u21a6 ''V''<sub>''n''</sub>(''R'')}} are contained in the set <math>\\{\\lfloor x_0\\rfloor, \\lceil x_0\\rceil\\}</math>.  If {{math|''x''<sub>0</sub>}} is an integer, then this set has only one element, and this element is the unique maximum of both {{math|''V''(''x'', ''R'')}} and {{math|''V''<sub>''n''</sub>(''R'')}}.  Otherwise, the set has two elements, and either {{math|''V''<sub>''n''</sub>(''R'')}} assumes its unique maximum at one of the two elements in the set, or {{math|''V''<sub>''n''</sub>(''R'')}} is maximized at both these elements.\n\nMore explicit, though less precise, estimates may be derived by bounding the digamma function.  For {{math|''y'' > 1}}, the digamma function satisfies:<ref>N. Elezovic, C. Giordano and J. Pecaric, ''The best bounds in Gautschi\u2019s inequality'', Math. Inequal. Appl. 3 (2000), 239\u2013252.</ref>\n:<math>\\log\\left(y - \\tfrac{1}{2}\\right) < \\psi(y) < \\log(y + e^{-\\gamma} - 1),</math>\nwhere {{math|''\u03b3''}} is the [[Euler\u2013Mascheroni constant]].  Applying these bounds with {{math|''y'' {{=}} {{sfrac|''x''<sub>0</sub>|2}} + 1}} yields\n:<math>\\log\\left(\\tfrac{x_0}{2} + \\tfrac{1}{2}\\right) < \\psi\\left(\\tfrac{x_0}{2} + 1\\right) = \\log \\pi + 2\\log R < \\log\\left(\\tfrac{x_0}{2} + e^{-\\gamma}\\right),</math>\nwhence\n:<math>2\\pi R^2 - 2e^{-\\gamma} < x_0 < 2\\pi R^2 - 1.</math>\n\nTherefore the maximum of {{math|''V''<sub>''n''</sub>(''R'')}} is achieved for some integer {{mvar|n}} such that\n:<math>\\lfloor 2\\pi R^2 - 2e^{-\\gamma}\\rfloor \\le n \\le \\lceil 2\\pi R^2 - 1\\rceil.</math>\nTo find the maximum of {{math|''V''<sub>''n''</sub>(''R'')}}, it suffices to maximize it over all {{math|''n''}} in this interval.  Because <math>|2e^{-\\gamma} - 1| < 0.2</math>, this interval contains at most three integers and often only two.\n\nFor example, when {{math|''R'' {{=}} 1}}, these bounds imply that the maximum volume is achieved for some {{mvar|n}} for which {{math|\u230a5.08\u230b \u2264 ''n'' \u2264 \u23085.28\u2309}}, that is, for {{math|''n'' {{=}} 5}} or {{math|''n'' {{=}} 6}}.  An examination of the table above shows that it is achieved at the lower bound, in dimension {{math|''n'' {{=}} 5}}.  When {{math|''R'' {{=}} 1.1}}, the bounds are {{math|\u230a6.48\u230b \u2264 ''n'' \u2264 \u23086.60\u2309}}, and the maximum is achieved at the upper bound, that is, when {{math|''n'' {{=}} 7}}.  Finally, if <math>R = \\exp(11/12 - \\gamma/2) / \\sqrt\\pi \\approx 1.057</math>, then the bounds are {{math|\u230a5.90\u230b \u2264 ''n'' \u2264 \u23086.02\u2309}}, so the interval of possible {{math|''n''}} contains three integers, and the maximum of both {{math|''V''<sub>''n''</sub>(''R'')}} and {{math|''V''(''x'', ''R'')}} is achieved at the integer {{math|''x''<sub>0</sub> {{=}} 6}}.\n\n== Proofs ==\nThere are many proofs of the above formulas.\n\n=== The volume is proportional to the {{math|''n''}}th power of the radius ===\nAn important step in several proofs about volumes of {{math|''n''}}-balls, and a generally useful fact besides, is that the volume of the {{math|''n''}}-ball of radius {{math|''R''}} is proportional to {{math|''R''<sup>''n''</sup>}}:\n:<math>V_n(R) \\propto R^n.</math>\nThe proportionality constant is the volume of the unit ball.\n\nThis is a special case of a general fact about volumes in {{math|''n''}}-dimensional space: If {{math|''K''}}\nis a body (measurable set) in that space and {{math|''RK''}} is the body obtained by stretching in all directions by the factor {{math|''R''}} then the volume of {{math|''RK''}} equals {{math|''R''<sup>''n''</sup>}} times the volume of {{math|''K''}}. This is a direct consequence of the change of variables formula:\n:<math> V(RK) = \\int_{RK} dx = \\int_K R^n\\, dy = R^n V(K) </math>\nwhere {{math|1=''dx'' = ''dx''<sub>1</sub>\u2026''dx<sub>n</sub>''}} and the substitution {{math|1=''x'' = ''Ry''}} was made.\n\nAnother proof of the above relation, which avoids multi-dimensional integration, uses induction: The base case is {{math|''n'' {{=}} 0}}, where the proportionality is obvious. For the inductive case, assume that proportionality is true in dimension {{math|''n'' \u2212 1}}. Note that the intersection of an {{math|''n''}}-ball with a hyperplane is an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-ball. When the volume of the {{math|''n''}}-ball is written as an integral of volumes of {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-balls:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\int_{-R}^R V_{n-1}\\left(\\sqrt{R^2 - x^2}\\right) \\,dx,</math>\nit is possible by the inductive assumption to remove a factor of {{math|''R''}} from the radius of the {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-ball to get:\n:<math>V_n(R) = R^{n-1} \\int_{-R}^R V_{n-1}\\left(\\sqrt{1 - \\left(\\frac{x}{R}\\right)^2}\\right) \\,dx.</math>\nMaking the change of variables {{math|''t'' {{=}} ''{{sfrac|x|R}}''}} leads to:\n:<math>V_n(R) = R^n \\int_{-1}^1 V_{n-1}\\left(\\sqrt{1 - t^2}\\right) \\,dt = R^n V_n(1),</math>\nwhich demonstrates the proportionality relation in dimension {{math|''n''}}. By induction, the proportionality relation is true in all dimensions.\n\n=== The two-dimension recursion formula ===\nA proof of the recursion formula relating the volume of the {{math|''n''}}-ball and an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 2)}}-ball can be given using the proportionality formula above and integration in [[Cylindrical coordinate system|cylindrical coordinates]]. Fix a plane through the center of the ball. Let {{math|''r''}} denote the distance between a point in the plane and the center of the sphere, and let {{math|''\u03b8''}} denote the azimuth. Intersecting the {{math|''n''}}-ball with the {{math|(''n'' \u2212 2)}}-dimensional plane defined by fixing a radius and an azimuth gives an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 2)}}-ball of radius {{math|{{sqrt|''R''<sup>2</sup> \u2212 ''r''<sup>2</sup>}}}}. The volume of the ball can therefore be written as an iterated integral of the volumes of the {{math|(''n'' \u2212 2)}}-balls over the possible radii and azimuths:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\int_0^{2\\pi} \\int_0^R V_{n-2}\\left(\\sqrt{R^2 - r^2}\\right) \\,r\\,dr\\,d\\theta,</math>\nThe azimuthal coordinate can be immediately integrated out. Applying the proportionality relation shows that the volume equals:\n:<math>V_n(R) = 2\\pi V_{n-2}(R) \\int_0^R \\left(1 - \\left(\\frac{r}{R}\\right)^2\\right)^\\frac{n-2}{2}\\,r\\,dr.</math>\nThe integral can be evaluated by making the substitution {{math|''u'' {{=}} 1 \u2212 (''{{sfrac|r|R}}''){{su|p=2}}}} to get:\n:<math>\\begin{align}\nV_n(R) &= 2\\pi V_{n-2}(R) \\cdot \\left[-\\frac{R^2}{n}\\left(1 - \\left(\\frac{r}{R}\\right)^2\\right)^\\frac{n}{2}\\right]_{r=0}^{r=R} \\\\\n&= \\frac{2\\pi R^2}{n} V_{n-2}(R),\n\\end{align}</math>\nwhich is the two-dimension recursion formula.\n\nThe same technique can be used to give an inductive proof of the volume formula. The base cases of the induction are the 0-ball and the 1-ball, which can be checked directly using the facts {{math|\u0393(1) {{=}} 1}} and {{math|\u0393({{sfrac|3|2}}) {{=}} {{sfrac|1|2}} \u00b7 \u0393({{sfrac|1|2}}) {{=}} {{sfrac|{{sqrt|\u03c0}}|2}}}}. The inductive step is similar to the above, but instead of applying proportionality to the volumes of the {{math|(''n'' \u2212 2)}}-balls, the inductive assumption is applied instead.\n\n=== The one-dimension recursion formula ===\nThe proportionality relation can also be used to prove the recursion formula relating the volumes of an {{math|''n''}}-ball and an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-ball. As in the proof of the proportionality formula, the volume of an {{math|''n''}}-ball can be written as an integral over the volumes of {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-balls. Instead of making a substitution, however, the proportionality relation can be applied to the volumes of the {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-balls in the integrand:\n:<math>V_n(R) = V_{n-1}(R) \\int_{-R}^R \\left(1 - \\left(\\frac{x}{R}\\right)^2\\right)^\\frac{n-1}{2} \\,dx.</math>\nThe integrand is an [[even function]], so by symmetry the interval of integration can be restricted to {{math|[0, ''R'']}}. On the interval {{math|[0, ''R'']}}, it is possible to apply the substitution {{math|''u'' {{=}} (''{{sfrac|x|R}}''){{su|p=2}}}}. This transforms the expression into:\n:<math>V_{n-1}(R) \\cdot R \\cdot \\int_0^1 (1-u)^\\frac{n-1}{2}u^{-\\frac12}\\,du</math>\nThe integral is a value of a well-known [[special function]] called the [[beta function]] {{math|\u0392(''x,y'')}}, and the volume in terms of the beta function is:\n:<math>V_n(R) = V_{n-1}(R) \\cdot R \\cdot \\Beta\\left(\\tfrac{n + 1}{2}, \\tfrac12\\right).</math>\nThe beta function can be expressed in terms of the gamma function in much the same way that factorials are related to [[binomial coefficient]]s. Applying this relationship gives:\n:<math>V_n(R) = V_{n-1}(R) \\cdot R \\cdot \\frac{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n + 1}{2}\\right)\\Gamma\\left(\\frac12\\right)}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2} + 1\\right)}.</math>\nUsing the value {{math|\u0393({{sfrac|1|2}}) {{=}} {{sqrt|\u03c0}}}} gives the one-dimension recursion formula:\n:<math>V_n(R) = R\\sqrt{\\pi}\\frac{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n+1}{2}\\right)}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2} + 1\\right)} V_{n-1}(R).</math>\n\nAs with the two-dimension recursive formula, the same technique can be used to give an inductive proof of the volume formula.\n\n=== Direct integration in spherical coordinates ===\nThe volume can be computed by integrating the volume element in [[Spherical coordinate system|spherical coordinates]]. The spherical coordinate system has a radial coordinate {{math|''r''}} and angular coordinates {{math|''\u03c6''<sub>1</sub>, \u2026, ''\u03c6''<sub>''n'' \u2212 1</sub>}}, where the domain of each {{math|''\u03c6''}} except {{math|''\u03c6''<sub>''n'' \u2212 1</sub>}} is {{math|[0, \u03c0)}}, and the domain of {{math|''\u03c6''<sub>''n'' \u2212 1</sub>}} is {{math|[0, 2\u03c0)}}. The spherical volume element is:\n:<math>dV = r^{n-1}\\sin^{n-2}(\\varphi_1)\\sin^{n-3}(\\varphi_2) \\cdots \\sin(\\varphi_{n-2})\\,dr\\,d\\varphi_1\\,d\\varphi_2 \\cdots d\\varphi_{n-1},</math>\nand the volume is the integral of this quantity over {{math|''r''}} between 0 and {{math|''R''}} and all possible angles:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\int_0^R \\int_0^\\pi \\cdots \\int_0^{2\\pi} r^{n-1}\\sin^{n-2}(\\varphi_1) \\cdots \\sin(\\varphi_{n-2})\\,d\\varphi_{n-1} \\cdots d\\varphi_1\\,dr.</math>\nEach of the factors in the integrand depends on only a single variable, and therefore the iterated integral can be written as a product of integrals:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\left(\\int_0^R r^{n-1}\\,dr\\right)\\left(\\int_0^\\pi \\sin^{n-2}(\\varphi_1)\\,d\\varphi_1\\right)\\cdots\\left(\\int_0^{2\\pi} d\\varphi_{n-1}\\right).</math>\nThe integral over the radius is {{math|''{{sfrac|R<sup>n</sup>|n}}''}}. The intervals of integration on the angular coordinates can, by symmetry, be changed to {{math|[0, {{sfrac|\u03c0|2}}]}}:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\frac{R^n}{n} \\left(2\\int_0^\\frac{\\pi}{2} \\sin^{n-2}(\\varphi_1)\\,d\\varphi_1\\right) \\cdots \\left(4\\int_0^\\frac{\\pi}{2} d\\varphi_{n-1}\\right).</math>\nEach of the remaining integrals is now a particular value of the beta function:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\frac{R^n}{n} \\Beta\\left(\\frac{n-1}{2}, \\frac12\\right) \\Beta\\left(\\frac{n-2}{2}, \\frac12\\right) \\cdots \\Beta\\left(1, \\frac12\\right) \\cdot 2\\Beta\\left(\\frac12, \\frac12\\right).</math>\nThe beta functions can be rewritten in terms of gamma functions:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\frac{R^n}{n} \\frac{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n-1}{2}\\right)\\Gamma\\left(\\frac12\\right)}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)} \\frac{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n-2}{2}\\right)\\Gamma\\left(\\frac12\\right)}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n - 1}{2}\\right)} \\cdots \\frac{\\Gamma\\left(1\\right)\\Gamma\\left(\\frac12\\right)}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac32\\right)} \\cdot 2 \\frac{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac12\\right)\\Gamma\\left(\\frac12\\right)}{\\Gamma\\left(1\\right)}.</math>\nThis product telescopes. Combining this with the values {{math|\u0393({{sfrac|1|2}}) {{=}} {{sqrt|\u03c0}}}} and {{math|\u0393(1) {{=}} 1}} and the functional equation {{math|''z''\u0393(''z'') {{=}} \u0393(''z'' + 1)}} leads to:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\frac{2\\pi^\\frac{n}{2}R^n}{n\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)} = \\frac{\\pi^\\frac{n}{2}R^n}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2} + 1\\right)}.</math>\n\n=== Gaussian integrals ===\nThe volume formula can be proven directly using [[Gaussian integral]]s. Consider the function:\n:<math>f(x_1, \\ldots, x_n) = \\exp\\left(-\\tfrac12 \\sum_{i=1}^n x_i^2\\right).</math>\nThis function is both rotationally invariant and a product of functions of one variable each. Using the fact that it is a product and the formula for the Gaussian integral gives:\n:<math>\\int_{\\mathbf{R}^n} f \\,dV = \\prod_{i=1}^n \\left(\\int_{-\\infty}^\\infty \\exp\\left(-\\tfrac12 x_i^2\\right)\\,dx_i\\right) = (2\\pi)^\\frac{n}{2},</math>\nwhere {{math|''dV''}} is the {{math|''n''}}-dimensional volume element. Using rotational invariance, the same integral can be computed in spherical coordinates:\n:<math>\\int_{\\mathbf{R}^n} f \\,dV = \\int_0^\\infty \\int_{S^{n-1}(r)} \\exp\\left(-\\tfrac12 r^2\\right) \\,dA\\,dr,</math>\nwhere {{math|''S''<sup>''n'' \u2212 1</sup>(''r'')}} is an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-sphere of radius {{math|''r''}} and {{math|''dA''}} is the area element (equivalently, the {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-dimensional volume element). The surface area of the sphere satisfies a proportionality equation similar to the one for the volume of a ball: If {{math|''A''<sub>''n'' \u2212 1</sub>(''r'')}} is the surface area of an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-sphere of radius {{math|''r''}}, then:\n:<math>A_{n-1}(r) = r^{n-1} A_{n-1}(1).</math>\nApplying this to the above integral gives the expression:\n:<math>A_{n-1}(1) \\int_0^\\infty \\exp\\left(-\\tfrac12 r^2\\right)\\,r^{n-1}\\,dr.</math>\nBy substituting {{math|''t'' {{=}} {{sfrac|''r''<sup>2</sup>|2}}}}, the expression is transformed into:\n:<math>A_{n-1}(1) 2^\\frac{n-2}{2} \\int_0^\\infty e^{-t} t^\\frac{n-2}{2}\\,dt.</math>\nThis is the gamma function evaluated at {{math|{{sfrac|''n''|2}}}}.\n\nCombining the two integrations shows that:\n:<math>A_{n-1}(1) = \\frac{2\\pi^\\frac{n}{2}}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)}.</math>\nTo derive the volume of an {{math|''n''}}-ball of radius {{math|''R''}} from this formula, integrate the surface area of a sphere of radius {{math|''r''}} for {{math|0 \u2264 ''r'' \u2264 ''R''}} and apply the functional equation {{math|''z''\u0393(''z'') {{=}} \u0393(''z'' + 1)}}:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\int_0^R \\frac{2\\pi^\\frac{n}{2}}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)} \\,r^{n-1}\\,dr = \\frac{2\\pi^\\frac{n}{2}}{n\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)}R^n = \\frac{\\pi^\\frac{n}{2}}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2} + 1\\right)}R^n.</math>\n\n=== Geometric proof ===\n\nThe relations <math display=\"inline\">V_{n+1}(R) = \\frac{R}{n+1}A_n(R)</math> and <math>A_{n+1}(R) = (2\\pi R)V_n(R)</math> and thus the volumes of ''n''-balls and areas of ''n''-spheres can also be derived geometrically.  As noted above, because a ball of radius <math>R</math> is obtained from a unit ball <math>B_n</math> by rescaling all directions in <math>R</math> times, <math>V_n(R)</math> is proportional to <math>R^n</math>, which implies <math display=\"inline\">\\frac{dV_n(R)}{dR} = \\frac{n}{R} V_n(R)</math>.  Also, <math display=\"inline\">A_{n-1}(R) = \\frac{dV_n(R)}{dR}</math> because a ball is a union of concentric spheres and increasing radius by ''\u03b5'' corresponds to a shell of thickness ''\u03b5''.  Thus, <math display=\"inline\">V_{n}(R) = \\frac{R}{n}A_{n-1}(R)</math>; equivalently, <math display=\"inline\">V_{n+1}(R) = \\frac{R}{n+1}A_n(R)</math>.\n\n<math>A_{n+1}(R) = (2\\pi R)V_n(R)</math> follows from existence of a volume-preserving bijection between the unit sphere <math>S_{n+1}</math> and <math> S_1 \\times B_n</math>:\n: <math>(x,y,\\vec{z}) \\rarr \\left(\\frac{x}{\\sqrt{x^2+y^2}},\\frac{y}{\\sqrt{x^2+y^2}},\\vec{z}\\right)</math>\n(<math>\\vec{z}</math> is an ''n''-tuple; <math>|(x,y,\\vec{z})|=1</math>; we are ignoring sets of measure 0).  Volume is preserved because at each point, the difference from [[isometry]] is a stretching in the ''xy'' plane (in <math display=\"inline\">1/\\sqrt{x^2+y^2}</math> times in the direction of constant <math>x^2+y^2</math>) that exactly matches the compression in the direction of the [[gradient]] of <math>|\\vec{z}|</math> on <math>S_n</math> (the relevant angles being equal).  For <math>S_2</math>, a similar argument was originally made by [[Archimedes]] in [[On the Sphere and Cylinder]].\n\n== Balls in {{math|''L''{{isup|''p''}}}} norms ==\nThere are also explicit expressions for the volumes of balls in [[Lp space|{{math|''L''{{isup|''p''}}}} norm]]s. The {{math|''L''{{isup|''p''}}}} norm of the vector {{math|''x'' {{=}} (''x''<sub>1</sub>, \u2026, ''x''<sub>''n''</sub>)}} in {{math|'''R'''<sup>''n''</sup>}} is:\n:<math>\\left(\\sum_{i=1}^n | x_i |^p \\right)^\\frac{1}{p},</math>\nand an {{math|''L''{{isup|''p''}}}} ball is the set of all vectors whose {{math|''L''{{isup|''p''}}}} norm is less than or equal to a fixed number called the radius of the ball. The case {{math|''p'' {{=}} 2}} is the standard Euclidean distance function, but other values of {{math|''p''}} occur in diverse contexts such as [[information theory]], [[coding theory]], and [[dimensional regularization]].\n\nThe volume of an {{math|''L''{{isup|''p''}}}} ball of radius {{math|''R''}} is:\n:<math>V^p_n(R) = \\frac{\\left(2\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{1}{p} + 1\\right)R\\right)^n}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{p} + 1\\right)}.</math>\nThese volumes satisfy a recurrence relation similar to the one dimension recurrence for {{math|''p'' {{=}} 2}}:\n:<math>V^p_n(R) = \\left(2\\Gamma\\left(\\tfrac{1}{p} + 1\\right) R\\right) \\frac{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n-1}{p} + 1\\right)}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{p} + 1\\right)} V^p_{n-1}(R).</math>\nFor {{math|''p'' {{=}} 2}}, one recovers the recurrence for the volume of a Euclidean ball because {{math|2\u0393({{sfrac|3|2}}) {{=}} {{sqrt|\u03c0}}}}.\n\nFor example, in the cases {{math|''p'' {{=}} 1}} ([[taxicab norm]]) and {{math|''p'' {{=}} \u221e}} ([[max norm]]), the volumes are:\n:<math>\\begin{align} V^1_n(R) &= \\frac{2^n}{n!}R^n, \\\\ V^\\infty_n(R) &= (2R)^n. \\end{align}</math>\nThese agree with elementary calculations of the volumes of [[cross-polytope]]s and [[hypercubes]].\n\n=== Relation with surface area ===\nFor most values of {{math|''p''}}, the surface area, <math>A_n^p(R)</math>, of an {{math|''L''{{isup|''p''}}}} sphere of radius {{math|''R''}} (the boundary of an {{math|''L''{{isup|''p''}}}} ball of radius {{math|''R''}}) cannot be calculated by differentiating the volume of an {{math|''L''{{isup|''p''}}}} ball with respect to its radius. While the volume can be expressed as an integral over the surface areas using the [[coarea formula]], the coarea formula contains a correction factor that accounts for how the {{math|''p''}}-norm varies from point to point. For {{math|''p'' {{=}} 2}} and {{math|''p'' {{=}} \u221e}}, this factor is one. However, if {{math|''p'' {{=}} 1}} then the correction factor is {{math|{{sqrt|''n''}}}}: the surface area of an {{math|''L''<sup>1</sup>}} sphere of radius {{math|''R''}} in {{math|'''R'''<sup>''n''</sup>}} is {{math|{{sqrt|''n''}}}} times the derivative of the volume of an {{math|''L''<sup>1</sup>}} ball.  This can be seen most simply by applying the [[divergence theorem]] to the vector field {{math|'''F'''(x) {{=}} x}} to get\n\n:<math>nV^1_n(R) = </math>{{oiint\n| preintegral = <math>\\iiint_V\\left(\\mathbf{\\nabla}\\cdot\\mathbf{F}\\right)\\,dV=</math>\n| intsubscpt = <math>\\scriptstyle S</math>\n| integrand = <math>(\\mathbf{F}\\cdot\\mathbf{n})\\,dS </math>\n}} <math> = </math> {{oiint\n| intsubscpt = <math>\\scriptstyle S</math>\n| integrand = <math>\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{n}}(|x_1|+\\cdots+|x_n|)\\,dS </math>\n}}  <math> = \\frac{R}{\\sqrt{n}} </math>{{oiint\n| intsubscpt = <math>\\scriptstyle S</math>\n| integrand = <math>\\,dS </math>\n}} <math> = \\frac{R}{\\sqrt{n}} A^1_n(R) </math>.\nFor other values of {{math|''p''}}, the constant is a complicated integral.\n\n=== Generalizations ===\nThe volume formula can be generalized even further. For positive real numbers {{math|''p''<sub>1</sub>, \u2026, ''p''<sub>''n''</sub>}}, define the unit {{math|(''p''<sub>1</sub>, \u2026, ''p''<sub>''n''</sub>)}} ball to be:\n:<math>B_{p_1, \\ldots, p_n} = \\left\\{ x = (x_1, \\ldots, x_n) \\in \\mathbf{R}^n : \\vert x_1 \\vert^{p_1} + \\cdots + \\vert x_n \\vert^{p_n} \\le 1 \\right\\}.</math>\nThe volume of this ball has been known since the time of Dirichlet:<ref>{{cite journal|last=Dirichlet|first=P. G. Lejeune|title=Sur une nouvelle m\u00e9thode pour la d\u00e9termination des int\u00e9grales multiples|trans-title=On a novel method for determining multiple integrals|journal=Journal de Math\u00e9matiques Pures et Appliqu\u00e9es|volume=4|date=1839|pages=164\u2013168}}</ref>\n:<math>V(B_{p_1, \\ldots, p_n}) = 2^n \\frac{\\Gamma\\left(1 + \\frac{1}{p_1}\\right) \\cdots \\Gamma\\left(1 + \\frac{1}{p_n}\\right)}{\\Gamma\\left(1 + \\frac{1}{p_1} + \\cdots + \\frac{1}{p_n}\\right)}.</math>\n\n==See also==\n* [[n-sphere|{{math|''n''}}-sphere]]\n* [[Sphere packing]]\n* [[Hamming bound]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.brouty.fr/Maths/sphere.html Derivation in hyperspherical coordinates] {{in lang|fr}}\n* [http://mathworld.wolfram.com/Hypersphere.html Hypersphere] on Wolfram MathWorld\n* [http://www.mathreference.com/ca-int,hsp.html Volume of the Hypersphere] at Math Reference\n\n[[Category:Multi-dimensional geometry]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Generalizing the notion of 3-dimensional volume to regions of points in n-dimensional Euclidean space with distance to a center less than a constant}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Volume of an ''n''-ball}}\n{{hypersphere_volume_and_surface_area_graphs.svg|250px}}\nIn [[geometry]], a '''[[ball (mathematics)|ball]]''' is a region in space comprising all points within a fixed distance from a given point; that is, it is the region enclosed by a [[sphere]] or [[hypersphere]]. An {{math|''n''}}-ball is a ball in {{math|''n''}}-dimensional [[Euclidean space]]. The '''volume of a unit {{math|''n''}}-ball''' is an important expression that occurs in formulas throughout mathematics; it generalizes the notion of the volume enclosed by a sphere in 3-dimensional space.\n\n== Formulas ==\n\n=== The volume ===\nThe {{math|''n''}}-dimensional volume of a Euclidean ball of radius {{math|''R''}} in {{math|''n''}}-dimensional Euclidean space is:<ref>Equation 5.19.4, ''NIST Digital Library of Mathematical Functions.'' http://dlmf.nist.gov/5.19#E4, Release 1.0.6 of 2013-05-06.</ref>\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\frac{\\pi^\\frac{n}{2}}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2} + 1\\right)}R^n,</math>\nwhere {{math|\u0393}} is [[Leonhard Euler]]'s [[gamma function]].  The gamma function extends the [[factorial]] function to non-integer arguments.  It satisfies {{math|\u0393(''n'') {{=}} (''n'' \u2212 1)!}} if {{math|''n''}} is a positive integer and {{math|\u0393(''n'' + {{sfrac|1|2}}) {{=}} (''n'' \u2212 {{sfrac|1|2}}) \u00b7 (''n'' \u2212 {{sfrac|3|2}}) \u00b7 \u2026 \u00b7 {{sfrac|1|2}} \u00b7 \u03c0<sup>1/2</sup>}} if {{math|''n''}} is a non-negative integer.\n\n=== Alternative forms ===\nUsing explicit formulas for [[particular values of the gamma function]] at the integers and half integers gives formulas for the volume of a Euclidean ball that do not require an evaluation of the gamma function. These are:\n:<math>\\begin{align}V_{2k}(R) &= \\frac{\\pi^k}{k!}R^{2k}, \\\\\nV_{2k+1}(R) &= \\frac{2^{k+1}\\pi^k}{(2k+1)!!}R^{2k+1} = \\frac{2(k!)(4\\pi)^k}{(2k+1)!}R^{2k+1}.\\end{align}</math>\nIn the formula for odd-dimensional volumes, the [[double factorial]] {{math|(2''k'' + 1)!!}} is defined for odd integers {{math|2''k'' + 1}} as {{math|(2''k'' + 1)!! {{=}} 1 \u00b7 3 \u00b7 5 \u00b7 \u2026 \u00b7 (2''k'' \u2212 1) \u00b7 (2''k'' + 1)}}. \n\nInstead of expressing the volume {{math|''V''}} of the ball in terms of its radius {{math|''R''}}, the formula can be [[Inverse function|inverted]] to express the radius as a function of the volume:\n:<math>R_n(V) = \\frac{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2} + 1\\right)^\\frac{1}{n}}{\\sqrt{\\pi}}V^\\frac{1}{n}.</math>\nThis formula, too, can be separated into even- and odd-dimensional cases using factorials and double factorials in place of the gamma function:\n:<math>\\begin{align}R_{2k}(V) &= \\frac{(k!V)^\\frac{1}{2k}}{\\sqrt{\\pi}}, \\\\\nR_{2k+1}(V) &= \\left(\\frac{(2k+1)!!V}{2^{k+1}\\pi^k}\\right)^\\frac{1}{2k+1}.\\end{align}</math>\n\n=== Recursions ===\nThe volume satisfies several recursive formulas. These formulas can either be proved directly or proved as consequences of the general volume formula above. The simplest to state is a formula for the volume of an {{math|''n''}}-ball in terms of the volume of an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 2)}}-ball of the same radius:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\frac{2\\pi R^2}{n} V_{n-2}(R).</math>\n\nThere is also a formula for the volume of an {{math|''n''}}-ball in terms of the volume of an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-ball of the same radius:\n:<math>V_n(R) = R\\sqrt{\\pi}\\frac{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n+1}{2}\\right)}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2} + 1\\right)} V_{n-1}(R).</math>\nUsing explicit formulas for the gamma function again shows that the one-dimension recursion formula can also be written as:\n\n:<math>\\begin{align}\nV_{2k}(R) &= R\\pi \\frac{(2k - 1)!!}{2^k k!} V_{2k-1}(R) = R\\pi \\frac{(2k-1)(2k-3) \\cdots 5 \\cdot 3 \\cdot 1}{(2k)(2k - 2) \\cdots 6 \\cdot 4 \\cdot 2} V_{2k-1}(R), \\\\[10px]\nV_{2k+1}(R) &= 2R\\frac{2^k k!}{(2k+1)!!} V_{2k}(R) = 2R\\frac{(2k)(2k - 2) \\cdots 6 \\cdot 4 \\cdot 2}{(2k+1)(2k-1) \\cdots 5 \\cdot 3 \\cdot 1} V_{2k}(R).\n\\end{align}</math>\n\nThe radius of an {{math|''n''}}-ball of volume {{math|''V''}} may be expressed recursively in terms of the radius of an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-ball or an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 2)}}-ball.  These formulas may be derived from the explicit formula for {{math|''R''<sub>''n''</sub>(''V'')}} above.\n:<math>\\begin{align}\nR_n(V) &= \\frac{\\Gamma(\\frac{n}{2} + 1)^{1/n}}{\\Gamma(\\frac{n-1}{2} + 1)^{1/(n-1)}}V^{-1/(n(n-1))}R_{n-1}(V), \\\\\nR_n(V) &= \\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)^{1/n}\\left(V \\cdot \\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)\\right)^{-2/(n(n-2))}R_{n-2}(V).\n\\end{align}</math>\nUsing explicit formulas for the gamma function shows that the one-dimension recursion formula is equivalent to\n:<math>\\begin{align}\nR_{2k}(V)\n&= \\frac{(2^kk!)^{1/(2k)}}{(2k-1)!!^{1/(2k-1)}}\\left(\\frac{2}{\\pi}\\right)^{1/(4k-2)}V^{-1/(2k(2k-1))} R_{2k-1}(V) \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\big((2k)(2k - 2) \\cdots 6 \\cdot 4 \\cdot 2\\big)^{1/(2k)}}{\\big((2k - 1)(2k - 3) \\cdots 5 \\cdot 3 \\cdot 1\\big)^{1/(2k-1)}} \\left(\\frac{2}{\\pi}\\right)^{1/(4k-2)}V^{-1/(2k(2k-1))} R_{2k-1}(V), \\\\\nR_{2k+1}(V)\n&= \\frac{(2k+1)!!^{1/(2k+1)}}{(2^k k!)^{1/(2k)}} \\left(\\frac{\\pi}{2}\\right)^{1/(4k+2)} V^{-1/((2k+1)2k)} R_{2k}(V) \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\big((2k + 1)(2k - 1) \\cdots 5 \\cdot 3 \\cdot 1\\big)^{1/(2k+1)}}{\\big((2k)(2k - 2) \\cdots 6 \\cdot 4 \\cdot 2\\big)^{1/(2k)}} \\left(\\frac{\\pi}{2}\\right)^{1/(4k+2)} V^{-1/((2k+1)2k)} R_{2k}(V), \\\\\n\\end{align}</math>\nand that the two-dimension recursion formula is equivalent to\n:<math>\\begin{align}\nR_{2k}(V)\n&= k^{1/(2k)} (V \\cdot (k-1)!)^{-1/(2(k-1)k)} R_{2k-2}(V) \\\\\n&= k^{1/(2k)} (V \\cdot (k-1) \\cdot (k-2) \\cdots 3 \\cdot 2 \\cdot 1)^{-1/(2(k-1)k)} R_{2k-2}(V), \\\\\nR_{2k+1}(V)\n&= (2k + 1)^{1/(2k+1)} \\left(V \\cdot (2k - 1)!!\\sqrt{\\frac{\\pi}{2}}\\right)^{-2/(4k^2 - 1)} R_{2k-1}(V) \\\\\n&= (2k + 1)^{1/(2k+1)} \\left(V \\cdot (2k - 1)(2k - 3) \\cdots 5 \\cdot 3 \\cdot 1 \\sqrt{\\frac{\\pi}{2}}\\right)^{-2/(4k^2-1)} R_{2k-1}(V).\n\\end{align}</math>\n\n=== Low dimensions ===\nIn low dimensions, these volume and radius formulas simplify to the following.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Dimension !! Volume of a ball of radius {{math|''R''}} !! Radius of a ball of volume {{math|''V''}}\n|-\n| 0\n| <math>1</math>\n| (all 0-balls have volume 1)\n|-\n| 1\n| <math>2R</math>\n| <math>\\frac{V}{2}=0.5\\times V</math>\n|-\n| 2\n| <math>\\pi R^2 \\approx 3.142\\times R^2</math>\n| <math>\\frac{V^\\frac12}{\\sqrt{\\pi}}\\approx 0.564\\times V^{\\frac{1}{2}}</math>\n|-\n| 3\n| <math>\\frac{4\\pi}{3} R^3 \\approx 4.189\\times R^3</math> \t\n| <math>\\left(\\frac{3V}{4\\pi}\\right)^\\frac13\\approx 0.620\\times V^\\frac13</math>\n|-\n| 4\n| <math>\\frac{\\pi^2}{2} R^4 \\approx 4.935\\times R^4</math>\n| <math>\\frac{(2V)^\\frac14}{\\sqrt{\\pi}}\\approx 0.671\\times V^\\frac14</math>\n|-\n| 5\n| <math>\\frac{8\\pi^2}{15} R^5\\approx 5.264\\times R^5</math>\n| <math>\\left(\\frac{15V}{8\\pi^2}\\right)^\\frac15\\approx 0.717\\times V^\\frac15</math>\n|-\n| 6\n| <math>\\frac{\\pi^3}{6} R^6 \\approx 5.168 \\times R^6</math>\n| <math>\\frac{(6V)^\\frac16}{\\sqrt{\\pi}}\\approx 0.761\\times V^\\frac16</math>\n|-\n| 7\n| <math>\\frac{16\\pi^3}{105} R^7 \\approx 4.725\\times R^7</math>\n| <math>\\left(\\frac{105V}{16\\pi^3}\\right)^\\frac17\\approx 0.801\\times V^\\frac17</math>\n|-\n| 8\n| <math>\\frac{\\pi^4}{24} R^8 \\approx 4.059\\times R^8</math>\n| <math>\\frac{(24V)^\\frac18}{\\sqrt{\\pi}}\\approx 0.839\\times V^\\frac18</math>\n|-\n| 9\n| <math>\\frac{32\\pi^4}{945} R^9 \\approx 3.299\\times R^9</math>\n| <math>\\left(\\frac{945V}{32\\pi^4}\\right)^\\frac19\\approx 0.876\\times V^\\frac19</math>\n|-\n| 10\n| <math>\\frac{\\pi^5}{120} R^{10} \\approx 2.550\\times R^{10}</math>\n| <math>\\frac{(120V)^\\frac{1}{10}}{\\sqrt{\\pi}}\\approx 0.911\\times V^\\frac{1}{10}</math>\n|-\n| 11\n| <math>\\frac{64\\pi^5}{10395} R^{11} \\approx 1.884\\times R^{11}</math>\n| <math>\\left(\\frac{10395V}{64\\pi^5}\\right)^\\frac{1}{11}\\approx 0.944\\times V^\\frac{1}{11}</math>\n|-\n| 12\n| <math>\\frac{\\pi^6}{720} R^{12} \\approx 1.335\\times R^{12}</math>\n| <math>\\frac{(720V)^\\frac{1}{12}}{\\sqrt{\\pi}}\\approx 0.976\\times V^\\frac{1}{12}</math>\n|}\n\n=== High dimensions ===\nSuppose that {{math|''R''}} is fixed. Then the volume of an {{math|''n''}}-ball of radius {{math|''R''}} approaches zero as {{math|''n''}} tends to infinity. This can be shown using the two-dimension recursion formula. At each step, the new factor being multiplied into the volume is proportional to {{math|1 / ''n''}}, where the constant of proportionality {{math|2\u03c0''R''<sup>2</sup>}} is independent of {{math|''n''}}. Eventually, {{math|''n''}} is so large that the new factor is less than 1. From then on, the volume of an {{math|''n''}}-ball must decrease at least geometrically, and therefore it tends to zero. A variant on this proof uses the one-dimension recursion formula. Here, the new factor is proportional to a quotient of gamma functions. [[Gautschi's inequality]] bounds this quotient above by {{math|''n''<sup>\u22121/2</sup>}}. The argument concludes as before by showing that the volumes decrease at least geometrically.\n\nA more precise description of the high dimensional behavior of the volume can be obtained using [[Stirling's approximation]]. It implies the [[asymptotic formula]]:\n:<math>V_n(R) \\sim \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{n\\pi}}\\left(\\frac{2\\pi e}{n}\\right)^\\frac{n}{2}R^n.</math>\nThe error in this approximation is a factor of {{math|1 + O(''n''<sup>\u22121</sup>)}}. Stirling's approximation is in fact an underestimate of the gamma function, so the above formula is an upper bound. This provides another proof that the volume of the ball decreases exponentially: When {{math|''n''}} is sufficiently large, the factor {{math|''R''{{sqrt|2\u03c0''e''/''n''}}}} is less than one, and then the same argument as before applies.\n\nIf instead {{math|''V''}} is fixed while {{math|''n''}} is large, then by Stirling's approximation again, the radius of an {{math|''n''}}-ball of volume {{math|''V''}} is approximately\n:<math>R_n(V) \\sim (\\pi n)^{\\frac{1}{2n}}\\sqrt{\\frac{n}{2\\pi e}}V^{\\frac{1}{n}}.</math>\nThis expression is a lower bound for {{math|''R''<sub>''n''</sub>(''V'')}}, and the error is again a factor of {{math|1 + O(''n''<sup>\u22121</sup>)}}. As {{math|''n''}} increases, {{math|''R''<sub>''n''</sub>(''V'')}} grows as <math>\\Theta(\\sqrt{n}).</math>\n\n=== Relation with surface area ===\nLet {{math|''A{{sub|n}}''(''R'')}} denote the surface area of the [[n-sphere|{{math|''n''}}-sphere]] of radius {{math|''R''}}. The {{math|''n''}}-sphere is the boundary of the {{math|(''n'' + 1)}}-ball of radius {{math|''R''}}. The {{math|(''n'' + 1)}}-ball is a union of concentric spheres, and consequently the surface area and the volume are related by:\n:<math>A_n(R) = \\frac{d}{dR}V_{n+1}(R).</math>\nCombining this with the explicit formula for the volume of an {{math|(''n'' + 1)}}-ball gives\n:<math>A_n(R) = \\frac{2\\pi^{\\frac{n + 1}{2}}}{\\Gamma\\big(\\frac{n + 1}{2}\\big)}R^n.</math>\n\nSince the volume is proportional to a power of the radius, the above relation leads to a simple equation relating the surface area of an {{math|''n''}}-ball and the volume of an {{math|(''n'' + 1)}}-ball. By applying the two-dimension recursion formula, it also gives an equation relating the surface area of an {{math|''n''}}-ball and the volume of an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-ball.  These formulas, together with the volume and surface area of zero-dimensional balls, can be used as a system of recurrence relations for the volumes and surface areas of balls:\n:<math>\\begin{align}\nV_0(R) &= 1, \\\\\nA_0(R) &= 2, \\\\\nV_{n+1}(R) &= \\frac{R}{n+1}A_n(R), \\\\\nA_{n+1}(R) &= (2\\pi R)V_n(R).\n\\end{align}</math>\n\n=== Dimension maximizing the volume of a fixed-radius ball ===\nSuppose that {{math|''R''}} is a fixed positive real number, and consider the volume {{math|''V''<sub>''n''</sub>(''R'')}} as a function of the positive integer {{nowrap|dimension {{math|''n''}}.}} Since the volume of a ball with fixed positive radius tends to zero as {{math|''n'' \u2192 \u221e}}, the maximum volume is achieved for some value of {{mvar|n}}. The dimension in which this happens depends on the radius {{math|''R''}}.\n\nTo find the {{mvar|n}} for which the maximum occurs, interpolate the function <math>n \\mapsto V_n(R)</math> to all real {{math|''x'' > 0}} by defining\n:<math>V(x, R) = \\frac{\\pi^\\frac{x}{2}}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{x}{2} + 1\\right)}R^x.</math>\nWhen {{math|''x''}} is not a positive integer, this function has no obvious geometric interpretation. However, it is smooth, so the techniques of calculus can be used to find maxima. \n\nThe extrema of {{math|''V''(''x'', ''R'')}} for fixed {{mvar|R}} may occur only at the critical points or at the boundaries {{math|''x'' \u2192 0<sup>+</sup>}} and {{math|''x'' \u2192 \u221e}}.  Because the logarithm is monotonically increasing, the critical points of <math>V(x, R)</math> are the same as those of its logarithm.  The derivative of <math>\\log V(x, R)</math> with respect to {{mvar|x}} is\n:<math>\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial x}\\big(\\log V(x, R)\\big) = \\frac{\\log \\pi}{2} + \\log R - \\frac{1}{2}\\psi\\left(\\frac{x}{2} + 1\\right),</math>\nwhere {{mvar|\u03c8}} is the [[digamma function]], the [[logarithmic derivative]] of the [[gamma function]].  The critical points of {{math|''V''(''x'', ''R'')}} therefore occur at the solutions of\n:<math>\\psi\\left(\\frac{x}{2} + 1\\right) = \\log \\pi + 2\\log R.</math>\n\nBecause the gamma function is [[logarithmically convex]] on the positive real axis, the digamma function is monotonically increasing there, so the above equation has at most one solution.  Because <math>\\textstyle\\lim_{x \\to 0^+} \\psi(x) = -\\infty</math> and <math>\\textstyle\\lim_{x \\to \\infty} \\psi(x) = +\\infty</math>, there is at least one positive real solution.  Therefore the above equation has a unique solution.  Denoting the solution by {{math|''x''<sub>0</sub>}}, we have\n:<math>x_0 =  2\\psi^{-1}(\\log \\pi + 2\\log R) - 2.</math>\n\nThe monotonicity of the digamma function along the positive real axis further implies that {{math|''V''(''x'', ''R'')}} is increasing for all {{math|''x'' < ''x''<sub>0</sub>}} and decreasing for all {{math|''x'' > ''x''<sub>0</sub>}}.  It follows that {{math|''x''<sub>0</sub>}} is the unique maximum of {{math|''V''(''x'', ''R'')}} and that the maxima of {{math|''n'' \u21a6 ''V''<sub>''n''</sub>(''R'')}} are contained in the set <math>\\{\\lfloor x_0\\rfloor, \\lceil x_0\\rceil\\}</math>.  If {{math|''x''<sub>0</sub>}} is an integer, then this set has only one element, and this element is the unique maximum of both {{math|''V''(''x'', ''R'')}} and {{math|''V''<sub>''n''</sub>(''R'')}}.  Otherwise, the set has two elements, and either {{math|''V''<sub>''n''</sub>(''R'')}} assumes its unique maximum at one of the two elements in the set, or {{math|''V''<sub>''n''</sub>(''R'')}} is maximized at both these elements.\n\nMore explicit, though less precise, estimates may be derived by bounding the digamma function.  For {{math|''y'' > 1}}, the digamma function satisfies:<ref>N. Elezovic, C. Giordano and J. Pecaric, ''The best bounds in Gautschi\u2019s inequality'', Math. Inequal. Appl. 3 (2000), 239\u2013252.</ref>\n:<math>\\log\\left(y - \\tfrac{1}{2}\\right) < \\psi(y) < \\log(y + e^{-\\gamma} - 1),</math>\nwhere {{math|''\u03b3''}} is the [[Euler\u2013Mascheroni constant]].  Applying these bounds with {{math|''y'' {{=}} {{sfrac|''x''<sub>0</sub>|2}} + 1}} yields\n:<math>\\log\\left(\\tfrac{x_0}{2} + \\tfrac{1}{2}\\right) < \\psi\\left(\\tfrac{x_0}{2} + 1\\right) = \\log \\pi + 2\\log R < \\log\\left(\\tfrac{x_0}{2} + e^{-\\gamma}\\right),</math>\nwhence\n:<math>2\\pi R^2 - 2e^{-\\gamma} < x_0 < 2\\pi R^2 - 1.</math>\n\nTherefore the maximum of {{math|''V''<sub>''n''</sub>(''R'')}} is achieved for some integer {{mvar|n}} such that\n:<math>\\lfloor 2\\pi R^2 - 2e^{-\\gamma}\\rfloor \\le n \\le \\lceil 2\\pi R^2 - 1\\rceil.</math>\nTo find the maximum of {{math|''V''<sub>''n''</sub>(''R'')}}, it suffices to maximize it over all {{math|''n''}} in this interval.  Because <math>|2e^{-\\gamma} - 1| < 0.2</math>, this interval contains at most three integers and often only two.\n\nFor example, when {{math|''R'' {{=}} 1}}, these bounds imply that the maximum volume is achieved for some {{mvar|n}} for which {{math|\u230a5.08\u230b \u2264 ''n'' \u2264 \u23085.28\u2309}}, that is, for {{math|''n'' {{=}} 5}} or {{math|''n'' {{=}} 6}}.  An examination of the table above shows that it is achieved at the lower bound, in dimension {{math|''n'' {{=}} 5}}.  When {{math|''R'' {{=}} 1.1}}, the bounds are {{math|\u230a6.48\u230b \u2264 ''n'' \u2264 \u23086.60\u2309}}, and the maximum is achieved at the upper bound, that is, when {{math|''n'' {{=}} 7}}.  Finally, if <math>R = \\exp(11/12 - \\gamma/2) / \\sqrt\\pi \\approx 1.057</math>, then the bounds are {{math|\u230a5.90\u230b \u2264 ''n'' \u2264 \u23086.02\u2309}}, so the interval of possible {{math|''n''}} contains three integers, and the maximum of both {{math|''V''<sub>''n''</sub>(''R'')}} and {{math|''V''(''x'', ''R'')}} is achieved at the integer {{math|''x''<sub>0</sub> {{=}} 6}}.\n\n== Proofs ==\nThere are many proofs of the above formulas.\n\n=== The volume is proportional to the {{math|''n''}}th power of the radius ===\nAn important step in several proofs about volumes of {{math|''n''}}-balls, and a generally useful fact besides, is that the volume of the {{math|''n''}}-ball of radius {{math|''R''}} is proportional to {{math|''R''<sup>''n''</sup>}}:\n:<math>V_n(R) \\propto R^n.</math>\nThe proportionality constant is the volume of the unit ball.\n\nThis is a special case of a general fact about volumes in {{math|''n''}}-dimensional space: If {{math|''K''}}\nis a body (measurable set) in that space and {{math|''RK''}} is the body obtained by stretching in all directions by the factor {{math|''R''}} then the volume of {{math|''RK''}} equals {{math|''R''<sup>''n''</sup>}} times the volume of {{math|''K''}}. This is a direct consequence of the change of variables formula:\n:<math> V(RK) = \\int_{RK} dx = \\int_K R^n\\, dy = R^n V(K) </math>\nwhere {{math|1=''dx'' = ''dx''<sub>1</sub>\u2026''dx<sub>n</sub>''}} and the substitution {{math|1=''x'' = ''Ry''}} was made.\n\nAnother proof of the above relation, which avoids multi-dimensional integration, uses induction: The base case is {{math|''n'' {{=}} 0}}, where the proportionality is obvious. For the inductive case, assume that proportionality is true in dimension {{math|''n'' \u2212 1}}. Note that the intersection of an {{math|''n''}}-ball with a hyperplane is an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-ball. When the volume of the {{math|''n''}}-ball is written as an integral of volumes of {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-balls:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\int_{-R}^R V_{n-1}\\left(\\sqrt{R^2 - x^2}\\right) \\,dx,</math>\nit is possible by the inductive assumption to remove a factor of {{math|''R''}} from the radius of the {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-ball to get:\n:<math>V_n(R) = R^{n-1} \\int_{-R}^R V_{n-1}\\left(\\sqrt{1 - \\left(\\frac{x}{R}\\right)^2}\\right) \\,dx.</math>\nMaking the change of variables {{math|''t'' {{=}} ''{{sfrac|x|R}}''}} leads to:\n:<math>V_n(R) = R^n \\int_{-1}^1 V_{n-1}\\left(\\sqrt{1 - t^2}\\right) \\,dt = R^n V_n(1),</math>\nwhich demonstrates the proportionality relation in dimension {{math|''n''}}. By induction, the proportionality relation is true in all dimensions.\n\n=== The two-dimension recursion formula ===\nA proof of the recursion formula relating the volume of the {{math|''n''}}-ball and an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 2)}}-ball can be given using the proportionality formula above and integration in [[Cylindrical coordinate system|cylindrical coordinates]]. Fix a plane through the center of the ball. Let {{math|''r''}} denote the distance between a point in the plane and the center of the sphere, and let {{math|''\u03b8''}} denote the azimuth. Intersecting the {{math|''n''}}-ball with the {{math|(''n'' \u2212 2)}}-dimensional plane defined by fixing a radius and an azimuth gives an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 2)}}-ball of radius {{math|{{sqrt|''R''<sup>2</sup> \u2212 ''r''<sup>2</sup>}}}}. The volume of the ball can therefore be written as an iterated integral of the volumes of the {{math|(''n'' \u2212 2)}}-balls over the possible radii and azimuths:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\int_0^{2\\pi} \\int_0^R V_{n-2}\\left(\\sqrt{R^2 - r^2}\\right) \\,r\\,dr\\,d\\theta,</math>\nThe azimuthal coordinate can be immediately integrated out. Applying the proportionality relation shows that the volume equals:\n:<math>V_n(R) = 2\\pi V_{n-2}(R) \\int_0^R \\left(1 - \\left(\\frac{r}{R}\\right)^2\\right)^\\frac{n-2}{2}\\,r\\,dr.</math>\nThe integral can be evaluated by making the substitution {{math|''u'' {{=}} 1 \u2212 (''{{sfrac|r|R}}''){{su|p=2}}}} to get:\n:<math>\\begin{align}\nV_n(R) &= 2\\pi V_{n-2}(R) \\cdot \\left[-\\frac{R^2}{n}\\left(1 - \\left(\\frac{r}{R}\\right)^2\\right)^\\frac{n}{2}\\right]_{r=0}^{r=R} \\\\\n&= \\frac{2\\pi R^2}{n} V_{n-2}(R),\n\\end{align}</math>\nwhich is the two-dimension recursion formula.\n\nThe same technique can be used to give an inductive proof of the volume formula. The base cases of the induction are the 0-ball and the 1-ball, which can be checked directly using the facts {{math|\u0393(1) {{=}} 1}} and {{math|\u0393({{sfrac|3|2}}) {{=}} {{sfrac|1|2}} \u00b7 \u0393({{sfrac|1|2}}) {{=}} {{sfrac|{{sqrt|\u03c0}}|2}}}}. The inductive step is similar to the above, but instead of applying proportionality to the volumes of the {{math|(''n'' \u2212 2)}}-balls, the inductive assumption is applied instead.\n\n=== The one-dimension recursion formula ===\nThe proportionality relation can also be used to prove the recursion formula relating the volumes of an {{math|''n''}}-ball and an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-ball. As in the proof of the proportionality formula, the volume of an {{math|''n''}}-ball can be written as an integral over the volumes of {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-balls. Instead of making a substitution, however, the proportionality relation can be applied to the volumes of the {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-balls in the integrand:\n:<math>V_n(R) = V_{n-1}(R) \\int_{-R}^R \\left(1 - \\left(\\frac{x}{R}\\right)^2\\right)^\\frac{n-1}{2} \\,dx.</math>\nThe integrand is an [[even function]], so by symmetry the interval of integration can be restricted to {{math|[0, ''R'']}}. On the interval {{math|[0, ''R'']}}, it is possible to apply the substitution {{math|''u'' {{=}} (''{{sfrac|x|R}}''){{su|p=2}}}}. This transforms the expression into:\n:<math>V_{n-1}(R) \\cdot R \\cdot \\int_0^1 (1-u)^\\frac{n-1}{2}u^{-\\frac12}\\,du</math>\nThe integral is a value of a well-known [[special function]] called the [[beta function]] {{math|\u0392(''x,y'')}}, and the volume in terms of the beta function is:\n:<math>V_n(R) = V_{n-1}(R) \\cdot R \\cdot \\Beta\\left(\\tfrac{n + 1}{2}, \\tfrac12\\right).</math>\nThe beta function can be expressed in terms of the gamma function in much the same way that factorials are related to [[binomial coefficient]]s. Applying this relationship gives:\n:<math>V_n(R) = V_{n-1}(R) \\cdot R \\cdot \\frac{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n + 1}{2}\\right)\\Gamma\\left(\\frac12\\right)}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2} + 1\\right)}.</math>\nUsing the value {{math|\u0393({{sfrac|1|2}}) {{=}} {{sqrt|\u03c0}}}} gives the one-dimension recursion formula:\n:<math>V_n(R) = R\\sqrt{\\pi}\\frac{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n+1}{2}\\right)}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2} + 1\\right)} V_{n-1}(R).</math>\n\nAs with the two-dimension recursive formula, the same technique can be used to give an inductive proof of the volume formula.\n\n=== Direct integration in spherical coordinates ===\nThe volume can be computed by integrating the volume element in [[Spherical coordinate system|spherical coordinates]]. The spherical coordinate system has a radial coordinate {{math|''r''}} and angular coordinates {{math|''\u03c6''<sub>1</sub>, \u2026, ''\u03c6''<sub>''n'' \u2212 1</sub>}}, where the domain of each {{math|''\u03c6''}} except {{math|''\u03c6''<sub>''n'' \u2212 1</sub>}} is {{math|[0, \u03c0)}}, and the domain of {{math|''\u03c6''<sub>''n'' \u2212 1</sub>}} is {{math|[0, 2\u03c0)}}. The spherical volume element is:\n:<math>dV = r^{n-1}\\sin^{n-2}(\\varphi_1)\\sin^{n-3}(\\varphi_2) \\cdots \\sin(\\varphi_{n-2})\\,dr\\,d\\varphi_1\\,d\\varphi_2 \\cdots d\\varphi_{n-1},</math>\nand the volume is the integral of this quantity over {{math|''r''}} between 0 and {{math|''R''}} and all possible angles:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\int_0^R \\int_0^\\pi \\cdots \\int_0^{2\\pi} r^{n-1}\\sin^{n-2}(\\varphi_1) \\cdots \\sin(\\varphi_{n-2})\\,d\\varphi_{n-1} \\cdots d\\varphi_1\\,dr.</math>\nEach of the factors in the integrand depends on only a single variable, and therefore the iterated integral can be written as a product of integrals:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\left(\\int_0^R r^{n-1}\\,dr\\right)\\left(\\int_0^\\pi \\sin^{n-2}(\\varphi_1)\\,d\\varphi_1\\right)\\cdots\\left(\\int_0^{2\\pi} d\\varphi_{n-1}\\right).</math>\nThe integral over the radius is {{math|''{{sfrac|R<sup>n</sup>|n}}''}}. The intervals of integration on the angular coordinates can, by symmetry, be changed to {{math|[0, {{sfrac|\u03c0|2}}]}}:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\frac{R^n}{n} \\left(2\\int_0^\\frac{\\pi}{2} \\sin^{n-2}(\\varphi_1)\\,d\\varphi_1\\right) \\cdots \\left(4\\int_0^\\frac{\\pi}{2} d\\varphi_{n-1}\\right).</math>\nEach of the remaining integrals is now a particular value of the beta function:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\frac{R^n}{n} \\Beta\\left(\\frac{n-1}{2}, \\frac12\\right) \\Beta\\left(\\frac{n-2}{2}, \\frac12\\right) \\cdots \\Beta\\left(1, \\frac12\\right) \\cdot 2\\Beta\\left(\\frac12, \\frac12\\right).</math>\nThe beta functions can be rewritten in terms of gamma functions:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\frac{R^n}{n} \\frac{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n-1}{2}\\right)\\Gamma\\left(\\frac12\\right)}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)} \\frac{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n-2}{2}\\right)\\Gamma\\left(\\frac12\\right)}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n - 1}{2}\\right)} \\cdots \\frac{\\Gamma\\left(1\\right)\\Gamma\\left(\\frac12\\right)}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac32\\right)} \\cdot 2 \\frac{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac12\\right)\\Gamma\\left(\\frac12\\right)}{\\Gamma\\left(1\\right)}.</math>\nThis product telescopes. Combining this with the values {{math|\u0393({{sfrac|1|2}}) {{=}} {{sqrt|\u03c0}}}} and {{math|\u0393(1) {{=}} 1}} and the functional equation {{math|''z''\u0393(''z'') {{=}} \u0393(''z'' + 1)}} leads to:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\frac{2\\pi^\\frac{n}{2}R^n}{n\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)} = \\frac{\\pi^\\frac{n}{2}R^n}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2} + 1\\right)}.</math>\n\n=== Gaussian integrals ===\nThe volume formula can be proven directly using [[Gaussian integral]]s. Consider the function:\n:<math>f(x_1, \\ldots, x_n) = \\exp\\left(-\\tfrac12 \\sum_{i=1}^n x_i^2\\right).</math>\nThis function is both rotationally invariant and a product of functions of one variable each. Using the fact that it is a product and the formula for the Gaussian integral gives:\n:<math>\\int_{\\mathbf{R}^n} f \\,dV = \\prod_{i=1}^n \\left(\\int_{-\\infty}^\\infty \\exp\\left(-\\tfrac12 x_i^2\\right)\\,dx_i\\right) = (2\\pi)^\\frac{n}{2},</math>\nwhere {{math|''dV''}} is the {{math|''n''}}-dimensional volume element. Using rotational invariance, the same integral can be computed in spherical coordinates:\n:<math>\\int_{\\mathbf{R}^n} f \\,dV = \\int_0^\\infty \\int_{S^{n-1}(r)} \\exp\\left(-\\tfrac12 r^2\\right) \\,dA\\,dr,</math>\nwhere {{math|''S''<sup>''n'' \u2212 1</sup>(''r'')}} is an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-sphere of radius {{math|''r''}} and {{math|''dA''}} is the area element (equivalently, the {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-dimensional volume element). The surface area of the sphere satisfies a proportionality equation similar to the one for the volume of a ball: If {{math|''A''<sub>''n'' \u2212 1</sub>(''r'')}} is the surface area of an {{math|(''n'' \u2212 1)}}-sphere of radius {{math|''r''}}, then:\n:<math>A_{n-1}(r) = r^{n-1} A_{n-1}(1).</math>\nApplying this to the above integral gives the expression:\n:<math>A_{n-1}(1) \\int_0^\\infty \\exp\\left(-\\tfrac12 r^2\\right)\\,r^{n-1}\\,dr.</math>\nBy substituting {{math|''t'' {{=}} {{sfrac|''r''<sup>2</sup>|2}}}}, the expression is transformed into:\n:<math>A_{n-1}(1) 2^\\frac{n-2}{2} \\int_0^\\infty e^{-t} t^\\frac{n-2}{2}\\,dt.</math>\nThis is the gamma function evaluated at {{math|{{sfrac|''n''|2}}}}.\n\nCombining the two integrations shows that:\n:<math>A_{n-1}(1) = \\frac{2\\pi^\\frac{n}{2}}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)}.</math>\nTo derive the volume of an {{math|''n''}}-ball of radius {{math|''R''}} from this formula, integrate the surface area of a sphere of radius {{math|''r''}} for {{math|0 \u2264 ''r'' \u2264 ''R''}} and apply the functional equation {{math|''z''\u0393(''z'') {{=}} \u0393(''z'' + 1)}}:\n:<math>V_n(R) = \\int_0^R \\frac{2\\pi^\\frac{n}{2}}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)} \\,r^{n-1}\\,dr = \\frac{2\\pi^\\frac{n}{2}}{n\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)}R^n = \\frac{\\pi^\\frac{n}{2}}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{2} + 1\\right)}R^n.</math>\n\n=== Geometric proof ===\n\nThe relations <math display=\"inline\">V_{n+1}(R) = \\frac{R}{n+1}A_n(R)</math> and <math>A_{n+1}(R) = (2\\pi R)V_n(R)</math> and thus the volumes of ''n''-balls and areas of ''n''-spheres can also be derived geometrically.  As noted above, because a ball of radius <math>R</math> is obtained from a unit ball <math>B_n</math> by rescaling all directions in <math>R</math> times, <math>V_n(R)</math> is proportional to <math>R^n</math>, which implies <math display=\"inline\">\\frac{dV_n(R)}{dR} = \\frac{n}{R} V_n(R)</math>.  Also, <math display=\"inline\">A_{n-1}(R) = \\frac{dV_n(R)}{dR}</math> because a ball is a union of concentric spheres and increasing radius by ''\u03b5'' corresponds to a shell of thickness ''\u03b5''.  Thus, <math display=\"inline\">V_{n}(R) = \\frac{R}{n}A_{n-1}(R)</math>; equivalently, <math display=\"inline\">V_{n+1}(R) = \\frac{R}{n+1}A_n(R)</math>.\n\n<math>A_{n+1}(R) = (2\\pi R)V_n(R)</math> follows from existence of a volume-preserving bijection between the unit sphere <math>S_{n+1}</math> and <math> S_1 \\times B_n</math>:\n: <math>(x,y,\\vec{z}) \\rarr \\left(\\frac{x}{\\sqrt{x^2+y^2}},\\frac{y}{\\sqrt{x^2+y^2}},\\vec{z}\\right)</math>\n(<math>\\vec{z}</math> is an ''n''-tuple; <math>|(x,y,\\vec{z})|=1</math>; we are ignoring sets of measure 0).  Volume is preserved because at each point, the difference from [[isometry]] is a stretching in the ''xy'' plane (in <math display=\"inline\">1/\\sqrt{x^2+y^2}</math> times in the direction of constant <math>x^2+y^2</math>) that exactly matches the compression in the direction of the [[gradient]] of <math>|\\vec{z}|</math> on <math>S_n</math> (the relevant angles being equal).  For <math>S_2</math>, a similar argument was originally made by [[Archimedes]] in [[On the Sphere and Cylinder]].\n\n== Balls in {{math|''L''{{isup|''p''}}}} norms ==\nThere are also explicit expressions for the volumes of balls in [[Lp space|{{math|''L''{{isup|''p''}}}} norm]]s. The {{math|''L''{{isup|''p''}}}} norm of the vector {{math|''x'' {{=}} (''x''<sub>1</sub>, \u2026, ''x''<sub>''n''</sub>)}} in {{math|'''R'''<sup>''n''</sup>}} is:\n:<math>\\left(\\sum_{i=1}^n | x_i |^p \\right)^\\frac{1}{p},</math>\nand an {{math|''L''{{isup|''p''}}}} ball is the set of all vectors whose {{math|''L''{{isup|''p''}}}} norm is less than or equal to a fixed number called the radius of the ball. The case {{math|''p'' {{=}} 2}} is the standard Euclidean distance function, but other values of {{math|''p''}} occur in diverse contexts such as [[information theory]], [[coding theory]], and [[dimensional regularization]].\n\nThe volume of an {{math|''L''{{isup|''p''}}}} ball of radius {{math|''R''}} is:\n:<math>V^p_n(R) = \\frac{\\left(2\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{1}{p} + 1\\right)R\\right)^n}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{p} + 1\\right)}.</math>\nThese volumes satisfy a recurrence relation similar to the one dimension recurrence for {{math|''p'' {{=}} 2}}:\n:<math>V^p_n(R) = \\left(2\\Gamma\\left(\\tfrac{1}{p} + 1\\right) R\\right) \\frac{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n-1}{p} + 1\\right)}{\\Gamma\\left(\\frac{n}{p} + 1\\right)} V^p_{n-1}(R).</math>\nFor {{math|''p'' {{=}} 2}}, one recovers the recurrence for the volume of a Euclidean ball because {{math|2\u0393({{sfrac|3|2}}) {{=}} {{sqrt|\u03c0}}}}.\n\nFor example, in the cases {{math|''p'' {{=}} 1}} and {{math|''p'' {{=}} \u221e}}, the volumes are:\n:<math>\\begin{align} V^1_n(R) &= \\frac{2^n}{n!}R^n, \\\\ V^\\infty_n(R) &= (2R)^n. \\end{align}</math>\nThese agree with elementary calculations of the volumes of [[cross-polytope]]s and [[hypercubes]].\n\n=== Relation with surface area ===\nFor most values of {{math|''p''}}, the surface area, <math>A_n^p(R)</math>, of an {{math|''L''{{isup|''p''}}}} sphere of radius {{math|''R''}} (the boundary of an {{math|''L''{{isup|''p''}}}} ball of radius {{math|''R''}}) cannot be calculated by differentiating the volume of an {{math|''L''{{isup|''p''}}}} ball with respect to its radius. While the volume can be expressed as an integral over the surface areas using the [[coarea formula]], the coarea formula contains a correction factor that accounts for how the {{math|''p''}}-norm varies from point to point. For {{math|''p'' {{=}} 2}} and {{math|''p'' {{=}} \u221e}}, this factor is one. However, if {{math|''p'' {{=}} 1}} then the correction factor is {{math|{{sqrt|''n''}}}}: the surface area of an {{math|''L''<sup>1</sup>}} sphere of radius {{math|''R''}} in {{math|'''R'''<sup>''n''</sup>}} is {{math|{{sqrt|''n''}}}} times the derivative of the volume of an {{math|''L''<sup>1</sup>}} ball.  This can be seen most simply by applying the [[divergence theorem]] to the vector field {{math|'''F'''(x) {{=}} x}} to get\n\n:<math>nV^1_n(R) = </math>{{oiint\n| preintegral = <math>\\iiint_V\\left(\\mathbf{\\nabla}\\cdot\\mathbf{F}\\right)\\,dV=</math>\n| intsubscpt = <math>\\scriptstyle S</math>\n| integrand = <math>(\\mathbf{F}\\cdot\\mathbf{n})\\,dS </math>\n}} <math> = </math> {{oiint\n| intsubscpt = <math>\\scriptstyle S</math>\n| integrand = <math>\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{n}}(|x_1|+\\cdots+|x_n|)\\,dS </math>\n}}  <math> = \\frac{R}{\\sqrt{n}} </math>{{oiint\n| intsubscpt = <math>\\scriptstyle S</math>\n| integrand = <math>\\,dS </math>\n}} <math> = \\frac{R}{\\sqrt{n}} A^1_n(R) </math>.\nFor other values of {{math|''p''}}, the constant is a complicated integral.\n\n=== Generalizations ===\nThe volume formula can be generalized even further. For positive real numbers {{math|''p''<sub>1</sub>, \u2026, ''p''<sub>''n''</sub>}}, define the unit {{math|(''p''<sub>1</sub>, \u2026, ''p''<sub>''n''</sub>)}} ball to be:\n:<math>B_{p_1, \\ldots, p_n} = \\left\\{ x = (x_1, \\ldots, x_n) \\in \\mathbf{R}^n : \\vert x_1 \\vert^{p_1} + \\cdots + \\vert x_n \\vert^{p_n} \\le 1 \\right\\}.</math>\nThe volume of this ball has been known since the time of Dirichlet:<ref>{{cite journal|last=Dirichlet|first=P. G. Lejeune|title=Sur une nouvelle m\u00e9thode pour la d\u00e9termination des int\u00e9grales multiples|trans-title=On a novel method for determining multiple integrals|journal=Journal de Math\u00e9matiques Pures et Appliqu\u00e9es|volume=4|date=1839|pages=164\u2013168}}</ref>\n:<math>V(B_{p_1, \\ldots, p_n}) = 2^n \\frac{\\Gamma\\left(1 + \\frac{1}{p_1}\\right) \\cdots \\Gamma\\left(1 + \\frac{1}{p_n}\\right)}{\\Gamma\\left(1 + \\frac{1}{p_1} + \\cdots + \\frac{1}{p_n}\\right)}.</math>\n\n==See also==\n* [[n-sphere|{{math|''n''}}-sphere]]\n* [[Sphere packing]]\n* [[Hamming bound]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.brouty.fr/Maths/sphere.html Derivation in hyperspherical coordinates] {{in lang|fr}}\n* [http://mathworld.wolfram.com/Hypersphere.html Hypersphere] on Wolfram MathWorld\n* [http://www.mathreference.com/ca-int,hsp.html Volume of the Hypersphere] at Math Reference\n\n[[Category:Multi-dimensional geometry]]\n", "name_user": "Jmacwiki", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBalls in {{math|L{{isup|p}}}} norms:Names", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume_of_an_n-ball"}
{"title_page": "Chambal Expressway", "text_new": "{{infobox road\n|header_type=UC\n|country=IND\n|name = Chambal Expressway\n|map=\n|map_notes=\n|length_km= 185\n|direction_a= West\n|direction_b= East\n|terminus_a= [[Sheopur]]\n|junction= [[Morena]], [[Shampur]], [[Ater]] & [[Gohad]]\n|terminus_b= [[Etawah]]\n|formed= \n|state= Madhya Pradesh\n|maint=\n}}\n\n'''Chambal Expressway''' is a proposed eight-lane [[Expressways in India|expressway]] in the state of [[Madhya Pradesh]]. The proposed highway will connect the historic towns of [[Kota, Rajasthan|kota]] in Rajasthan to [[Etawah]] in [[Uttar Pradesh]] alongside of [[Chambal River]] which will cover [[sheopur]] [[Morena]], [[Shampur]], [[Ater]] and [[Gohad]] .<ref>{{cite web |url = http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bhopal/centre-approves-chambal-narmada-expressways-in-mp/articleshow/56901474.cms |title = Centre approves Chambal, Narmada Expressways in MP  |work = Times of India }}</ref> The highways measures 185 km will connected Madhya Pradesh with Uttar Pradesh.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bhopal/govt-takes-up-narmada-chambal-expressway-work-on-priority/articleshow/56943183.cms |title = Government takes up Narmada, Chambal Expressway work on priority  |work = Times of India }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.freepressjournal.in/bhopal/bhopal-nitin-gadkari-gifts-narmada-chambal-expressways/1011344 |title = Bhopal: Nitin Gadkari gifts Narmada, Chambal Expressways  |work = Free Press Journal }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.livemint.com/Politics/72KkQlzP0mENy69oUCxp5J/We-have-the-funds-the-target-is-to-change-mindset-Nitin-Ga.html |title = We have the funds, the target is to change mindset: Nitin Gadkari |first = Jyotika |last = Sood |date = 2 February 2017 |work = LiveMint.com }}</ref>\n\n==Status updates==\n* '''Dec 2018:''' Detailed Project Report (DPR) to be ready by February 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/rajasthan/barmer/news/chambal-expressway-will-be-ready-by-february-if-the-coordination-of-the-center-from-the-dpr-mp-and-rajasthan-will-be-approved-soon-064530-3501466.html|title=DPR is expected to be ready by February}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Proposed expressways in India]]\n[[Category:Transport in Madhya Pradesh]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox road\n|header_type=UC\n|country=IND\n|name = Chambal Expressway\n|map=\n|map_notes=\n|length_km= 185\n|direction_a= West\n|direction_b= East\n|terminus_a= [[Sheopur]]\n|junction= [[Morena]], [[Shampur]], [[Ater]] & [[Gohad]]\n|terminus_b= [[Etawah]]\n|formed= \n|state= Madhya Pradesh\n|maint=\n}}\n\n'''Chambal Expressway''' is a proposed eight-lane [[Expressways in India|expressway]] in the state of [[Madhya Pradesh]]. The proposed highway will connect the historic towns of [[kota]] in Rajasthan to [[Etawah]] in [[Uttar Pradesh]] alongside of [[Chambal River]] which will cover [[sheopur]] [[Morena]], [[Shampur]], [[Ater]] and [[Gohad]] .<ref>{{cite web |url = http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bhopal/centre-approves-chambal-narmada-expressways-in-mp/articleshow/56901474.cms |title = Centre approves Chambal, Narmada Expressways in MP  |work = Times of India }}</ref> The highways measures 185 km will connected Madhya Pradesh with Uttar Pradesh.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bhopal/govt-takes-up-narmada-chambal-expressway-work-on-priority/articleshow/56943183.cms |title = Government takes up Narmada, Chambal Expressway work on priority  |work = Times of India }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.freepressjournal.in/bhopal/bhopal-nitin-gadkari-gifts-narmada-chambal-expressways/1011344 |title = Bhopal: Nitin Gadkari gifts Narmada, Chambal Expressways  |work = Free Press Journal }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.livemint.com/Politics/72KkQlzP0mENy69oUCxp5J/We-have-the-funds-the-target-is-to-change-mindset-Nitin-Ga.html |title = We have the funds, the target is to change mindset: Nitin Gadkari |first = Jyotika |last = Sood |date = 2 February 2017 |work = LiveMint.com }}</ref>\n\n==Status updates==\n* '''Dec 2018:''' Detailed Project Report (DPR) to be ready by February 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/rajasthan/barmer/news/chambal-expressway-will-be-ready-by-february-if-the-coordination-of-the-center-from-the-dpr-mp-and-rajasthan-will-be-approved-soon-064530-3501466.html|title=DPR is expected to be ready by February}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Proposed expressways in India]]\n[[Category:Transport in Madhya Pradesh]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toKota(link changed toKota, Rajasthan) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chambal_Expressway"}
{"title_page": "Faf de Klerk", "text_new": "{{short description|South African rugby union player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography\n|           name = Faf de Klerk\n|          image = Faf de Klerk aka Charlie Rod \n|     image_size = 200px\n|        caption = Faf de Klerk playing for Sale Sharks, 2017\n|       fullname = Fran\u00e7ois de Klerk\n|     birth_date = {{birth date and age|1991|10|19|df=y}}\n|    birth_place = [[Mbombela]], [[South Africa]]\n|         height = {{height|m=1.72}}\n|         weight = {{cvt|88|kg|lb}}\n|     occupation = \n|         school = [[Ho\u00ebrskool Waterkloof]], [[Pretoria]]\n|     university = \n|      relatives = \n|       position = [[Scrum-half (rugby union)|Scrum-half]]\n|    currentclub = [[Sale Sharks]]\n|    youthyears1 = 2007\u20132009\n|    youthclubs1 = {{Rut Blue Bulls}}\n|    youthyears2 = 2010\u20132011\n|    youthclubs2 = {{Rut Golden Lions}}\n|         years1 = 2012\u20132015\n|         clubs1 = {{Rut Pumas}}\n|          apps1 = 56\n|        points1 = 20\n|         years2 = 2014\u20132017\n|         clubs2 = {{Rut Lions}}\n|          apps2 = 65\n|        points2 = 72\n|         years3 = 2016\n|         clubs3 = {{Rut Golden Lions}}\n|          apps3 = 1\n|        points3 = 0\n|         years4 = 2017\n|         clubs4 = {{Rut Golden Lions XV}}\n|          apps4 = 2\n|        points4 = 0\n|         years5 = 2017\u2013present\n|         clubs5 = [[Sale Sharks]]\n|          apps5 = 42\n|        points5 = 136\n|      repyears1 = 2016\u2013present\n|       repteam1 = {{nrut|South Africa}}\n|       repcaps1 = 30\n|     reppoints1 = 20\n|     clubupdate = 23 March 2020\n|      repupdate = 16 November 2019\n}}\n'''Fran\u00e7ois 'Faf' de Klerk''' (born 19 October 1991 in [[Nelspruit]]) is a [[South Africa]]n professional [[rugby union]] player. He plays as a [[Rugby union positions#Scrum-half|scrum-half]] for [[Sale Sharks]] in the [[English Premiership (rugby union)|English Premiership]] and for the [[South Africa national rugby union team|South Africa national team]], He was a member of the South Africa team that won the [[2019 Rugby World Cup]].\n\n==Pre Professional Career==\n\nDe Klerk played rugby at [[Ho\u00ebrskool Waterkloof]] in [[Pretoria]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/faf-de-klerk-five-quick-facts/|title=Faf de Klerk: Five quick facts about the Springbok superstar|date=26 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\n\nDe Klerk was included in the {{Rut Lions}} squad for the [[2014 Super Rugby season]]<ref name=\"2014 Lions Super Rugby squad\">{{cite press release|url=http://www.lionsrugby.co.za/lionsnews.aspx?item=4128&multiid=1010&archive=0 |title=2014 Lions Super Rugby squad |publisher=Lions |date=11 February 2014 |access-date=11 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222152732/http://www.lionsrugby.co.za/lionsnews.aspx?item=4128&multiid=1010&archive=0 |archive-date=22 February 2014 |df= }}</ref> and made his debut in a 21\u201320 victory over the {{Rut Cheetahs}} in [[Bloemfontein]].<ref name=\"Match Centre: Cheetahs v Lions\">{{cite web | url=http://www.sanzarrugby.com/superrugby/match-centre/?season=2014&competition=205&match=514011 | title=Match Centre: Cheetahs v Lions | publisher=SANZAR | date=15 February 2014 | accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Toyota Cheetahs 20-21 Lions\">{{SA Rugby Match Centre | id=113674 | homeid=16144 | awayid=16154 | leagueid=1574 | hometeam=Toyota Cheetahs | homescore=20 | awayscore=21 | awayteam=Lions | matchdate=15 February 2014 | date=5 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe joined the{{Rut Golden Lions}} Currie Cup team for the 2016 season.<ref name=\"De Klerk and Fourie sign with Lions Rugby\">{{cite press release | url=http://www.lionsrugby.co.za/lionsnews.aspx?item=4128&multiid=1363&archive=0 | title=De Klerk and Fourie sign with Lions Rugby | publisher=Golden Lions | date=3 July 2015 | access-date=3 July 2015 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150704000948/http://www.lionsrugby.co.za/lionsnews.aspx?item=4128&multiid=1363&archive=0 | archive-date=4 July 2015 | df= }}</ref>\n\nHe joined [[English Premiership (rugby union)|English Premiership]] side [[Sale Sharks]] prior to the 2017\u201318 season on a three-year contract.<ref name=\"Sale Sharks announce signing of South Africa international Faf de Klerk\">{{cite press release | url=http://www.salesharks.com/news/5041.php | title=Sale Sharks announce signing of South Africa international Faf de Klerk | publisher=Sale Sharks | date=8 May 2017 | access-date=8 May 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508074133/http://www.salesharks.com/news/5041.php | archive-date=8 May 2017 | url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2018, the club announced that De Klerk signed a contract extension until 2023.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/sport/rugby/2019-01-01-faf-de-klerk-commits-to-sale-sharks-until-2023/|accessdate=6 November 2019|title=Faf de Klerk commits to Sale Sharks until 2023|date=1 January 2019|publisher=BusinessLIVE}}</ref>\n\n==International Career ==\n\nDe Klerk was rewarded for his Super Rugby form when he was selected by the recently appointed Springbok coach [[Allister Coetzee]] in {{nrut|South Africa}}\u2019s 31-man squad for their [[2016 mid-year rugby union internationals|2016 three-test match series]] against {{nrut|Ireland}}<ref name=\"Squad of 31 ushers in new era of Springbok rugby\">{{SA Rugby Article | id=3548594 | leagueid=2724 | title=Squad of 31 ushers in new era of Springbok rugby | date=28 May 2016 | accessdate=31 May 2016 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531064100/http://www.sarugby.co.za/article.aspx?id=3548594&leagueid=2724 | archivedate=31 May 2016}}</ref> and made his test debut as the starting scrum-half in the opening test at [[Newlands Stadium]]. In a tightly-fought series, Ireland won the first test 26\u221220, but the Springboks fought back to clinch the series, winning 32\u221226 in [[Johannesburg]] and 19\u221213 in [[Port Elizabeth]].\n\nAfter signing for Sale Sharks in 2017, De Klerk was ineligible to represent the Springboks due to having fewer than 30 caps.<ref name=guardian>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/oct/23/faf-de-klerk-moving-to-england-blessing-sale-south-africa-rugby-world-cup|title=Faf de Klerk: 'I guess moving to England was a blessing in disguise'|date=24 October 2019|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|first=Paul|last=Rees}}</ref> However, after this selection criterion was abolished in 2018, new Springbok coach [[Rassie Erasmus]] recalled De Klerk to the team for the [[2018 mid-year rugby union internationals|2018 three-test match series]] against {{nrut|England}}.<ref name=guardian/>\n\nHe was an important member of South Africa's victorious [[2019 Rugby Championship]] campaign and was duly selected for the [[2019 Rugby World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/50205789 | title=England v South Africa: Can Faf de Klerk be stopped in World Cup final? | date=29 October 2019 | via=www.bbc.co.uk | work=BBC Sport}}</ref> In their 20 October quarter-final match against Japan, he was named Player of the Match.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rugbyworldcup.com/match/quarter-final-4 | title=Japan v South Africa - Catch up on all the action - Rugby World Cup 2019 | work=World Rugby | date=20 October 2019 | accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref> He was a key player for South Africa's World Cup victory, being named as the starting scrum-half in two of their pool matches, as well as all their play-off games. He scored a try in their quarter-final win over {{nrut|Japan}}.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://sarugby.online/tournaments/match/id/5504 | title=Match 44, Quarter Final | work=South African Rugby Union | date=20 October 2019 | accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref> \nFaf was once again included as the starting scrum-half against England in the 2019 [[Rugby World Cup Final]], which saw South Africa beating England 32-12. The [[Springboks]] lifting the [[Webb Ellis Cup]] for the third time.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{SA Rugby Profile}}\n* [http://www.itsrugby.co.uk/player_25597.html itsrugby.co.uk profile]\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/50519816 Interview with BBC Sport (November 2019)]\n\n{{South Africa rugby union squad}}\n{{Sale Sharks squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Squads\n|list1 = \n{{South Africa Squad 2019 Rugby World Cup}}\n{{2014 Pumas Vodacom Cup squad}}\n{{2013 Pumas Currie Cup squad}}\n{{2013 Pumas Vodacom Cup squad}}\n{{2012 Pumas Currie Cup squad}}\n{{2012 Pumas Vodacom Cup squad}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:De Klerk, Francois}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Afrikaner people]]\n[[Category:South African rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Rugby union scrum-halves]]\n[[Category:People from Mbombela]]\n[[Category:Pumas (rugby team) players]]\n[[Category:Lions (Super Rugby) players]]\n[[Category:South Africa international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African rugby union player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography\n|           name = Faf de Klerk\n|          image = Faf de Klerk.jpg\n|     image_size = 200px\n|        caption = Faf de Klerk playing for Sale Sharks, 2017\n|       fullname = Fran\u00e7ois de Klerk\n|     birth_date = {{birth date and age|1991|10|19|df=y}}\n|    birth_place = [[Mbombela]], [[South Africa]]\n|         height = {{height|m=1.72}}\n|         weight = {{cvt|88|kg|lb}}\n|     occupation = \n|         school = [[Ho\u00ebrskool Waterkloof]], [[Pretoria]]\n|     university = \n|      relatives = \n|       position = [[Scrum-half (rugby union)|Scrum-half]]\n|    currentclub = [[Sale Sharks]]\n|    youthyears1 = 2007\u20132009\n|    youthclubs1 = {{Rut Blue Bulls}}\n|    youthyears2 = 2010\u20132011\n|    youthclubs2 = {{Rut Golden Lions}}\n|         years1 = 2012\u20132015\n|         clubs1 = {{Rut Pumas}}\n|          apps1 = 56\n|        points1 = 20\n|         years2 = 2014\u20132017\n|         clubs2 = {{Rut Lions}}\n|          apps2 = 65\n|        points2 = 72\n|         years3 = 2016\n|         clubs3 = {{Rut Golden Lions}}\n|          apps3 = 1\n|        points3 = 0\n|         years4 = 2017\n|         clubs4 = {{Rut Golden Lions XV}}\n|          apps4 = 2\n|        points4 = 0\n|         years5 = 2017\u2013present\n|         clubs5 = [[Sale Sharks]]\n|          apps5 = 42\n|        points5 = 136\n|      repyears1 = 2016\u2013present\n|       repteam1 = {{nrut|South Africa}}\n|       repcaps1 = 30\n|     reppoints1 = 20\n|     clubupdate = 23 March 2020\n|      repupdate = 16 November 2019\n}}\n'''Fran\u00e7ois 'Faf' de Klerk''' (born 19 October 1991 in [[Nelspruit]]) is a [[South Africa]]n professional [[rugby union]] player. He plays as a [[Rugby union positions#Scrum-half|scrum-half]] for [[Sale Sharks]] in the [[English Premiership (rugby union)|English Premiership]] and for the [[South Africa national rugby union team|South Africa national team]], He was a member of the South Africa team that won the [[2019 Rugby World Cup]].\n\n==Pre Professional Career==\n\nDe Klerk played rugby at [[Ho\u00ebrskool Waterkloof]] in [[Pretoria]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/faf-de-klerk-five-quick-facts/|title=Faf de Klerk: Five quick facts about the Springbok superstar|date=26 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\n\nDe Klerk was included in the {{Rut Lions}} squad for the [[2014 Super Rugby season]]<ref name=\"2014 Lions Super Rugby squad\">{{cite press release|url=http://www.lionsrugby.co.za/lionsnews.aspx?item=4128&multiid=1010&archive=0 |title=2014 Lions Super Rugby squad |publisher=Lions |date=11 February 2014 |access-date=11 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222152732/http://www.lionsrugby.co.za/lionsnews.aspx?item=4128&multiid=1010&archive=0 |archive-date=22 February 2014 |df= }}</ref> and made his debut in a 21\u201320 victory over the {{Rut Cheetahs}} in [[Bloemfontein]].<ref name=\"Match Centre: Cheetahs v Lions\">{{cite web | url=http://www.sanzarrugby.com/superrugby/match-centre/?season=2014&competition=205&match=514011 | title=Match Centre: Cheetahs v Lions | publisher=SANZAR | date=15 February 2014 | accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Toyota Cheetahs 20-21 Lions\">{{SA Rugby Match Centre | id=113674 | homeid=16144 | awayid=16154 | leagueid=1574 | hometeam=Toyota Cheetahs | homescore=20 | awayscore=21 | awayteam=Lions | matchdate=15 February 2014 | date=5 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe joined the{{Rut Golden Lions}} Currie Cup team for the 2016 season.<ref name=\"De Klerk and Fourie sign with Lions Rugby\">{{cite press release | url=http://www.lionsrugby.co.za/lionsnews.aspx?item=4128&multiid=1363&archive=0 | title=De Klerk and Fourie sign with Lions Rugby | publisher=Golden Lions | date=3 July 2015 | access-date=3 July 2015 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150704000948/http://www.lionsrugby.co.za/lionsnews.aspx?item=4128&multiid=1363&archive=0 | archive-date=4 July 2015 | df= }}</ref>\n\nHe joined [[English Premiership (rugby union)|English Premiership]] side [[Sale Sharks]] prior to the 2017\u201318 season on a three-year contract.<ref name=\"Sale Sharks announce signing of South Africa international Faf de Klerk\">{{cite press release | url=http://www.salesharks.com/news/5041.php | title=Sale Sharks announce signing of South Africa international Faf de Klerk | publisher=Sale Sharks | date=8 May 2017 | access-date=8 May 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508074133/http://www.salesharks.com/news/5041.php | archive-date=8 May 2017 | url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2018, the club announced that De Klerk signed a contract extension until 2023.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/sport/rugby/2019-01-01-faf-de-klerk-commits-to-sale-sharks-until-2023/|accessdate=6 November 2019|title=Faf de Klerk commits to Sale Sharks until 2023|date=1 January 2019|publisher=BusinessLIVE}}</ref>\n\n==International Career ==\n\nDe Klerk was rewarded for his Super Rugby form when he was selected by the recently appointed Springbok coach [[Allister Coetzee]] in {{nrut|South Africa}}\u2019s 31-man squad for their [[2016 mid-year rugby union internationals|2016 three-test match series]] against {{nrut|Ireland}}<ref name=\"Squad of 31 ushers in new era of Springbok rugby\">{{SA Rugby Article | id=3548594 | leagueid=2724 | title=Squad of 31 ushers in new era of Springbok rugby | date=28 May 2016 | accessdate=31 May 2016 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531064100/http://www.sarugby.co.za/article.aspx?id=3548594&leagueid=2724 | archivedate=31 May 2016}}</ref> and made his test debut as the starting scrum-half in the opening test at [[Newlands Stadium]]. In a tightly-fought series, Ireland won the first test 26\u221220, but the Springboks fought back to clinch the series, winning 32\u221226 in [[Johannesburg]] and 19\u221213 in [[Port Elizabeth]].\n\nAfter signing for Sale Sharks in 2017, De Klerk was ineligible to represent the Springboks due to having fewer than 30 caps.<ref name=guardian>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/oct/23/faf-de-klerk-moving-to-england-blessing-sale-south-africa-rugby-world-cup|title=Faf de Klerk: 'I guess moving to England was a blessing in disguise'|date=24 October 2019|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|first=Paul|last=Rees}}</ref> However, after this selection criterion was abolished in 2018, new Springbok coach [[Rassie Erasmus]] recalled De Klerk to the team for the [[2018 mid-year rugby union internationals|2018 three-test match series]] against {{nrut|England}}.<ref name=guardian/>\n\nHe was an important member of South Africa's victorious [[2019 Rugby Championship]] campaign and was duly selected for the [[2019 Rugby World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/50205789 | title=England v South Africa: Can Faf de Klerk be stopped in World Cup final? | date=29 October 2019 | via=www.bbc.co.uk | work=BBC Sport}}</ref> In their 20 October quarter-final match against Japan, he was named Player of the Match.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rugbyworldcup.com/match/quarter-final-4 | title=Japan v South Africa - Catch up on all the action - Rugby World Cup 2019 | work=World Rugby | date=20 October 2019 | accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref> He was a key player for South Africa's World Cup victory, being named as the starting scrum-half in two of their pool matches, as well as all their play-off games. He scored a try in their quarter-final win over {{nrut|Japan}}.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://sarugby.online/tournaments/match/id/5504 | title=Match 44, Quarter Final | work=South African Rugby Union | date=20 October 2019 | accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref> \nFaf was once again included as the starting scrum-half against England in the 2019 [[Rugby World Cup Final]], which saw South Africa beating England 32-12. The [[Springboks]] lifting the [[Webb Ellis Cup]] for the third time.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{SA Rugby Profile}}\n* [http://www.itsrugby.co.uk/player_25597.html itsrugby.co.uk profile]\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/50519816 Interview with BBC Sport (November 2019)]\n\n{{South Africa rugby union squad}}\n{{Sale Sharks squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Squads\n|list1 = \n{{South Africa Squad 2019 Rugby World Cup}}\n{{2014 Pumas Vodacom Cup squad}}\n{{2013 Pumas Currie Cup squad}}\n{{2013 Pumas Vodacom Cup squad}}\n{{2012 Pumas Currie Cup squad}}\n{{2012 Pumas Vodacom Cup squad}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:De Klerk, Francois}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Afrikaner people]]\n[[Category:South African rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Rugby union scrum-halves]]\n[[Category:People from Mbombela]]\n[[Category:Pumas (rugby team) players]]\n[[Category:Lions (Super Rugby) players]]\n[[Category:South Africa international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7d:4473:1600:38d3:b5f:e354:b359", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faf_de_Klerk"}
{"title_page": "K'aayelii", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=February 2017}}\n\n'''Hastii K'aay\u00e9lii''' (''One With Quiver''; {{circa}} 1801\u20131894) was a [[Din\u00e9]] leader.\n\nK'aay\u00e9lii was born around 1801 in Elk Ridge, north of [[Bears Ears]]. His birthplace was near a spring at the head of a canyon. Both were named for him with the corrupted spelling \"Kigalia\".<ref name=\"UHQ\"/>\n\nNorth of the [[San Juan River (Colorado River)|San Juan River]], K'aay\u00e9lii was one of the principal headmen.  He and his followers spent their lives ranging from the [[Henry Mountains]], the [[La Sal Mountains]], the Uncompaghre Plateau in Colorado's Allen Canyon, the [[Abajo Mountains]], and Bears Ears.<ref name=\"UHQ\"/> Like Hashkeneinii, K'aay\u00e9lii had fled from the [[Ute people|Utes]], and brought his people to the Bears Ears area.<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Powell|editor1-first=Allan Kent|title=Utah History Encyclopedia|date=1995|publisher=University of Utah Press|location=Salt Lake City|isbn=978-0-87480-425-6|page=392|edition=2nd}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Edison|first1=Carol A.|title=Willow Stories: Utah Navajo Baskets|date=1996|publisher=Utah Arts Council|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|isbn=978-0-9623975-2-3|page=17}}</ref> They never surrendered and avoided the [[Long Walk of the Navajo|Long Walk]], the forced deportation and ethnic cleansing of the Navajo by the United States government.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Thompson|first1=Jonathan|title=In Utah, the fight for a Bears Ears monument heats up|url=https://www.hcn.org/articles/bears-ears-monument-gets-closer-to-reality|work=High Country News|date=May 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nK'aay\u00e9lii died near [[Montezuma Creek (Utah)|Montezuma Creek]] in 1894 and is buried there.<ref name=\"UHQ\">{{cite journal|last1=Correll|first1=J. Lee|title=Navajo Frontiers in Utah and Troublous Times in Monument Valley|journal=Utah Historical Quarterly|pages=146\u2013147|date=Spring 1971|volume=39|url=http://content.lib.utah.edu/utils/getfile/collection/USHSArchPub/id/6498/filename/6533.pdf}}</ref> Jack Jones, one of his descendants, attempted to reclaim their historical land rights but was denied by the [[United States Department of the Interior|Department of the Interior]]. His Utah descendants' attempts to acquire additional grazing land were denied by the courts in 1961.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Maryboy|first1=Nancy C.|last2=Begay|first2=David|title=Utah's Native Americans|url=http://historytogo.utah.gov/people/ethnic_cultures/the_history_of_utahs_american_indians/chapter7.html|publisher=State of Utah|accessdate=June 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last1=Cuch|first1=Forrest S.|title=A History of Utah's American Indians|date=2003|publisher=Utah State Division of Indian Affairs|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|isbn=978-0-87421-383-6|pages=242, 279, 284}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kaayelii}}\n[[Category:1800s births]]\n[[Category:1894 deaths]]\n[[Category:Navajo leaders]]\n[[Category:People of the American Old West]]\n\n\n{{OldWest-bio-stub}}\n{{NorthAm-native-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=February 2017}}\n\n'''Hastii K'aay\u00e9lii''' (''One With Quiver''; {{circa}} 1801\u20131894) was a [[Din\u00e9]] leader.\n\nK'aay\u00e9lii was born around 1801 in Elk Ridge, north of [[Bears Ears]]. His birthplace was near a spring at the head of a canyon. Both were named for him with the corrupted spelling \"Kigalia\".<ref name=\"UHQ\"/>\n\nNorth of the [[San Juan River (Colorado River)|San Juan River]], K'aay\u00e9lii was one of the principal headmen.  He and his followers spent their lives ranging from the [[Henry Mountains]], the [[La Sal Mountains]], the Uncompaghre Plateau in Colorado's Allen Canyon, the [[Abajo Mountains]], and Bears Ears.<ref name=\"UHQ\"/> Like Hashkeneinii, K'aay\u00e9lii had fled from the [[Ute people|Utes]], and brought his people to the Bears Ears area.<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Powell|editor1-first=Allan Kent|title=Utah History Encyclopedia|date=1995|publisher=University of Utah Press|location=Salt Lake City|isbn=978-0-87480-425-6|page=392|edition=2nd}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Edison|first1=Carol A.|title=Willow Stories: Utah Navajo Baskets|date=1996|publisher=Utah Arts Council|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|isbn=978-0-9623975-2-3|page=17}}</ref> They never surrendered and avoided the [[Long Walk of the Navajo|Long Walk]], the forced deportation and ethnic cleansing of the Navajo by the United States government.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Thompson|first1=Jonathan|title=In Utah, the fight for a Bears Ears monument heats up|url=https://www.hcn.org/articles/bears-ears-monument-gets-closer-to-reality|work=High Country News|date=May 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nK'aay\u00e9lii died near [[Montezuma Creek (San Juan River)|Montezuma Creek]] in 1894 and is buried there.<ref name=\"UHQ\">{{cite journal|last1=Correll|first1=J. Lee|title=Navajo Frontiers in Utah and Troublous Times in Monument Valley|journal=Utah Historical Quarterly|pages=146\u2013147|date=Spring 1971|volume=39|url=http://content.lib.utah.edu/utils/getfile/collection/USHSArchPub/id/6498/filename/6533.pdf}}</ref> Jack Jones, one of his descendants, attempted to reclaim their historical land rights but was denied by the [[United States Department of the Interior|Department of the Interior]]. His Utah descendants' attempts to acquire additional grazing land were denied by the courts in 1961.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Maryboy|first1=Nancy C.|last2=Begay|first2=David|title=Utah's Native Americans|url=http://historytogo.utah.gov/people/ethnic_cultures/the_history_of_utahs_american_indians/chapter7.html|publisher=State of Utah|accessdate=June 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last1=Cuch|first1=Forrest S.|title=A History of Utah's American Indians|date=2003|publisher=Utah State Division of Indian Affairs|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|isbn=978-0-87421-383-6|pages=242, 279, 284}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kaayelii}}\n[[Category:1800s births]]\n[[Category:1894 deaths]]\n[[Category:Navajo leaders]]\n[[Category:People of the American Old West]]\n\n\n{{OldWest-bio-stub}}\n{{NorthAm-native-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "An Errant Knight", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K%27aayelii"}
{"title_page": "Japanese School in Prague", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n| name                    = Japanese School in Prague\n| native_name             = \u30d7\u30e9\u30cf\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821<br>Japonsk\u00e1 \u0161kola v Praze\n| image                   = Praha, \u0158epy, Japonsk\u00e1 \u0161kola (2).jpg\n| caption                 = Entrance\n| address                 = Skuteckeho 1388, 16300 Praha6\n| location                = [[Prague]]\n| country                 = Czech Republic\n| coordinates             = {{Coord|50|4|9.98|N|14|18|42.37|E|display=title}}\n| pushpin_map             = Czech Republic Prague#Czech Republic\n| established             = \n| opened                  = \n| closed                  =\n| type                    = Japanese international school\n| district                = \n| grades                  = \n| superintendent          = \n| principal               = \n| enrollment              = \n| faculty                 = \n| campus_type             = \n| campus_size             = \n| team_name               = \n| newspaper               = \n| colors                  = \n| communities             = \n| feeders                 = \n| website                 = {{URL|jpschool.cz}}\n| footnotes               =\n}}\nThe '''Japanese School in Prague''' ({{lang-cz|'''Japonsk\u00e1 \u0161kola v Praze'''}}, \u30d7\u30e9\u30cf\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821 ''Puraha Nihonjin Gakk\u014d'') is a [[nihonjin gakko|Japanese international school]] in [[\u0158epy]], [[Prague 6|District 6]], [[Prague]], [[Czech Republic]].<ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20070515165733/http://www.jschool.cz/g_gaiyou/index.htm \u5b66\u6821\u306e\u6982\u8981].\" Japanese School in Prague. Retrieved on 23 January 2015. \"Skuteckeho\u30001388,\u300016300 Praha6\" \u2013 [https://web.archive.org/web/20070517164257/http://www.jschool.cz/g_gaiyou/map.htm Map]</ref><ref>\"[http://www.cz.emb-japan.go.jp/ryoji_education.html \u5b50\u5973\u6559\u80b2].\" Embassy of Japan in the Czech Republic. Retrieved on 20 February 2015. \"\u30d7\u30e9\u30cf\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821 \u4f4f\u6240\uff1aSkuteckeho 1388, 163 00 Praha 6\u2013Repy\"</ref> It is attached affiliated with the [[Embassy of Japan in Prague]].<!--[http://www.jpschool.cz/ Home page]. Japanese School in Prague. Retrieved on April 13, 2015. [http://ikh.sakura.ne.jp/jpschool/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/japaneseschool.jpg See banner]-->\n\nThe school opened on April 28, 1980 ([[Sh\u014dwa period|Showa]] 55),<ref name=Profile2001>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20010308064529/http://www.vol.cz/japschool/start.html/sub1.htm \u5b66\u6821\u306e\u6982\u8981]\" (). Japanese School in Prague. March 8, 2001. Retrieved on April 24, 2016. \"Slunna 8 PRAHA 6 Stresovice CR\" and \"\uff13.\u8a2d\u7f6e\u5e74\u6708\u65e5\u3000\u3000\uff11\uff19\uff18\uff10\u5e74\uff08\u662d\u548c\uff15\uff15\u5e74\uff09\uff14\u6708\uff12\uff18\u65e5\u3000\uff1c\u4eca\u5e74\u306f\u958b\u6821\uff12\uff10\u5468\u5e74\u306b\u3042\u305f\u308a\u307e\u3059\uff1e\"</ref> and it had its origins in an educational programme established in 1972.<ref>\u6587\u90e8\u79d1\u5b66\u6642\u5831 \u2013 Issues 1559\u20131570. p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=SvE0AQAAIAAJ 62]. \"\u30d7\u30e9\u30cf\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821\u306f\u3001 1972 \u5e74\u306b\u5728\u30c1\u30f1\u30b3\u65e5\u672c\u56fd\u5927\u4f7f\u9928\u306e\u4e2d\u306b\u88dc\u7fd2\u6388\u696d\u6821\u3068\u3057\u3066\u767a\u8db3\u3057\u3001 1980 \u5e74\u306b\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821\u3068\u3057\u3066\u958b\u6821\u3057\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002\u305d\u306e\u5f8c\u3001\u6821\u820e\u304c\u6570\u56de\u79fb\u8ee2\u3057\u3001 2004 \u5e74\u590f\u304b\u3089\u73fe\u5728\u5730\u306b\u843d\u3061\u7740\u304d\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002 2002 \u5e74\u5ea6\u307e\u3067 25 \u540d\u524d\u5f8c\u3067\u63a8\u79fb\u3092\u3057\u3066\u3044\u305f\u5150\u7ae5\u751f\u5f92\u6570[...]\" \u2013 [https://www.google.com/search?q=Japonsk%C3%A1+%C5%A1kola+v+Praze&btnG=Search+Books&tbm=bks&tbo=1&gw