rts by those affiliated with the school:\n*Sugino, Masahiko (\u6749\u91ce\u3000\u96c5\u5f66; \u524d\u30d7\u30e9\u30cf\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821\u3000\u6559\u982d \u9ad8\u77e5\u770c\u6559\u80b2\u59d4\u54e1\u4f1a\u4e8b\u52d9\u5c40\u751f\u6daf\u5b66\u7fd2\u8ab2\u3000\u8ab2\u9577\u88dc\u4f50). \"[https://www.webcitation.org/6VnuKIDNc?url=http://crie.u-gakugei.ac.jp/report/pdf31/31_27sugino.pdf \u30d7\u30e9\u30cf\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821\u306e\u56fd\u969b\u7406\u89e3\u6559\u80b2]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6VnuKIDNc?url=http://crie.u-gakugei.ac.jp/report/pdf31/31_27sugino.pdf Archive]). [[Tokyo Gakugei University]]. p.&nbsp;108\u2013110.\n*Tanei, Ichir\u014d (\u7a2e\u4e95 \u4e00\u90ce; \u524d\u30d7\u30e9\u30cf\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821\u3000\u6559\u8aed \u5175\u5eab\u770c\u795e\u6238\u5e02\u7acb\u5869\u5c4b\u4e2d\u5b66\u6821\u3000\u6559\u8aed) \"[https://www.webcitation.org/6VnuRKThL?url=http://crie.u-gakugei.ac.jp/report/pdf36/22Tanei.pdf \u30d7\u30e9\u30cf\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821\u3067\u306e\u73fe\u5730\u7406\u89e3\u3068\u5e73\u548c\u5b66\u7fd2]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6VnuRKThL?url=http://crie.u-gakugei.ac.jp/report/pdf36/22Tanei.pdf Archive]). [[Tokyo Gakugei University]]. p.&nbsp;74\u201377.\n\n==External links==\n{{portal|Japan|Czech Republic|Schools}}\n{{Commons category|Japanese school (Prague)}}\n* {{in lang|ja}} [http://www.jpschool.cz/ Japanese School in Prague]\n* {{in lang|ja}} [http://japschool.grhosting.cz/ Japanese School in Prague] (old website)\n* {{in lang|ja}} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.jschool.cz|title=Japanese School in Prague}} (old website)\n* {{in lang|ja}} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.vol.cz/japschool/|title=Japanese School in Prague}} (old website)<!--  referred from http://web.archive.org/web/19990221134328/http://www.naec.go.jp/kaigai/jeurope.html-->\n\n{{International schools in Prague}}\n{{Japanese schools in Europe}}\n\n[[Category:Nihonjin gakk\u014d|Prague]]\n[[Category:Schools in Prague]]\n[[Category:International schools in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Czech Republic\u2013Japan relations]]\n[[Category:1980 establishments in Czechoslovakia]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1980]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n| name                    = Japanese School in Prague\n| native_name             = \u30d7\u30e9\u30cf\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821<br>Japonsk\u00e1 \u0161kola v Praze\n| image                   = Praha, \u0158epy, Japonsk\u00e1 \u0161kola (2).jpg\n| caption                 = Entrance\n| address                 = Skuteckeho 1388, 16300 Praha6\n| location                = [[Prague]]\n| country                 = Czech Republic\n| coordinates             = {{Coord|50|4|9.98|N|14|18|42.37|E|display=title}}\n| pushpin_map             = Czech Republic Prague#Czech Republic\n| established             = \n| opened                  = \n| closed                  =\n| type                    = Japanese international school\n| district                = \n| grades                  = \n| superintendent          = \n| principal               = \n| enrollment              = \n| faculty                 = \n| campus_type             = \n| campus_size             = \n| team_name               = \n| newspaper               = \n| colors                  = \n| communities             = \n| feeders                 = \n| website                 = {{URL|jpschool.cz}}\n| footnotes               =\n}}\nThe '''Japanese School in Prague''' ({{lang-cz|'''Japonsk\u00e1 \u0161kola v Praze'''}}, \u30d7\u30e9\u30cf\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821 ''Puraha Nihonjin Gakk\u014d'') is a [[nihonjin gakko|Japanese international school]] in [[\u0158epy]], [[Prague 6|District 6]], [[Prague]], [[Czech Republic]].<ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20070515165733/http://www.jschool.cz/g_gaiyou/index.htm \u5b66\u6821\u306e\u6982\u8981].\" Japanese School in Prague. Retrieved on 23 January 2015. \"Skuteckeho\u30001388,\u300016300 Praha6\" - [https://web.archive.org/web/20070517164257/http://www.jschool.cz/g_gaiyou/map.htm Map]</ref><ref>\"[http://www.cz.emb-japan.go.jp/ryoji_education.html \u5b50\u5973\u6559\u80b2].\" Embassy of Japan in the Czech Republic. Retrieved on 20 February 2015. \"\u30d7\u30e9\u30cf\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821 \u4f4f\u6240\uff1aSkuteckeho 1388, 163 00 Praha 6\u2013Repy\"</ref> It is attached affiliated with the [[Embassy of Japan in Prague]].<!--[http://www.jpschool.cz/ Home page]. Japanese School in Prague. Retrieved on April 13, 2015. [http://ikh.sakura.ne.jp/jpschool/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/japaneseschool.jpg See banner]-->\n\nThe school opened on April 28, 1980 ([[Sh\u014dwa period|Showa]] 55),<ref name=Profile2001>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20010308064529/http://www.vol.cz/japschool/start.html/sub1.htm \u5b66\u6821\u306e\u6982\u8981]\" (). Japanese School in Prague. March 8, 2001. Retrieved on April 24, 2016. \"Slunna 8 PRAHA 6 Stresovice CR\" and \"\uff13.\u8a2d\u7f6e\u5e74\u6708\u65e5\u3000\u3000\uff11\uff19\uff18\uff10\u5e74\uff08\u662d\u548c\uff15\uff15\u5e74\uff09\uff14\u6708\uff12\uff18\u65e5\u3000\uff1c\u4eca\u5e74\u306f\u958b\u6821\uff12\uff10\u5468\u5e74\u306b\u3042\u305f\u308a\u307e\u3059\uff1e\"</ref> and it had its origins in an educational programme established in 1972.<ref>\u6587\u90e8\u79d1\u5b66\u6642\u5831 - Issues 1559-1570. p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=SvE0AQAAIAAJ&q=%221972+%E5%B9%B4%E3%81%AB%E5%9C%A8%E3%83%81%E3%83%B1%E3%82%B3%E6%97%A5%E6%9C%AC%E5%9B%BD%E5%A4%A7%E4%BD%BF%E9%A4%A8%E3%81%AE%E4%B8%AD%E3%81%AB%E8%A3%9C%E7%BF%92%E6%8E%88%E6%A5%AD%E6%A0%A1%E3%81%A8%E3%81%97%E3%81%A6%E7%99%BA%E8%B6%B3%E3%81%97%22&dq=%221972+%E5%B9%B4%E3%81%AB%E5%9C%A8%E3%83%81%E3%83%B1%E3%82%B3%E6%97%A5%E6%9C%AC%E5%9B%BD%E5%A4%A7%E4%BD%BF%E9%A4%A8%E3%81%AE%E4%B8%AD%E3%81%AB%E8%A3%9C%E7%BF%92%E6%8E%88%E6%A5%AD%E6%A0%A1%E3%81%A8%E3%81%97%E3%81%A6%E7%99%BA%E8%B6%B3%E3%81%97%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=NLHDVP-iHYK4ggTtuoTwDg&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAA 62]. \"\u30d7\u30e9\u30cf\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821\u306f\u3001 1972 \u5e74\u306b\u5728\u30c1\u30f1\u30b3\u65e5\u672c\u56fd\u5927\u4f7f\u9928\u306e\u4e2d\u306b\u88dc\u7fd2\u6388\u696d\u6821\u3068\u3057\u3066\u767a\u8db3\u3057\u3001 1980 \u5e74\u306b\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821\u3068\u3057\u3066\u958b\u6821\u3057\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002\u305d\u306e\u5f8c\u3001\u6821\u820e\u304c\u6570\u56de\u79fb\u8ee2\u3057\u3001 2004 \u5e74\u590f\u304b\u3089\u73fe\u5728\u5730\u306b\u843d\u3061\u7740\u304d\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002 2002 \u5e74\u5ea6\u307e\u3067 25 \u540d\u524d\u5f8c\u3067\u63a8\u79fb\u3092\u3057\u3066\u3044\u305f\u5150\u7ae5\u751f\u5f92\u6570[...]\" - [https://www.google.com/search?q=Japonsk%C3%A1+%C5%A1kola+v+Praze&btnG=Search+Books&tbm=bks&tbo=1&gws_rd=ssl#tbm=bks&q=%221972+%E5%B9%B4%E3%81%AB%E5%9C%A8%E3%83%81%E3%83%B1%E3%82%B3%E6%97%A5%E6%9C%AC%E5%9B%BD%E5%A4%A7%E4%BD%BF%E9%A4%A8%E3%81%AE%E4%B8%AD%E3%81%AB%E8%A3%9C%E7%BF%92%E6%8E%88%E6%A5%AD%E6%A0%A1%E3%81%A8%E3%81%97%E3%81%A6%E7%99%BA%E8%B6%B3%E3%81%97%22 See search page]</ref> It was previously at Slunna 8.<ref name=Profile2001/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* \u6728\u5ead \u548c\u96c4 (\u798f\u751f\u5e02\u7acb\u798f\u751f\u7b2c\u4e09\u5c0f\u5b66\u6821). \"[http://ci.nii.ac.jp/els/110007150037.pdf?id=ART0009097381&type=pdf&lang=en&host=cinii&order_no=&ppv_type=0&lang_sw=&no=1422026735&cp= \u30d7\u30e9\u30cf\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821\u306b\u8d74\u4efb\u3057\u3066(\u7b2c6\u56de\u5275\u4fa1\u5927\u5b66\u6559\u80b2\u7814\u7a76\u5927\u4f1a\u5831\u544a)]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6VnaG23QG?url=http://ci.nii.ac.jp/els/110007150037.pdf?id=ART0009097381&type=pdf&lang=en&host=cinii&order_no=&ppv_type=0&lang_sw=&no=1422027122&cp= Archive]). \u5275\u5927\u6559\u80b2\u7814\u7a76 17, 43-44, 2008-03. [[Soka University]]. [https://www.webcitation.org/6VnaMR3qR?url=http://libir.soka.ac.jp/dspace/bitstream/10911/3068/1/KJ00005455288.pdf Alternate location] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6VnaMR3qR?url=http://libir.soka.ac.jp/dspace/bitstream/10911/3068/1/KJ00005455288.pdf Archive]). [http://ci.nii.ac.jp/naid/110007150037 See profile at] [[CiNii]]. [https://web.archive.org/web/20150123191014/http://libir.soka.ac.jp/dspace/handle/10911/3068 See profile at] Soka University.\n* \"[https://www.webcitation.org/6VnunQ9Ns?url=http://www.shinkyo.or.jp/15kaihou/sekai32.pdf \u30d7\u30e9\u30cf\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821 \u5927\u4e45\u4fdd \u745e\u6075]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6VnunQ9Ns?url=http://www.shinkyo.or.jp/15kaihou/sekai32.pdf Archive]). \u516c\u76ca\u793e\u56e3\u6cd5\u4eba[[:ja:\u4fe1\u6fc3\u6559\u80b2\u4f1a|\u4fe1\u6fc3\u6559\u80b2\u4f1a]].\n\nReports by those affiliated with the school:\n*Sugino, Masahiko (\u6749\u91ce\u3000\u96c5\u5f66; \u524d\u30d7\u30e9\u30cf\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821\u3000\u6559\u982d \u9ad8\u77e5\u770c\u6559\u80b2\u59d4\u54e1\u4f1a\u4e8b\u52d9\u5c40\u751f\u6daf\u5b66\u7fd2\u8ab2\u3000\u8ab2\u9577\u88dc\u4f50). \"[https://www.webcitation.org/6VnuKIDNc?url=http://crie.u-gakugei.ac.jp/report/pdf31/31_27sugino.pdf \u30d7\u30e9\u30cf\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821\u306e\u56fd\u969b\u7406\u89e3\u6559\u80b2]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6VnuKIDNc?url=http://crie.u-gakugei.ac.jp/report/pdf31/31_27sugino.pdf Archive]). [[Tokyo Gakugei University]]. p.&nbsp;108-110.\n*Tanei, Ichir\u014d (\u7a2e\u4e95 \u4e00\u90ce; \u524d\u30d7\u30e9\u30cf\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821\u3000\u6559\u8aed \u5175\u5eab\u770c\u795e\u6238\u5e02\u7acb\u5869\u5c4b\u4e2d\u5b66\u6821\u3000\u6559\u8aed) \"[https://www.webcitation.org/6VnuRKThL?url=http://crie.u-gakugei.ac.jp/report/pdf36/22Tanei.pdf \u30d7\u30e9\u30cf\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5b66\u6821\u3067\u306e\u73fe\u5730\u7406\u89e3\u3068\u5e73\u548c\u5b66\u7fd2]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6VnuRKThL?url=http://crie.u-gakugei.ac.jp/report/pdf36/22Tanei.pdf Archive]). [[Tokyo Gakugei University]]. p.&nbsp;74-77.\n\n==External links==\n{{portal|Japan|Czech Republic|Schools}}\n{{Commons category|Japanese school (Prague)}}\n* {{in lang|ja}} [http://www.jpschool.cz/ Japanese School in Prague]\n* {{in lang|ja}} [http://japschool.grhosting.cz/ Japanese School in Prague] (old website)\n* {{in lang|ja}} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.jschool.cz|title=Japanese School in Prague}} (old website)\n* {{in lang|ja}} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.vol.cz/japschool/|title=Japanese School in Prague}} (old website)<!--  referred from http://web.archive.org/web/19990221134328/http://www.naec.go.jp/kaigai/jeurope.html-->\n{{International schools in Prague}}\n{{Japanese schools in Europe}}\n\n[[Category:Nihonjin gakk\u014d|Prague]]\n[[Category:Schools in Prague]]\n[[Category:International schools in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Czech Republic\u2013Japan relations]]\n[[Category:1980 establishments in Czechoslovakia]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1980]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "link maintenance", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_School_in_Prague"}
{"title_page": "The Rofft", "text_new": "{{coord|53.0971|-2.9616|type:landmark_region:GB-WRX|format=dms|display=title}}\n'''The Rofft''' was a site situated at  [[Marford]] in the [[Wrexham County Borough]], that was initially a pre-historic camp, and later a [[Motte-and-bailey castle|motte and bailey]] castle. Today, due to its history, there is no visible evidence of the site.\n\n== Pre-Norman Conquest (1066) ==\nThe Rofft had initially been the site of an [[Hillfort|Iron Age fort]] encompassing about {{convert|30|acre}}.<ref name=\"Pratt 1992\">{{Cite journal|last=Pratt|first=D|date=1992|title=Fourteenth Century Marford and Hoseley: A Maerdref in Transition|journal=Transactions of Denbighshire Historical Society|volume=41|pages=25\u201369|via=}}</ref>  Suggested was the continued use of the site was due to its strategic position on a flat-top promontory providing views towards [[Pulford]].<ref name=\"Palmer 2018\">{{Cite book|url=https://socialsciences.mcmaster.ca/econ/ugcm/3ll3/palmer/AncientTenuresNorthWales.pdf|title=A History of Ancient Tenures of Land in North Wales and the Marches|last=Palmer|first=A. N.|last2=Owen|first2=E.|publisher=|year=1910|isbn=|edition=2nd|location=|pages=|access-date=4 May 2018}}</ref> Seventh-century Welsh sources stated that Pulford was the Welsh boundary with the [[Mercia|Kingdom of Mercia]]. The Rofft fort, in addition to the other nearby small forts of Caer Alyn and Y Gaer, guarded the approach to the [[River Alyn]] valley.<ref name=\"Jones 2018\">{{Cite journal|last=Jones|first=R|date=2013|title=Landscape Changes in a Borderland Township|url=http://www.chesterlandscapehistory.org.uk/publications/downloads/bulletin_0913.pdf|journal=Landscape History Today|volume=53|pages=4\u201323|access-date=4 May 2018|via=}}</ref>  The Rofft fort had local administrative and judicial functions for the [[commote]] of Marford.<ref name=\"Silvester 2018\" />\n\n== Post-Norman Conquest ==\nIn 1071, [[William the Conqueror|William I]] gave the Earldom of Chester to [[Hugh d'Avranches, Earl of Chester|Hugh d\u2019Avranches]] that included modern day Marford.<ref name=\"Jones 2018\" />  Recorded in the [[Domesday Book]] (1086) is that the Norman Lord Osbern Fitz Tesso controlled the commote of Marford and Hoseley.<ref name=\"Silvester 2018\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.walesher1974.org/herumd.php?group=CPAT&level=3&docid=301369150|title=The Llys and the Maerdref in East and North-East Wales|last=Silvester|first=R.J.|date=2015|publisher=The Clwyd-Powys Archaeological Trust|type=Report|access-date=4 May 2018}}</ref> The reason suggested for building the motte and bailey Rofft castle was a desire to widen Norman influences into the area.<ref name=\"Jones 2018\" />  The bailey was calculated to be {{convert|18|ft}} higher than the natural ground level and protected by a dry moat.<ref name=\"Pratt 1992\" />  Documentary evidence about the castle is vague and disputed. Stated is that in March 1140 the castle was severely damaged, and rebuilt by [[Madog ap Maredudd]], along with the castles at Doddington, [[Pulford Castle|Pulford]] and Wrexham.<ref name=\"Pratt 1992\" />  Uncertainty exists if  Rofft Castle was damaged and suggested is that record may instead refer to Wrexham castle, if so, making the first confirmed written reference to the Rofft in 1161\u201362.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hogg|first=A.H.A.|last2=King|first2=D.J.C.|date=1963|title=Early Castles in Wales and the Marches: A Preliminary List|url=|journal=Archaeologia Cambrensis|volume=112|pages=77\u2013124|via=}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Views_Westward_from_Marford.jpg|thumb|The view west from near the site of The Rofft over the Cheshire Plains|left]]\n\nAn administrative task related to the castle was the collection of Tolls at the nearby Pant Olwen.<ref name=\"Pratt 1992\" />  The presence of the Rofft influenced the local environment. It initially controlled the medieval Mersley Park, in a subdivision known as Horsley.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Smith|first=S.G.|date=2012|title=Medieval Parks, Gardens and Designed Landscapes of North Wales and the Shropshire Marches|url=http://whgt.wales/documents/bulletin/bulletin63.pdf|journal=Welsh Historical Gardens Trust|volume=63|pages=4\u20136|via=}}</ref> Religion was focused at St. Leonards chapel, the only nearby place of worship, and under the jurisdiction of the castle.<ref name=\"Pratt 1984\">{{Cite journal|last=Pratt|first=D|date=1984|title=Some Sidelights on the Early History of Gresford Church|url=|journal=Transactions of Denbighshire Historical Society|volume=33|pages=1\u201325|via=}}</ref>\n\n== The declining influence of the Rofft ==\nPratt wrote the influence of the Rofft declined due to a combination of events. The completion of the stone castles, such as [[Castell Dinas Br\u00e2n|Dinas Bran]], Llangollen by [[Gruffydd II ap Madog, Lord of Dinas Bran|Gruffydd Maelor II]], affected the significance of the areas motte and bailey castles. [[Wrexham]] had become the centre of local trade. Changes in the local politics diluted the importance of the Rofft. In 1282, the commotes of Marford, Wrexham and Yale were combined to create the Marcher [[The Lordship of Bromfield and Yale|Lordship of Bromfield and Yale]]. The Royal Bailiffs moved from the Rofft to reside at Wrexham. In 1284, when William de Warenne received the Bromfield seisin, he chose to do so at Wrexham rather than at the Rofft.<ref name=\"Pratt 1992\" /> In the mid-thirteenth century, the importance of the Chapel of St. Leonard lessened due to the foundation of the [[All Saints' Church, Gresford]].<ref name=\"Pratt 1984\" />\n\n== Post-14th century ==\n[[File:The_View_Eastwards_from_Marford.jpg|thumb|The view east into Wales, over the quarry, from near the site of The Rofft.  |alt=The View Eastwards from Marford]]\nA 1315 survey recorded a manor house on the Rofft bailey, and by 1575, Rofft Hall covered the site of the former Iron Age hill fort.<ref name=\"Silvester 2018\" />  In the 1840s the construction of the railway partially destroyed the Rofft earthworks. Between 1927 and 1958, gravel quarrying obliterated the Rofft site.<ref name=\"Silvester 2018\" />  The Rofft survives only in name as land near the Rofft is called Castle Croft.<ref name=\"Palmer 2018\" /> The name of the Rofft Primary School, Marford acknowledges the site.\n\nMersley Park became associated with [[Holt, Wrexham County Borough|Holt]], and latterly known as Holt Park, and in the seventeenth century disparked. The remaining traces of the park are within the local names of places such as Parkside and Lower Park.<ref name=\"Pratt 1992\" />  The Chapel of St. Leonard stood until the fifteenth century. The site of the chapel is unknown but remembered through the road name Pont-Y-Capel.<ref name=\"Pratt 1984\" />\n\n== See also ==\n\n[[Alfred Neobard Palmer]], a notable local historian for the area of Wrexham\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rofft}}\n[[Category:Castles in Wrexham County Borough]]\n[[Category:Former buildings and structures in Wrexham County Borough]]\n[[Category:History of Wrexham County Borough]]\n[[Category:Motte-and-bailey castles]]\n[[Category:The Lordship of Bromfield and Yale]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|53.0971|-2.9616|type:landmark_region:GB-WRX|format=dms|display=title}}\n'''The Rofft''' was a site situated at  [[Marford]] in the [[Wrexham County Borough]], that was initially a pre-historic camp, and later a [[Motte-and-bailey castle|motte and bailey]] castle. Today, due to its history, there is no visible evidence of the site.\n\n== Pre-Norman Conquest (1066) ==\nThe Rofft had initially been the site of an [[Hillfort|Iron Age fort]] encompassing about {{convert|30|acre}}.<ref name=\"Pratt 1992\">{{Cite journal|last=Pratt|first=D|date=1992|title=Fourteenth Century Marford and Hoseley: A Maerdref in Transition|journal=Transactions of Denbighshire Historical Society|volume=41|pages=25\u201369|via=}}</ref>  Suggested was the continued use of the site was due to its strategic position on a flat-top promontory providing views towards [[Pulford]].<ref name=\"Palmer 2018\">{{Cite book|url=https://socialsciences.mcmaster.ca/econ/ugcm/3ll3/palmer/AncientTenuresNorthWales.pdf|title=A History of Ancient Tenures of Land in North Wales and the Marches|last=Palmer|first=A. N.|last2=Owen|first2=E.|publisher=|year=1910|isbn=|edition=2nd|location=|pages=|access-date=4 May 2018}}</ref> Seventh-century Welsh sources stated that Pulford was the Welsh boundary with the [[Mercia|Kingdom of Mercia]]. The Rofft fort, in addition to the other nearby small forts of Caer Alyn and Y Gaer, guarded the approach to the [[River Alyn]] valley.<ref name=\"Jones 2018\">{{Cite journal|last=Jones|first=R|date=2013|title=Landscape Changes in a Borderland Township|url=http://www.chesterlandscapehistory.org.uk/publications/downloads/bulletin_0913.pdf|journal=Landscape History Today|volume=53|pages=4\u201323|access-date=4 May 2018|via=}}</ref>  The Rofft fort had local administrative and judicial functions for the [[commote]] of Marford.<ref name=\"Silvester 2018\" />\n\n== Post-Norman Conquest ==\nIn 1071, [[William the Conqueror|William I]] gave the Earldom of Chester to [[Hugh d'Avranches, Earl of Chester|Hugh d\u2019Avranches]] that included modern day Marford.<ref name=\"Jones 2018\" />  Recorded in the [[Domesday Book]] (1086) is that the Norman Lord Osbern Fitz Tesso controlled the commote of Marford and Hoseley.<ref name=\"Silvester 2018\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.walesher1974.org/herumd.php?group=CPAT&level=3&docid=301369150|title=The Llys and the Maerdref in East and North-East Wales|last=Silvester|first=R.J.|date=2015|publisher=The Clwyd-Powys Archaeological Trust|type=Report|access-date=4 May 2018}}</ref> The reason suggested for building the motte and bailey Rofft castle was a desire to widen Norman influences into the area.<ref name=\"Jones 2018\" />  The bailey was calculated to be {{convert|18|ft}} higher than the natural ground level and protected by a dry moat.<ref name=\"Pratt 1992\" />  Documentary evidence about the castle is vague and disputed. Stated is that in March 1140 the castle was severely damaged, and rebuilt by [[Madog ap Maredudd]], along with the castles at Doddington, [[Pulford Castle|Pulford]] and Wrexham.<ref name=\"Pratt 1992\" />  Uncertainty exists if  Rofft Castle was damaged and suggested is that record may instead refer to Wrexham castle, if so, making the first confirmed written reference to the Rofft in 1161\u201362.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hogg|first=A.H.A.|last2=King|first2=D.J.C.|date=1963|title=Early Castles in Wales and the Marches: A Preliminary List|url=|journal=Archaeologia Cambrensis|volume=112|pages=77\u2013124|via=}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Views_Westward_from_Marford.jpg|thumb|The view west from near the site of The Rofft over the Cheshire Plains|left]]\n\nAn administrative task related to the castle was the collection of Tolls at the nearby Pant Olwen.<ref name=\"Pratt 1992\" />  The presence of the Rofft influenced the local environment. It initially controlled the medieval Mersley Park, in a subdivision known as Horsley.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Smith|first=S.G.|date=2012|title=Medieval Parks, Gardens and Designed Landscapes of North Wales and the Shropshire Marches|url=http://whgt.wales/documents/bulletin/bulletin63.pdf|journal=Welsh Historical Gardens Trust|volume=63|pages=4\u20136|via=}}</ref> Religion was focused at St. Leonards chapel, the only nearby place of worship, and under the jurisdiction of the castle.<ref name=\"Pratt 1984\">{{Cite journal|last=Pratt|first=D|date=1984|title=Some Sidelights on the Early History of Gresford Church|url=|journal=Transactions of Denbighshire Historical Society|volume=33|pages=1\u201325|via=}}</ref>\n\n== The declining influence of the Rofft ==\nPratt wrote the influence of the Rofft declined due to a combination of events. The completion of the stone castles, such as [[Castell Dinas Br\u00e2n|Dinas Bran]], Llangollen by [[Gruffydd II ap Madog, Lord of Dinas Bran|Gruffydd Maelor II]], affected the significance of the areas motte and bailey castles. [[Wrexham]] had become the centre of local trade. Changes in the local politics diluted the importance of the Rofft. In 1282, the commotes of Marford, Wrexham and Yale were combined to create the Marcher [[The Lordship of Bromfield and Yale|Lordship of Bromfield and Yale]]. The Royal Bailiffs moved from the Rofft to reside at Wrexham. In 1284, when William de Warenne received the Bromfield seisin, he chose to do so at Wrexham rather than at the Rofft.<ref name=\"Pratt 1992\" /> In the mid-thirteenth century, the importance of the Chapel of St. Leonard lessened due to the foundation of the [[All Saints' Church, Gresford]].<ref name=\"Pratt 1984\" />\n\n== Post-14th century ==\n[[File:The_View_Eastwards_from_Marford.jpg|thumb|The view east into Wales, over the quarry, from near the site of The Rofft.  |alt=The View Eastwards from Marford]]\nA 1315 survey recorded a manor house on the Rofft bailey, and by 1575, Rofft Hall covered the site of the former Iron Age hill fort.<ref name=\"Silvester 2018\" />  In the 1840s the construction of the railway partially destroyed the Rofft earthworks. Between 1927 and 1958, gravel quarrying obliterated the Rofft site.<ref name=\"Silvester 2018\" />  The Rofft survives only in name as land near the Rofft is called Castle Croft.<ref name=\"Palmer 2018\" /> The name of the Rofft Primary School, Marford acknowledges the site.\n\nMersley Park became associated with [[Holt, Wrexham County Borough|Holt]], and latterly known as Holt Park, and in the seventeenth century disparked. The remaining traces of the park are within the local names of places such as Parkside and Lower Park.<ref name=\"Pratt 1992\" />  The Chapel of St. Leonard stood until the fifteenth century. The site of the chapel is unknown but remembered through the road name Pont-Y-Capel.<ref name=\"Pratt 1984\" />\n\n== See also ==\n\n[[Alfred Neobard Palmer]] a notable local historian for the area of Wrexham\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rofft}}\n[[Category:Castles in Wrexham County Borough]]\n[[Category:Former buildings and structures in Wrexham County Borough]]\n[[Category:History of Wrexham County Borough]]\n[[Category:Motte-and-bailey castles]]\n[[Category:The Lordship of Bromfield and Yale]]\n", "name_user": "Maproom", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:add comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Rofft"}
{"title_page": "Siege of Gloucester", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox Military Conflict\n|conflict=Siege of Gloucester\n|partof=the [[First English Civil War]]\n|date=10 August - 5 September 1643\n|place=[[Gloucester]], [[Gloucestershire]]\n|result=Parliamentarian victory\n|combatant1=[[Cavalier|Royalists]]\n|combatant2=[[Roundhead|Parliamentarians]]\n|commander1=[[Charles I of England|Charles I]]\n|commander2=[[Edward Massey]]\n|strength1=13,150+\n|strength2=1,500\n|casualties1=1,000\u20131,500+\n|casualties2=30\u201350\n}}\n{{Campaignbox First English Civil War|state=collapsed}}\n\nThe '''Siege of Gloucester''' was an engagement in the [[First English Civil War]]. It took place between 10 August and 5 September 1643, between the defending Parliamentarian garrison of [[Gloucester]] and the besieging army of [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]]. The siege ended with the arrival of a relieving Parliamentarian army under the [[Robert Devereux, 3rd Earl of Essex|Earl of Essex]]. The Royalist forces withdrew, having sustained heavy casualties and had several cannons disabled as a result of sallies made by the defenders.\n\n==Prelude==\nFollowing the Royalist defeat at the [[Battle of Edgehill]] in October 1642, King Charles I's control of the south was limited to [[Cornwall]], [[Wales]] and the [[Welsh Marches|Marches]], and a pocket of the [[Thames Valley]] around [[Oxford]], where he based his wartime capital.<ref>Day 2007 p. 29</ref> The ruling [[Puritans|Puritan]] elite of [[Gloucester]] ensured the city of some 5,000 inhabitants would be from the outset a staunchly Parliamentarian stronghold in the struggle against an anti-Puritan King and his [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] Queen.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 59\u201360</ref> Possession of Gloucester, along with [[Bristol]] to the south, threatened both Oxford and access to the Royalist recruiting grounds of Wales.<ref>Day 2007 p. 21</ref>\n\nAn unsuccessful attempt to rally Royalist support in [[Cirencester]] in August 1642 prompted Parliamentarians in [[Gloucestershire]] to muster the [[Militia (English)|militia]], and in November the first regular troops were garrisoned in Gloucester.<ref>Day 2007 p. 60</ref> In February 1643 the Royalist commander [[Prince Rupert of the Rhine|Prince Rupert]] easily defeated a militia garrison at Cirencester, prompting the Parliamentarians to recall their outposts at [[Berkeley, Gloucestershire|Berkeley]], [[Sudeley Castle|Sudeley]] and [[Tewkesbury]]. The next day Rupert appeared before Gloucester, but lacked the strength to enforce his demand for the city's surrender. Later that month an army of 2,000 Welshman led by [[Henry Somerset, 1st Duke of Beaufort|Lord Herbert of Raglan]] arrived on the west bank of the Severn opposite the city, but lacked the strength for an assault across the river. Its presence caused great consternation in Gloucester until a Parliamentarian army commanded by Sir [[William Waller]] defeated it on 24 March.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 60\u201362</ref>\n\nThe defeat of Waller in the [[Battle of Roundway Down]] on 13 July by the Royalist Western Army left both Bristol and Gloucester vulnerable, and on 18 July Rupert led another Royalist army out of Oxford to take control of the Severn valley. On 26 July Rupert's Oxford Army, supported by the Western Army, seized Bristol. Royalist casualties were high, and despite Rupert's instructions to the contrary, the victorious troops plundered the city.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 21\u201325</ref> Rupert was appointed governor of Bristol, but infighting within the Royalist leadership and concerns that an attack on Gloucester would result in the same high casualties prompted [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]] to travel to Bristol for a council of war.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 26\u201328</ref> He arrived on 2 August, and over the next five days consulted with his advisers on the best course of action. The strategic situation since Edgehill had improved significantly for the Royalists, with victories in the north of England, the arrival of reinforcements and materiel in June, and an opposition that had fallen into disarray.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 29\u201331</ref> Rupert's plan to consolidate the Royalist grip on the west by seizing Gloucester faced opposition from those in the King's camp, led by his wife Queen [[Henrietta Maria of France|Henrietta Maria]], who believed a march on London could end the war.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 51\u201353</ref>\n\nThe capture of Gloucester would give Charles some advantages. It would allow the Royalist garrisons farther up the Severn at [[Worcester]] and [[Shrewsbury]] to be supplied from Bristol, with consequent benefit to the economy of that city. Gloucestershire \u2013 populous, wealthy and Parliamentarian \u2013 could be punitively taxed, and Welsh manpower and money could be freely deployed against the King's enemies in the rest of the country. Although it was likely that Rupert would have been able to storm a city that was less well defended than Bristol, Charles was not willing to risk the casualties an assault would incur.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 54\u201355</ref> On 6 August the Parliamentarian governor of Gloucester, Lieutenant-Colonel [[Edward Massey]], refused to surrender the city, but in a secret communication he let it be known that he would do so if the King, rather than Rupert, led the army on Gloucester. Charles decided the next day that this was the best chance of securing Gloucester quickly and without bloodshed. This compromise plan pleased neither the Queen's faction, who saw it as an unnecessary diversion from the more decisive objective of London, nor Rupert, who remained in Bristol in the belief that the Royalist army was not strong enough to allow Massey to honourably surrender without a fight.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 55\u201357</ref>\n\n==Gloucester defences==\nGloucester's strength lay in its location. To the west, the River Severn formed a natural defence against an assaulting army. To the north and north-east the marshy ground was unsuitable for siege operations, and the River Twyver and a tributary stream added to the obstacles. This left the higher and drier ground to the east and south as the only feasible directions for an attack. In the preceding centuries the city had grown beyond its medieval defences, of which only the ruined [[Gloucester Castle|castle]] by the river and a stretch of wall that linked the south, east and original north fates, the last known as the inner north gate and now well within the city, still survived. From the south gate to the east gate the wall was high but not thick enough to withstand 17th-century artillery or mining operations.<ref name=Day65\u201366>Day 2007 pp. 65\u201366</ref>\n\nThe fall of Bristol prompted the hurried reinforcement of the existing defences. New earthworks and a narrow water-filled ditch completed the line of fortifications from the south gate to the Severn. Another earthwork was extended north from Whitefriars Barn on the north-east corner of the medieval wall to the outer north gate. From there the River Twyver formed a moat as the earthwork followed it north-west to Alvin Gate then on to the river's junction with the Old Severn.<ref name=Day65\u201366 /> This easternmost channel of the River Severn had dried up by the 19th century, but at the time of the civil war it was still a navigable river.<ref>Herbert 1988 para. 2</ref><ref>Rhodes 2006 p. 14</ref> The earthwork then followed the Old Severn south-west to a point a short distance north of Westgate Street, from where it was extended the other side of the Old Severn to the River Severn just above the west gate.<ref name=Day66>Day 2007 p. 66</ref> Inside the city, an earthwork was extended west from the end of the medieval wall at the inner north gate via [[Gloucester Cathedral]] to [[St Oswald's Priory, Gloucester|St Oswald's Priory]], where it met the new outer earthwork.<ref name=Day66 /> The outer north gate and Alvin Gate were fortified with earthwork [[bastion]]s,<ref name=Day66 /> a drawbridge was installed at Westgate Bridge and the Old Severn was dammed at Dockham, causing the ground to north-west of the city to flood.<ref>Rhodes 2006 pp. 17, 29\u201330</ref>\n\nThe garrison numbered no more than 1,500 troops. The bulk of these comprised two half-strength regiments each of some 600 men: the [[Henry Grey, 1st Earl of Stamford|Earl of Stamford]]'s Regiment of Foot, recruited from London and Leicestershire, and a locally recruited regiment known as the Town Regiment. The remainder comprised a company of [[Trained bands|trained band]], 100 [[dragoon]]s and a [[troop]] of cavalry. The city's dozen or so artillery pieces ranged in size from light cannon to two nine-pounder [[demi-culverin]]s. Stamford's regiment was experienced and well led, though of uncertain discipline. The Town Regiment lacked experience but was motivated by its ties to the city it was defending, although there is evidence that some of its men would refuse to oppose the King. The city could support itself with basic necessities, but it lacked sufficient gunpowder to withstand an assault or prolonged siege.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 63\u201365</ref>\n\nMassey was an autocratic military commander, but his authority in the city was shared with the civilian administration. A committee had been established in December 1642 to manage the Parliamentarian war effort in the county, but [[Thomas Pury]], the [[member of parliament]] for Gloucester, was the only committee member in the city. Civic authority was held by a forty-member council, though in practice an inner core of some fifteen [[Alderman|aldermen]], including the mayor, wielded power. As many of these were, like Pury, officers in the city's garrison, political and military command was largely integrated.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 66\u201367</ref> In the days immediately following the fall of Bristol, morale in the city, both military and civilian, was low.<ref>Day 2007 p. 68</ref> It's possible that this was what prompted Massey consider surrendering the city, though his message suggesting he would may have been a subterfuge designed to buy some time.<ref>Day 2007 p. 73</ref> There is strong evidence that the conduct and actions of the city elite, including Massey and particularly Pury, did much to stiffen the city's resolve. Officers and councillors with Royalist sympathies were given the opportunity to leave, and those who remained were required to restate an oath of allegiance to Parliament. The discipline of the troops was improved by paying them, and civilians were kept busy reinforcing the city's defences.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 69\u201370</ref>\n\n==Siege==\nAs Charles marched north from Bristol, reinforcements were converging on Gloucester from Oxford, Worcester and Herefordshire.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 86\u201387</ref> By the afternoon of 10 August the Royalist army, comprising some 6,000 infantry and 2,500 mounted troops, began assembling around the city.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 90\u201391</ref> Charles set up his headquarters at [[Matson, Gloucester|Matson]] House.<ref>Day 2007 p. 97</ref> His demand for Gloucester's surrender was unanimously and somewhat insolently rejected, and the Parliamentarians set fire to the suburbs outside the city defences to clear lines of fire and deprive the Royalists of cover.<ref>Day 2007 pp. , 91\u201393,96</ref> Charles had decided to march on Gloucester in the belief that the city would be quickly surrendered. Now that gambit had failed, he decided to besiege it. His pride had been wounded by the manner of the Parliamentarian rejection. His commanders, assessing the state of the city's defences, supplies and morale, persuaded him the city could be taken within ten days without an assault. Intelligence indicated the even if the Parliamentarians were able to send a relieving force, it could be easily defeated before it could reach the city. Most decisively, the [[William Cavendish, 1st Duke of Newcastle|Earl of Newcastle]], whose support was necessary in any campaign against London, declared himself unable to march south while Hull remained in Parliamentarian hands, leaving Charles too weak to contemplate such a move.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 93\u201395</ref>\n\nThe first shots were fired in the afternoon as Sir [[Jacob Astley, 1st Baron Astley of Reading|Jacob Astley]] established his forces near Issold's House on the eastern side of the city. [[Patrick Ruthven, 1st Earl of Forth|Lord Forth]], who had been given overall command of the siege, set up a fortified leaguer to the rear of the ruined [[Llanthony Secunda Priory]] and established his forces to the south of the city.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 95\u201396, 99, 100\u2013101</ref> By dawn on 11 August, a line of trenches had been dug some {{convert|130|yd|m}} from the walls, placing the two sides within musket range of each other, stretching from [[Brunswick Square, Gloucester|Gaudy Green]] on the south side to Issold's House on the east.<ref>Day 2007 p. 99</ref> Massey responded with spoiling tactics in an attempt to hinder Royalist siege operations and delay the assault he was expecting. At midnight a small raiding party succeeded in disrupting Royalist entrenching operations on Gaudy Green, and a larger raid on the green the next morning, 12 August, resulted in the capture of Royalist men, tools and weapons.<ref>Day 2007 p. 100</ref> By this time, the reinforcements from Herefordshire and Worcester under the command of Sir William Vavasour arrived on the west bank of the Severn and began crossing the river to take up positions at Kingsholm, to the north of the city. This force increased the size of the besieging army by another 2,400 infantry and over 300 cavalry. They too were the target of a Parliamentarian raid which inflicted up to fifteen casualties on the Royalists.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 10, 100</ref>\n\nLater on 12 August, Forth completed an earthwork square on Gaudy Green, in which he placed two 24-pounders, the largest of the Royalist's eight cannon, along with a 12-pounder to target the south wall. Another artillery emplacement was positioned to target the east wall nearby.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 10, 99\u2013102</ref> With the artillery in place, the Royalists began bombarding the walls, with the main effort beginning at 11:00 on 13 August. The cannon were too light to have any significant impact, and of the two mortars the Royalists possessed, one, reputed to be the largest in the country, exploded on its first use. When it became evident the Royalists were focusing their efforts on the south-east corner of the city defences, Massey quickly buttressed the medieval walls with up to {{convert|5|ft|m}} of earth, which ensured that the defences held. Meanwhile, the majority of Vavasour's troops completed their crossing of the Severn, leaving behind a small contingent to blockade the west bank.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 100\u2013102</ref>\n\nReacting to rumours that Vavasour had received a reinforcement of artillery, the Parliamentarians mounted another raid to the north of the city on 14 August. They captured two prisoners but failed in their primary objective of locating and spiking any guns.<ref>Day 2007 p. 102</ref> The Royalist bombardment continued through 14 August, but a breach blown in the wall by the larger guns on Gaudy Green was quickly plugged by the defenders with woolsacks and [[gabion]]s. Royalist engineers mining towards the walls from trenches at the green succeeded in draining the ditch below the walls, but this was not followed up with an assault. By the end of the day the Royalist guns had fallen silent; the evidence suggests they had run out of ammunition.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 102\u2013103</ref>\n\nThe following day Vavasour received a reinforcement of 500 [[Glamorgan]] militia and 450 musketeers from Bristol, while the Parliamentarians bolstered the earthwork defences around the south and north gates. On 16 August Rupert accompanied Charles to Oxford, and neither were at Gloucester to witness the most ambitious Parliamentarian raid yet. Just before sunset, 150 musketeers of Stamford's regiment sallied out of the north gate to attack the Royalist trenches east of the city. The Parliamentarians claimed 100 Royalist killed for the cost of 2 injured, while Royalist sources report 24 Parliamentarians killed and more wounded, for the loss of 4 Royalists killed.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 103\u2013105</ref>\n\nStruggling with a shortage of gunpowder and with the guns quiet, the Royalists concentrated on mining operations to breach the city walls. Miners recruited from the [[Forest of Dean]] were set to work under a protective gallery to fill the {{convert|12|ft|m|adj=on}} deep by {{convert|30|ft|m|adj=on}} wide moat which, when completed, would allow them to undermine the walls. It was slow work, estimated to need a week to complete. The faster alternative was to forgo the protection and fill the moat with [[fascine]]s. An attempt to do this was beaten back by musket fire from the walls, and resulted in the desertion of the miners.<ref>Day 2007 103, 106\u2013107</ref>\n\nBy 18 August Vavasour had deployed three cannon in front of his main camp at Kingsholm and another opposite Alvin Gate. These were the targets of a Parliamentarian raid that morning that was even larger than previous efforts; a diversionary attack by 50 men and a main force of 400. All four of Vavasour's cannon were disabled, the Parliamentarians claiming over 100 Royalist casualties for the loss of 6, the Royalists admitting 28 casualties and claiming to have killed 27 Parliamentarians. Another Parliamentarian raid the same day involved their only recorded use of cavalry during the siege, when 150 musketeers and 40 cavalry mounted an ineffectual attack on Royalist positions to the east of the city. Charles, meanwhile, was on his way back to Gloucester with another 1,000 reinforcements.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 106\u2013107</ref>\n\nBy the morning of 19 August, two 6-pounder cannon had been installed in a third emplacement opposite the east gate, bringing all the original artillery online. At 10:00, the bombardment was resumed in a last effort to subdue the city by the original ten-day deadline. Constrained by the limited supplies of ammunition and gunpowder, the bombardment had little material effect, though it prompted Massey to hastily erect a breastwork in the open ground of Friar's Orchard, at the south east corner of the city where the Royalist artillery was being concentrated. A Royalist attempt to cross the moat after dark was beaten back by musket fire. The objective of forcing the surrender of Gloucester by siege in ten days had failed, partly due to the city's resolve and Massey's spoiling attacks, but mainly due to the inadequacy of the Royalist artillery.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 107\u2013109</ref> \n\nThe Parliamentarians mounted another raid at dawn on 21 August. It was a two-pronged attack designed to disable the Royalist artillery south and east of the walls. One detachment travelled by boat down the Severn, landed between Forth's camp and a redoubt opposite the castle and successfuly stormed the redoubt. The second detachment of 200 musketeers sallied from the north gate. Intending first to attack the battery opposite the east gate, this force became lost and blundered into Royalist infantry camps. When Massey saw that the raid was not going to plan, he sounded the recall. The Parliamentarians suffered eight casualties, the Royalists more than twenty. Such raids were proving risky and wasteful of the garrison's limited ammunition, and this was the last large-scale operation mounted by the Parliamentarians.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 112\u2013113</ref>\n\nAs the Royalists set about replenishing their stocks of ammunition, they intensified their mining efforts. It was anticipated that the original effort to bridge the moat would allow the besiegers to reach the east wall on 24 August. A second effort to bridge the moat to the south was begun, as was a more complicated project to tunnel towards the east gate. Royalist agents attempted to persuade the garrison to surrender, and Royalist cavalry staged a mock battle in an unsuccessful attempt to lure the garrison out of the city in the belief that a relief force had arrived.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 114\u2013115</ref> A desultory bombardment was maintained, particularly by the mortars, until 25 August, when it was intensified. An attempt that day by Massey to disrupt it with a sally from the north gate was beaten back by cavalry, but as before, a shortage of ammunition \u2013 at one stage the Royalists resorted to firing stones \u2013 blunted the impact, and little damage was done to the city.<ref>Day 2007 p. 116</ref>\n\nFollowing news that the [[Robert Devereux, 3rd Earl of Essex|Earl of Essex]] was raising a Parliamentarian army in London, Charles and Rupert travelled to Oxford on 26 August, where they held a two-day council of war. With no intelligence of Essex's plans, the Royalists bolstered the defences of Oxford with troops earmarked for the siege of Gloucester while the Royalist garrison at Bristol was urged to send all the forces it could spare to Gloucester. Believing that Essex could muster no more than 6,000 troops, the decision was made to continue the siege, though contingency plans for the blockade of Gloucester were drawn up in case it had to be lifted. [[Henry Wilmot, 1st Earl of Rochester|Lord Wilmot]] was instructed to muster 2,000 cavalry around [[Banbury]]. Their task would be to delay the Parliamentarians in the [[Cotswolds]] until Rupert could come up with the rest of the Royalist cavalry in support, should Essex march to the relief of Gloucester.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 117\u2013118</ref>\n\nEssex began his march from [[Colnbrook]], west of London, on 26 August.<ref>Day 2007 p. 127</ref> His plan was to relieve Gloucester without provoking a major battle in which, with the Royalist superiority in cavalry, he would be at a disdvantage. His route was dictated by the desire to minimise the amount of open country favourable to cavalry operations he would have to pass through, and took him north of Oxford via Aylesbury and Bicester and then across the Cotswolds.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 124\u2013126</ref> At the beginning of September Essex was due north of Oxford with an army of some 10,500 infantry, no more than 4,500 mounted troops and an artillery train that is estimated at no more than 50 guns.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 130\u2013131, 133</ref>\n\nMining was now the principal tactic by which the Royalists hoped to bring the siege to a successful conclusion. Priority was given to tunnelling at the east gate, which caused progress on efforts to fill the moat below the south and east walls to slow, possibly as a result of a lack of miners and engineers. Parliamentarian countermining at the east gate on 28 August was quickly abandoned because of springs that caused flooding, which accounts for the slow pace of the Royalist efforts there.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 136\u2013138</ref> Massey continued to harass the besiegers with sniping and artillery fire, and he resumed countermining operations at the east gate after a reconnaissance party had reported Royalists miners were still working on their mine. The progress of the Royalist mines closer towards the walls, quickened by the arrival of Welsh miners on 29 August, led Massey to believe an an assault was imminent. On 1 September he fortified Friars Orchard with an earthwork wall and [[Sconce (fortification)|sconce]], a fort in which he placed four pieces of artillery that could be brought to bear on any Royalists who broke through the south-east corner or the east gate.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 138\u2013140</ref>\n\nOn 3 September the Parliamentarians placed a [[Saker (cannon)|saker]] in a gun port they had been secretly building in east wall above the gallery protecting the Royalist miners. The medium-sized cannon was employed most of the day against the gallery, to little effect, until the Royalists targeted it with a cannon of their own, at which point it was withdrawn. The Royalists anticipated their mine would reach the east gate the next day, while they believed Essex could be delayed in the Cotswolds for four days. The Bristol garrison was being stripped for reinforcements and orders had been sent to Oxford for ten field guns and the equipment necessary to make the guns already at Gloucester mobile, should it be necessary to redeploy them from siegework to use in open battle.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 140\u2013141</ref>\n\nBy the end of the day Essex's lead element, the London brigade, was at [[Oddington, Gloucestershire|Oddington]], {{convert|2|mi|km}} east of [[Stow-on-the-Wold]]. The Parliamentarian army was largely untroubled by Wilmot's Royalist cavalry, and because of the differing rates of march it was strung out as far back as [[Chipping Norton]], nearly {{convert|6|mi|km}} to the east. Earlier the same day Rupert had led the rest of the Royalist cavalry from Gloucester, and having rendezvoused with Wilmot, now had some 5,000 men camped around [[Bourton-on-the-Water]], {{convert|4|mi|km}} south-west of Stow.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 141\u2013143, 146</ref>\n\nBy the end of the siege, Massey had only three barrels of gunpowder left for the defence of the city.\n\n==Aftermath==\nWith the arrival of the Earl of Essex, the Royalists forces withdrew and began to march on towards London. They intercepted Essex's army at the [[First Battle of Newbury]], but failed to destroy it. For the remainder of the war, Massey's force based in Gloucester continually threatened the lines of communication between Oxford, the King's wartime capital, and Wales and the West Country.\n\nFollowing the return of Charles II to the throne, the king took his revenge upon the city by having its walls torn down. The foundations of the wall, however, are still visible in parts of the city today.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist|30em}}\n\n==Commemoration==\nFor centuries afterwards, the lifting of the siege was marked by an annual [[Gloucester Day]]. This died out in the nineteenth century but was reinstated in 2009.<ref name=bbc>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/gloucestershire/8239588.stm Tradition revived for city pride.] BBC News, 5 September 2009. Retrieved 11 September 2011.</ref>\n\nThe modern ''Gloucester Day'' has recently included a parade by the [[Mock Mayor]] of [[Barton and Tredworth|Barton]], an office created after Barton was moved outside of the limits of the city following the restoration of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]].<ref>[http://www.gloucester.gov.uk/Freetime/Museums/historyweek/gloucesterday.aspx GLOUCESTER DAY 2011.] gloucester.gov.uk 2011. Retrieved 11 September 2011.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last=Day |first=Jon |title=Gloucester and Newbury 1643: The Turning Point of the Civil War |type=E-Book |publisher=Pen & Sword Military |location=Barnsley, South Yorkshire |year=2007 |isbn=978-1-84415-591-0 }}\n* {{cite web |editor-last=Herbert |editor-first=N.M. |year=1988 |title=A History of the County of Gloucester: Gloucester: Bridges, gates and walls|volume=4|pages=242\u2013245|publisher=British History Online |accessdate=8 April 2020|url=https://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/glos/vol4/pp242-245 }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Rhodes|first=John|title=The Severn Flood-Plain at Gloucester in the Medieval and Early Modern Periods|journal= Transactions of the Bristol and Gloucestershire Archaeological Society|volume=124|publisher=|year=2006|pages=9\u201336|doi=}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Whiting, J.R.S. ''Gloucester besieged: The story of a roundhead city 1640-1660.'' Gloucester: [[Gloucester City Museum & Art Gallery|City Museum & Art Gallery]], 1975. (2nd edition 1984)\n\n{{coord |51.864|-2.2438|type:event_region:GB-GLS|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Sieges of the English Civil Wars|Gloucester, Siege of]]\n[[Category:1643 in England]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1643]]\n[[Category:History of Gloucester]]\n[[Category:Military history of Gloucestershire]]\n[[Category:17th century in Gloucestershire]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox Military Conflict\n|conflict=Siege of Gloucester\n|partof=the [[First English Civil War]]\n|date=10 August - 5 September 1643\n|place=[[Gloucester]], [[Gloucestershire]]\n|result=Parliamentarian victory\n|combatant1=[[Cavalier|Royalists]]\n|combatant2=[[Roundhead|Parliamentarians]]\n|commander1=[[Charles I of England|Charles I]]\n|commander2=[[Edward Massey]]\n|strength1=13,150+\n|strength2=1,500\n|casualties1=1,000\u20131,500+\n|casualties2=30\u201350\n}}\n{{Campaignbox First English Civil War|state=collapsed}}\n\nThe '''Siege of Gloucester''' was an engagement in the [[First English Civil War]]. It took place between 10 August and 5 September 1643, between the defending Parliamentarian garrison of [[Gloucester]] and the besieging army of [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]]. The siege ended with the arrival of a relieving Parliamentarian army under the [[Robert Devereux, 3rd Earl of Essex|Earl of Essex]]. The Royalist forces withdrew, having sustained heavy casualties and had several cannons disabled as a result of sallies made by the defenders.\n\n==Prelude==\nFollowing the Royalist defeat at the [[Battle of Edgehill]] in October 1642, King Charles I's control of the south was limited to [[Cornwall]], [[Wales]] and the [[Welsh Marches|Marches]], and a pocket of the [[Thames Valley]] around [[Oxford]], where he based his wartime capital.<ref>Day 2007 p. 29</ref> The ruling [[Puritans|Puritan]] elite of [[Gloucester]] ensured the city of some 5,000 inhabitants would be from the outset a staunchly Parliamentarian stronghold in the struggle against an anti-Puritan King and his [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] Queen.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 59\u201360</ref> Possession of Gloucester, along with [[Bristol]] to the south, threatened both Oxford and access to the Royalist recruiting grounds of Wales.<ref>Day 2007 p. 21</ref>\n\nAn unsuccessful attempt to rally Royalist support in [[Cirencester]] in August 1642 prompted Parliamentarians in [[Gloucestershire]] to muster the [[Militia (English)|militia]], and in November the first regular troops were garrisoned in Gloucester.<ref>Day 2007 p. 60</ref> In February 1643 the Royalist commander [[Prince Rupert of the Rhine|Prince Rupert]] easily defeated a militia garrison at Cirencester, prompting the Parliamentarians to recall their outposts at [[Berkeley, Gloucestershire|Berkeley]], [[Sudeley Castle|Sudeley]] and [[Tewkesbury]]. The next day Rupert appeared before Gloucester, but lacked the strength to enforce his demand for the city's surrender. Later that month an army of 2,000 Welshman led by [[Henry Somerset, 1st Duke of Beaufort|Lord Herbert of Raglan]] arrived on the west bank of the Severn opposite the city, but lacked the strength for an assault across the river. Its presence caused great consternation in Gloucester until a Parliamentarian army commanded by Sir [[William Waller]] defeated it on 24 March.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 60\u201362</ref>\n\nThe defeat of Waller in the [[Battle of Roundway Down]] on 13 July by the Royalist Western Army left both Bristol and Gloucester vulnerable, and on 18 July Rupert led another Royalist army out of Oxford to take control of the Severn valley. On 26 July Rupert's Oxford Army, supported by the Western Army, seized Bristol. Royalist casualties were high, and despite Rupert's instructions to the contrary, the victorious troops plundered the city.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 21\u201325</ref> Rupert was appointed governor of Bristol, but infighting within the Royalist leadership and concerns that an attack on Gloucester would result in the same high casualties prompted [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]] to travel to Bristol for a council of war.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 26\u201328</ref> He arrived on 2 August, and over the next five days consulted with his advisers on the best course of action. The strategic situation since Edgehill had improved significantly for the Royalists, with victories in the north of England, the arrival of reinforcements and materiel in June, and an opposition that had fallen into disarray.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 29\u201331</ref> Rupert's plan to consolidate the Royalist grip on the west by seizing Gloucester faced opposition from those in the King's camp, led by his wife Queen [[Henrietta Maria of France|Henrietta Maria]], who believed a march on London could end the war.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 51\u201353</ref>\n\nThe capture of Gloucester would give Charles some advantages. It would allow the Royalist garrisons farther up the Severn at [[Worcester]] and [[Shrewsbury]] to be supplied from Bristol, with consequent benefit to the economy of that city. Gloucestershire \u2013 populous, wealthy and Parliamentarian \u2013 could be punitively taxed, and Welsh manpower and money could be freely deployed against the King's enemies in the rest of the country. Although it was likely that Rupert would have been able to storm a city that was less well defended than Bristol, Charles was not willing to risk the casualties an assault would incur.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 54\u201355</ref> On 6 August the Parliamentarian governor of Gloucester, Lieutenant-Colonel [[Edward Massey]], refused to surrender the city, but in a secret communication he let it be known that he would do so if the King, rather than Rupert, led the army on Gloucester. Charles decided the next day that this was the best chance of securing Gloucester quickly and without bloodshed. This compromise plan pleased neither the Queen's faction, who saw it as an unnecessary diversion from the more decisive objective of London, nor Rupert, who remained in Bristol in the belief that the Royalist army was not strong enough to allow Massey to honourably surrender without a fight.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 55\u201357</ref>\n\n==Gloucester defences==\nGloucester's strength lay in its location. To the west, the River Severn formed a natural defence against an assaulting army. To the north and north-east the marshy ground was unsuitable for siege operations, and the River Twyver and a tributary stream added to the obstacles. This left the higher and drier ground to the east and south as the only feasible directions for an attack. In the preceding centuries the city had grown beyond its medieval defences, of which only the ruined [[Gloucester Castle|castle]] by the river and a stretch of wall that linked the south, east and original north fates, the last known as the inner north gate and now well within the city, still survived. From the south gate to the east gate the wall was high but not thick enough to withstand 17th-century artillery or mining operations.<ref name=Day65\u201366>Day 2007 pp. 65\u201366</ref>\n\nThe fall of Bristol prompted the hurried reinforcement of the existing defences. New earthworks and a narrow water-filled ditch completed the line of fortifications from the south gate to the Severn. Another earthwork was extended north from Whitefriars Barn on the north-east corner of the medieval wall to the outer north gate. From there the River Twyver formed a moat as the earthwork followed it north-west to Alvin Gate then on to the river's junction with the Old Severn.<ref name=Day65\u201366 /> This easternmost channel of the River Severn had dried up by the 19th century, but at the time of the civil war it was still a navigable river.<ref>Herbert 1988 para. 2</ref><ref>Rhodes 2006 p. 14</ref> The earthwork then followed the Old Severn south-west to a point a short distance north of Westgate Street, from where it was extended the other side of the Old Severn to the River Severn just above the west gate.<ref name=Day66>Day 2007 p. 66</ref> Inside the city, an earthwork was extended west from the end of the medieval wall at the inner north gate via [[Gloucester Cathedral]] to [[St Oswald's Priory, Gloucester|St Oswald's Priory]], where it met the new outer earthwork.<ref name=Day66 /> The outer north gate and Alvin Gate were fortified with earthwork [[bastion]]s,<ref name=Day66 /> a drawbridge was installed at Westgate Bridge and the Old Severn was dammed at Dockham, causing the ground to north-west of the city to flood.<ref>Rhodes 2006 pp. 17, 29\u201330</ref>\n\nThe garrison numbered no more than 1,500 troops. The bulk of these comprised two half-strength regiments each of some 600 men: the [[Henry Grey, 1st Earl of Stamford|Earl of Stamford]]'s Regiment of Foot, recruited from London and Leicestershire, and a locally recruited regiment known as the Town Regiment. The remainder comprised a company of [[Trained bands|trained band]], 100 [[dragoon]]s and a [[troop]] of cavalry. The city's dozen or so artillery pieces ranged in size from light cannon to two nine-pounder [[demi-culverin]]s. Stamford's regiment was experienced and well led, though of uncertain discipline. The Town Regiment lacked experience but was motivated by its ties to the city it was defending, although there is evidence that some of its men would refuse to oppose the King. The city could support itself with basic necessities, but it lacked sufficient gunpowder to withstand an assault or prolonged siege.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 63\u201365</ref>\n\nMassey was an autocratic military commander, but his authority in the city was shared with the civilian administration. A committee had been established in December 1642 to manage the Parliamentarian war effort in the county, but [[Thomas Pury]], the [[member of parliament]] for Gloucester, was the only committee member in the city. Civic authority was held by a forty-member council, though in practice an inner core of some fifteen [[Alderman|aldermen]], including the mayor, wielded power. As many of these were, like Pury, officers in the city's garrison, political and military command was largely integrated.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 66\u201367</ref> In the days immediately following the fall of Bristol, morale in the city, both military and civilian, was low.<ref>Day 2007 p. 68</ref> It's possible that this was what prompted Massey consider surrendering the city, though his message suggesting he would may have been a subterfuge designed to buy some time.<ref>Day 2007 p. 73</ref> There is strong evidence that the conduct and actions of the city elite, including Massey and particularly Pury, did much to stiffen the city's resolve. Officers and councillors with Royalist sympathies were given the opportunity to leave, and those who remained were required to restate an oath of allegiance to Parliament. The discipline of the troops was improved by paying them, and civilians were kept busy reinforcing the city's defences.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 69\u201370</ref>\n\n==Siege==\nAs Charles marched north from Bristol, reinforcements were converging on Gloucester from Oxford, Worcester and Herefordshire.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 86\u201387</ref> By the afternoon of 10 August the Royalist army, comprising some 6,000 infantry and 2,500 mounted troops, began assembling around the city.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 90\u201391</ref> Charles set up his headquarters at [[Matson, Gloucester|Matson]] House.<ref>Day 2007 p. 97</ref> His demand for Gloucester's surrender was unanimously and somewhat insolently rejected, and the Parliamentarians set fire to the suburbs outside the city defences to clear lines of fire and deprive the Royalists of cover.<ref>Day 2007 pp. , 91\u201393,96</ref> Charles had decided to march on Gloucester in the belief that the city would be quickly surrendered. Now that gambit had failed, he decided to besiege it. His pride had been wounded by the manner of the Parliamentarian rejection. His commanders, assessing the state of the city's defences, supplies and morale, persuaded him the city could be taken within ten days without an assault. Intelligence indicated the even if the Parliamentarians were able to send a relieving force, it could be easily defeated before it could reach the city. Most decisively, the [[William Cavendish, 1st Duke of Newcastle|Earl of Newcastle]], whose support was necessary in any campaign against London, declared himself unable to march south while Hull remained in Parliamentarian hands, leaving Charles too weak to contemplate such a move.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 93\u201395</ref>\n\nThe first shots were fired in the afternoon as Sir [[Jacob Astley, 1st Baron Astley of Reading|Jacob Astley]] established his forces near Issold's House on the eastern side of the city. [[Patrick Ruthven, 1st Earl of Forth|Lord Forth]], who had been given overall command of the siege, set up a fortified leaguer to the rear of the ruined [[Llanthony Secunda Priory]] and established his forces to the south of the city.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 95\u201396, 99, 100\u2013101</ref> By dawn on 11 August, a line of trenches had been dug some {{convert|130|yd|m}} from the walls, placing the two sides within musket range of each other, stretching from [[Brunswick Square, Gloucester|Gaudy Green]] on the south side to Issold's House on the east.<ref>Day 2007 p. 99</ref> Massey responded with spoiling tactics in an attempt to hinder Royalist siege operations and delay the assault he was expecting. At midnight a small raiding party succeeded in disrupting Royalist entrenching operations on Gaudy Green, and a larger raid on the green the next morning, 12 August, resulted in the capture of Royalist men, tools and weapons.<ref>Day 2007 p. 100</ref> By this time, the reinforcements from Herefordshire and Worcester under the command of Sir William Vavasour arrived on the west bank of the Severn and began crossing the river to take up positions at Kingsholm, to the north of the city. This force increased the size of the besieging army by another 2,400 infantry and over 300 cavalry. They too were the target of a Parliamentarian raid which inflicted up to fifteen casualties on the Royalists.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 10, 100</ref>\n\nLater on 12 August, Forth completed an earthwork square on Gaudy Green, in which he placed two 24-pounders, the largest of the Royalist's eight cannon, along with a 12-pounder to target the south wall. Another artillery emplacement was positioned to target the east wall nearby.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 10, 99\u2013102</ref> With the artillery in place, the Royalists began bombarding the walls, with the main effort beginning at 11:00 on 13 August. The cannon were too light to have any significant impact, and of the two mortars the Royalists possessed, one, reputed to be the largest in the country, exploded on its first use. When it became evident the Royalists were focusing their efforts on the south-east corner of the city defences, Massey quickly buttressed the medieval walls with up to {{convert|5|ft|m}} of earth, which ensured that the defences held. Meanwhile, the majority of Vavasour's troops completed their crossing of the Severn, leaving behind a small contingent to blockade the west bank.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 100\u2013102</ref>\n\nReacting to rumours that Vavasour had received a reinforcement of artillery, the Parliamentarians mounted another raid to the north of the city on 14 August. They captured two prisoners but failed in their primary objective of locating and spiking any guns.<ref>Day 2007 p. 102</ref> The Royalist bombardment continued through 14 August, but a breach blown in the wall by the larger guns on Gaudy Green was quickly plugged by the defenders with woolsacks and [[gabion]]s. Royalist engineers mining towards the walls from trenches at the green succeeded in draining the ditch below the walls, but this was not followed up with an assault. By the end of the day the Royalist guns had fallen silent; the evidence suggests they had run out of ammunition.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 102\u2013103</ref>\n\nThe following day Vavasour received a reinforcement of 500 [[Glamorgan]] militia and 450 musketeers from Bristol, while the Parliamentarians bolstered the earthwork defences around the south and north gates. On 16 August Rupert accompanied Charles to Oxford, and neither were at Gloucester to witness the most ambitious Parliamentarian raid yet. Just before sunset, 150 musketeers of Stamford's regiment sallied out of the north gate to attack the Royalist trenches east of the city. The Parliamentarians claimed 100 Royalist killed for the cost of 2 injured, while Royalist sources report 24 Parliamentarians killed and more wounded, for the loss of 4 Royalists killed.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 103\u2013105</ref>\n\nStruggling with a shortage of gunpowder and with the guns quiet, the Royalists concentrated on mining operations to breach the city walls. Miners recruited from the [[Forest of Dean]] were set to work under a protective gallery to fill the {{convert|12|ft|m|adj=on}} deep by {{convert|30|ft|m|adj=on}} wide moat which, when completed, would allow them to undermine the walls. It was slow work, estimated to need a week to complete. The faster alternative was to forgo the protection and fill the moat with [[fascine]]s. An attempt to do this was beaten back by musket fire from the walls, and resulted in the desertion of the miners.<ref>Day 2007 103, 106\u2013107</ref>\n\nBy 18 August Vavasour had deployed three cannon in front of his main camp at Kingsholm and another opposite Alvin Gate. These were the targets of a Parliamentarian raid that morning that was even larger than previous efforts; a diversionary attack by 50 men and a main force of 400. All four of Vavasour's cannon were disabled, the Parliamentarians claiming over 100 Royalist casualties for the loss of 6, the Royalists admitting 28 casualties and claiming to have killed 27 Parliamentarians. Another Parliamentarian raid the same day involved their only recorded use of cavalry during the siege, when 150 musketeers and 40 cavalry mounted an ineffectual attack on Royalist positions to the east of the city. Charles, meanwhile, was on his way back to Gloucester with another 1,000 reinforcements.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 106\u2013107</ref>\n\nBy the morning of 19 August, two 6-pounder cannon had been installed in a third emplacement opposite the east gate, bringing all the original artillery online. At 10:00, the bombardment was resumed in a last effort to subdue the city by the original ten-day deadline. Constrained by the limited supplies of ammunition and gunpowder, the bombardment had little material effect, though it prompted Massey to hastily erect a breastwork in the open ground of Friar's Orchard, at the south east corner of the city where the Royalist artillery was being concentrated. A Royalist attempt to cross the moat after dark was beaten back by musket fire. The objective of forcing the surrender of Gloucester by siege in ten days had failed, partly due to the city's resolve and Massey's spoiling attacks, but mainly due to the inadequacy of the Royalist artillery.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 107\u2013109</ref> \n\nThe Parliamentarians mounted another raid at dawn on 21 August. It was a two-pronged attack designed to disable the Royalist artillery south and east of the walls. One detachment travelled by boat down the Severn, landed between Forth's camp and a redoubt opposite the castle and successfuly stormed the redoubt. The second detachment of 200 musketeers sallied from the north gate. Intending first to attack the battery opposite the east gate, this force became lost and blundered into Royalist infantry camps. When Massey saw that the raid was not going to plan, he sounded the recall. The Parliamentarians suffered eight casualties, the Royalists more than twenty. Such raids were proving risky and wasteful of the garrison's limited ammunition, and this was the last large-scale operation mounted by the Parliamentarians.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 112\u2013113</ref>\n\nAs the Royalists set about replenishing their stocks of ammunition, they intensified their mining efforts. It was anticipated that the original effort to bridge the moat would allow the besiegers to reach the east wall on 24 August. A second effort to bridge the moat to the south was begun, as was a more complicated project to tunnel towards the east gate. Royalist agents attempted to persuade the garrison to surrender, and Royalist cavalry staged a mock battle in an unsuccessful attempt to lure the garrison out of the city in the belief that a relief force had arrived.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 114\u2013115</ref> A desultory bombardment was maintained, particularly by the mortars, until 25 August, when it was intensified. An attempt that day by Massey to disrupt it with a sally from the north gate was beaten back by cavalry, but as before, a shortage of ammunition \u2013 at one stage the Royalists resorted to firing stones \u2013 blunted the impact, and little damage was done to the city.<ref>Day 2007 p. 116</ref>\n\nFollowing news that the [[Robert Devereux, 3rd Earl of Essex|Earl of Essex]] was raising a Parliamentarian army in London, Charles and Rupert travelled to Oxford on 26 August, where they held a two-day council of war. With no intelligence of Essex's plans, the Royalists bolstered the defences of Oxford with troops earmarked for the siege of Gloucester while the Royalist garrison at Bristol was urged to send all the forces it could spare to Gloucester. Believing that Essex could muster no more than 6,000 troops, the decision was made to continue the siege, though contingency plans for the blockade of Gloucester were drawn up in case it had to be lifted. [[Henry Wilmot, 1st Earl of Rochester|Lord Wilmot]] was instructed to muster 2,000 cavalry around [[Banbury]]. Their task would be to delay the Parliamentarians in the [[Cotswolds]] until Rupert could come up with the rest of the Royalist cavalry in support, should Essex march to the relief of Gloucester.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 117\u2013118</ref>\n\nEssex began his march from [[Colnbrook]], west of London, on 26 August.<ref>Day 2007 p. 127</ref> His plan was to relieve Gloucester without provoking a major battle in which, with the Royalist superiority in cavalry, he would be at a disdvantage. His route was dictated by the desire to minimise the amount of open country favourable to cavalry operations he would have to pass through, and took him north of Oxford via Aylesbury and Bicester and then across the Cotswolds.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 124\u2013126</ref> At the beginning of September Essex was due north of Oxford with an army of some 10,500 infantry, no more than 4,500 mounted troops and an artillery train that is estimated at no more than 50 guns.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 130\u2013131, 133</ref>\n\nMining was now the principal tactic by which the Royalists hoped to bring the siege to a successful conclusion. Priority was given to tunnelling at the east gate, which caused progress on efforts to fill the moat below the south and east walls to slow, possibly as a result of a lack of miners and engineers. Parliamentarian countermining at the east gate on 28 August was quickly abandoned because of springs that caused flooding, which accounts for the slow pace of the Royalist efforts there.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 136\u2013138</ref> Massey continued to harass the besiegers with sniping and artillery fire, and he resumed countermining operations at the east gate after a reconnaissance party had reported Royalists miners were still working on their mine. The progress of the Royalist mines closer towards the walls, quickened by the arrival of Welsh miners on 29 August, led Massey to believe an an assault was imminent. On 1 September he fortified Friars Orchard with an earthwork wall and [[Sconce (fortification)|sconce]], a fort in which he placed four pieces of artillery that could be brought to bear on any Royalists who broke through the south-east corner or the east gate.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 138\u2013140</ref>\n\nOn 3 September the Parliamentarians placed a [[Saker (cannon)|saker]] in a gun port they had been secretly building in east wall above the gallery protecting the Royalist miners. The medium-sized cannon was employed most of the day against the gallery, to little effect, until the Royalists targeted it with a cannon of their own, at which point it was withdrawn. The Royalists anticipated their mine would reach the east gate the next day, while they believed Essex could be delayed in the Cotswolds for four days. The Bristol garrison was being stripped for reinforcements and orders had been sent to Oxford for ten field guns and the equipment necessary to make the guns already at Gloucester mobile, should it be necessary to redeploy them from siegework to use in open battle.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 140\u2013141</ref>\n\nBy the end of the day Essex's lead element, the London brigade, was at [[Oddington, Gloucestershire|Oddington]], {{convert|2|mi|km}} east of [[Stow-on-the-Wold]]. His army was largely untroubled by Wilmot's Royalist cavalry, and because of the differing rates of march it was strung out as far back as [[Chipping Norton]], nearly {{convert|6|mi|km}} to the east. Earlier the same day Rupert had led the rest of the Royalist cavalry from Gloucester, and having rendezvoused with Wilmot, now had some 5,000 men camped around [[Bourton-on-the-Water]], {{convert|4|mi|km}} south-west of Stow.<ref>Day 2007 pp. 141\u2013143, 146</ref>\n\nBy the end of the siege, Massey had only three barrels of gunpowder left for the defence of the city.\n\n==Aftermath==\nWith the arrival of the Earl of Essex, the Royalists forces withdrew and began to march on towards London. They intercepted Essex's army at the [[First Battle of Newbury]], but failed to destroy it. For the remainder of the war, Massey's force based in Gloucester continually threatened the lines of communication between Oxford, the King's wartime capital, and Wales and the West Country.\n\nFollowing the return of Charles II to the throne, the king took his revenge upon the city by having its walls torn down. The foundations of the wall, however, are still visible in parts of the city today.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist|30em}}\n\n==Commemoration==\nFor centuries afterwards, the lifting of the siege was marked by an annual [[Gloucester Day]]. This died out in the nineteenth century but was reinstated in 2009.<ref name=bbc>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/gloucestershire/8239588.stm Tradition revived for city pride.] BBC News, 5 September 2009. Retrieved 11 September 2011.</ref>\n\nThe modern ''Gloucester Day'' has recently included a parade by the [[Mock Mayor]] of [[Barton and Tredworth|Barton]], an office created after Barton was moved outside of the limits of the city following the restoration of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]].<ref>[http://www.gloucester.gov.uk/Freetime/Museums/historyweek/gloucesterday.aspx GLOUCESTER DAY 2011.] gloucester.gov.uk 2011. Retrieved 11 September 2011.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last=Day |first=Jon |title=Gloucester and Newbury 1643: The Turning Point of the Civil War |type=E-Book |publisher=Pen & Sword Military |location=Barnsley, South Yorkshire |year=2007 |isbn=978-1-84415-591-0 }}\n* {{cite web |editor-last=Herbert |editor-first=N.M. |year=1988 |title=A History of the County of Gloucester: Gloucester: Bridges, gates and walls|volume=4|pages=242\u2013245|publisher=British History Online |accessdate=8 April 2020|url=https://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/glos/vol4/pp242-245 }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Rhodes|first=John|title=The Severn Flood-Plain at Gloucester in the Medieval and Early Modern Periods|journal= Transactions of the Bristol and Gloucestershire Archaeological Society|volume=124|publisher=|year=2006|pages=9\u201336|doi=}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Whiting, J.R.S. ''Gloucester besieged: The story of a roundhead city 1640-1660.'' Gloucester: [[Gloucester City Museum & Art Gallery|City Museum & Art Gallery]], 1975. (2nd edition 1984)\n\n{{coord |51.864|-2.2438|type:event_region:GB-GLS|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Sieges of the English Civil Wars|Gloucester, Siege of]]\n[[Category:1643 in England]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1643]]\n[[Category:History of Gloucester]]\n[[Category:Military history of Gloucestershire]]\n[[Category:17th century in Gloucestershire]]\n", "name_user": "Factotem", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSiege:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siege_of_Gloucester"}
{"title_page": "The American Meme", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| director       = Bert Marcus\n| producer       = Bert Marcus, Cassandra Thornton\n| writer         = Bert Marcus\n| starring       = Paris Hilton, Josh Ostrovsky, Kirill Bichutsky, Brittany Furlan, Hailey Baldwin, DJ Khaled, Emily Ratajkowski, Matthew Felker\n| editing        = Tchavdar Georgiev, Monique Zavistovski\n| studio         = Bert Marcus Productions\n| distributor    = [[Netflix]]\n| released       = December 7, 2018\n| language       = English\n}}{{italic title}}\n'''''The American Meme''''' is a 2018 [[documentary film]] starring [[Paris Hilton]], [[Josh Ostrovsky]], Kirill Bichutsky, [[Brittany Furlan]], [[Hailey Baldwin]], [[DJ Khaled]], [[Emily Ratajkowski]], [[Dane Cook]] and [[Matthew Felker]]. It is written and directed by Bert Marcus and produced by Bert Marcus and Cassandra Thornton,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt8106160/|title=The American Meme|date=1 April 2018|publisher=|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref> and premiered at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]] on April 27, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribecafilm.com/filmguide/american-meme-2018|title=The American Meme - 2018 Tribeca Film Festival|website=Tribeca}}</ref>\n\nThe film follows four social media personalities as they work to create commercial brands out of their online presence. The film premiered to critical acclaim<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/the-american-meme-review-1202793778/|title=Film Review: \u2018The American Meme\u2019|first=Owen|last=Gleiberman|date=2 May 2018|publisher=}}</ref> and was purchased at the Tribeca Film Festival as a [[Netflix]] Original Documentary. The sale was one of the most high-profile documentary acquisitions of 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/netflix-picks-up-paris-hilton-produced-doc-american-meme-1153270|title=Netflix Picks Up Doc 'The American Meme' (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\nThe film was released on December 7, 2018 on Netflix.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-news/dj-khaled-paris-hilton-netflix-the-american-meme-trailer-766111/|title=\u2018The American Meme\u2019: DJ Khaled, Paris Hilton Ponder Social Media Fame in New Trailer|last=Reed|first=Ryan|date=2018-12-07|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-07}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]] the film has an approval rating of 94% based on 31 reviews. The site's critical consensus reads, \"The American Meme dives into the shallow end of modern celebrity, emerging with a series of fascinating -- and surprisingly deep -- observations.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_american_meme/|title=The American Meme (2018)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate=Aug 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out New York]]'' named it the number one movie to see at the 2018 Tribeca Film Festival, writing that the documentary \"finds its way to an unexpected sadness and maybe something deeper and cautionary.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/film/best-movies-at-tribeca-film-festival-2018|title=The 10 best movies at Tribeca Film Festival 2018|website=Time Out New York|language=en|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref>\n\n[[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', hailed it as \"highly entertaining and an essential snapshot of the narcotic voyeuristic parasitic American fishbowl,\" following its premiere at the 2018 Tribeca Film Festival. He went on to say, \"Bert Marcus, the director of 'The American Meme,' works in a kaleidoscopic style that channels the glitzy, fragmented screen-shot spirit of his subjects. At the same time, he gets us close to them, so that we can see the kind of people they are: shrewdly likable and kind of ordinary. Their lives consist of feeding a beast that pumps their fame and drains their souls.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/the-american-meme-review-1202793778/|title=Film Review: \u2018The American Meme\u2019|last=Gleiberman|first=Owen|date=2018-05-02|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2018-12-07}}</ref> Internet film critic, S. James Wegg writes, \"[Bert] Marcus set himself the task of profiling some of the world\u2019s most 'followed' social media superstars, letting their work and their own voices make his points about the business of making a living doing outrageous things and sharing those with their seemingly insatiable admirers and online 'family.'\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jamesweggreview.org/Articles.aspx?ID=2152|title=JWR Articles: Film/DVD - The American Meme (Director/Writer: Bert Marcus) - December 4, 2018|website=www.jamesweggreview.org|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\n[[Paris Hilton]], one the film's central characters, has been praised for showing her vulnerability and giving audiences a glimpse into the dark side of fame. [[Decider (website)|Decider]] reports, \"In a series of quiet, reflective interviews, Hilton explains why she trusts her fans more than her friends and dissects the risqu\u00e9 [[David LaChapelle|David LaChappelle]] photoshoot that transformed her into a household name.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://decider.com/2018/12/07/the-american-meme-paris-hilton/|title=Paris Hilton Tears Up About Sex Tape: 'It Was Like Being Raped. It Felt Like I\u2019ve Lost Part of My Soul'|date=2018-12-07|website=Decider|language=en|access-date=2018-12-07}}</ref> Furthermore, ''[[USA Today]]'' shares \"5 ways Netflix's 'The American Meme' will change the way you think about Paris Hilton,\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2018/12/07/american-meme-changes-your-impression-paris-hilton/2190399002/|title=5 ways Netflix's 'The American Meme' will change the way you think about Paris Hilton|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2018-12-07}}</ref> including the closeness she has with her fans and her genuine self-awareness about the reality of internet stardom and notoriety.\n\nIn a review of the film in ''[[The New Yorker]]'', Naomi Fry writes, \"But what is fascinating, and valuable, about 'The American Meme' is its ability to reveal the desperation, loneliness, and sheer Sisyphean tedium of ceaselessly chasing what will most likely end up being an ever-diminishing share of the online-attention economy.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/the-american-meme-a-new-netflix-documentary-records-the-angst-of-social-media-influencers|title='The American Meme,' a New Netflix Documentary, Records the Angst of Social-Media Influencers|last=Fry|first=Naomi|date=December 7, 2018|website=The New Yorker}}</ref> [[Bust (magazine)|Bust]] reports, \"'The American Meme' unpacks and reveals the ecosystem of social media celebrity with incredible thoughtfulness....this movie is no hand-wringing thinkpiece from a legacy publication about how the Young People and their Insta-whatevers are ruining society, written with an insufferably lofty tone by an outsider. What Marcus does, radically enough, is treat the social media personalities he interviews for this film as real people, rather than subjects in a study or avatars of moral degradation.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bust.com/movies/195479-american-meme-review.html|title=\"The American Meme\" Is Most Disturbing Movie Of The Year|website=bust.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-12-13}}</ref>\n\nThe film has been hailed by ''[[The Irish Times]]'' as \"a fascinating look into the curious appeal and lives of social media superstars and reality celebrities.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/tv-radio-web/netflix-the-10-best-new-films-and-shows-in-december-1.3715256|title=Netflix: the 10 best new films and shows in December|work=The Irish Times|access-date=2018-11-30|language=en-US}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mattsmoviereviews.net/|title=Matt\u2019s Movie Reviews - Movie Reviews & Opinion by Film Critic Matthew Pejkovic|website=mattsmoviereviews.net|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\"The American Meme takes a deep dive into fame during the social media age, delivering a surprisingly insightful and even illuminating look at the influencers who entertain the online masses,\" adds [[MattsMoviereview.net|Matts Movie Reviews]], \"Marus' gaze has never been as relevant, nor his storytelling as entertaining.\"  [[Themarysue.com]] says, '\" I highly recommend The American Meme....it is going to change the way you view both social media and society.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themarysue.com/|title=The American Meme|last=|first=|date=|website=www.themarysue.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmracket.com/|title=Film Racket Movie Reviews \u00bb|website=Film Racket Movie Reviews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> [[Film Racket]] declares, \" Documentaries have been made about celebrities before, even about celebrities that are famous for no reason whatsoever.  But serial documentarian Bert Marcus, with The American Meme, does more that just profile celebrities that include Brittany Furlan, DJ Khalid and Josh Ostrovsky (The Fat Jewish.) He asks why? Or more to the point, he asks How?\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Reviews ==\n*[https://www.filminquiry.com/american-meme-2018-review-2/ THE AMERICAN MEME: Stretching The Fifteen Minutes Of Fame]\n*[https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_american_meme/]{{IMDb title|id=tt8106160}}\n*[https://www.netflix.com/title/81003741 The American Meme on Netflix]\n*[https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/the-american-meme-review-1202793778/ Film Review: \u2018The American Meme\u2019]\n*[https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/the-american-meme-a-new-netflix-documentary-records-the-angst-of-social-media-influencers \"The American Meme,\" a New Netflix Documentary, Records the Angst of Social-Media Influencers]\n*[https://www.timeout.com